<HEADLINE>
KONERKO NEEDED THAT HOME RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Paul Konerko waited nine weeks for his coming out
party. When it finally happened Saturday afternoon, he didn't seem
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko didn't smile as he rounded the bases after crushing a
Bob Wells' fastball for a 431-foot home run in the sixth inning
that turned out to be the game-winner in a 10-6 Dodgers victory
over the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter that it was his first major-league homer. The
fact that it took 72 at-bats to get was more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never felt like I was a rookie here, just a guy with
responsibilities just like everyone else,'' said Konerko, last
year's Minor League Player of the Year. ``That's the way I've seen
my time here. It was important that I produce. I feel I've been
letting them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Konerko was 0 for 8 since his recall from Triple-A Albuquerque
when he singled home two runs in the third inning off Mariners
starter Jeff Fassero. He made the team out of spring training and
started at first when Eric Karros opened the season on the disabled
list. But he batted just .197 (12 for 61) without an extra base
hit. His four RBI Saturday were two more than he had all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this has been tough for him,'' manager Bill Russell
said. ``But no one ever doubted his talent. He is an excellent
hitter. He just needed an opportunity and some time to show it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lineup bump: Konerko started a first with Karros as the
designated hitter. Juan Castro played third in place of Bobby
Bonilla, who was sent home with flu, sore throat and a .204 batting
average since joining the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told him to go back about 2{ hours before the game,''
trainer Charlie Strasser said. ``He really isn't in very good
shape.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Mlicki struggled:!off! Dave Mlicki's Dodgers debut was
rocky. He allowed eight hits and five earned runs in just three
innings. Although he reportedly had the best arm in the New York
Mets organization, Mlicki seemed intent on trying to beat the
Mariners with breaking pitches and off speed stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is a little confused with what he should do,'' said
pitching coach Goose Gregson. ``I'm not so sure he knew what
direction to take over there. I've only seen him once but I saw
some pitches I liked.''
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki is the Dodgers fifth starter, the same role he had in New
York. But the Mets suffered 10 rainouts early this year and he was
bumped around in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't very good, but I feel confident everything will
fall into place,'' said Mlicki, whose ERA jumped to 6.15.
</P>
<P>
   Quick Hits: Antonio Osuna took over for Jim Bruske to begin the
eighth and pitched two scoreless innings to earn his second save.
In the ninth, Osuna, the closer on Opening Day, struck out Alex
Rodriguez and got Ken Griffey Jr. to line to first. Those players
are 1-2 in the American League in homers, led by Griffey's 23....
Eric Young went 3 for 5 with three runs and two stolen bases,
raising his NL lead to 26.... When Raul Mondesi threw out Edgar
Martinez at the plate to end the seventh, it was the 60th assist of
his career.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
