<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7908 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HERSKOWITZ-HNS &LR;      06-07 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: Belmont provides remarkable drama
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ A picture might be worth a thousand words, but a
photo finish is worth $5 million, depending on your camera angle.
</P>
<P>
   In as epic a stretch run as the Belmont Stakes has seen, Victory
Gallop and Real Quiet went nose-to-nose and stride-for-stride
Saturday. Students of horseflesh were rewarded with a race for the
ages, if not the wonder colt who was expected to join a legendary
list.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be much consolation for Real Quiet, and his
connections, who were denied the Triple Crown, the megabucks bonus,
and the thrill of proving his critics wrong. But in losing to
Victory Gallop by a nostril, Real Quiet might have won the respect
that had been withheld after his wins in the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Triple Crown roll call holds at 11, and another year
has passed without a champion to join Affirmed, the last in 1978.
But it wasn't the curse of Belmont that beat the underrated son of
Quiet American. Victory Gallop did it with a closing charge that
electrified a near-record crowd of 80,162.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind Secretariat or Citation or War Admiral. The last time
anyone had seen ground closed that fast, it was Silver or Trigger
or Champion trying to catch a train or a stagecoach.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those at the track and watching on TV had conceded the
race to Real Quiet, and were preparing to measure the skinny bay
colt for his new credentials. It would be hard to imagine a wilder
or more controversial ending than the one this race almost
produced. It could have been decided on a disqualification _ if
Real Quiet had hit the finish line first.
</P>
<P>
   Disqualification loomed
</P>
<P>
   The astonishing fact is no one knew, at that moment, who had
won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' said Bob Baffert, the witty trainer with the
hair by Clorox. ``I thought we might have won on a head bob. I
asked Wayne Lukas in front of me and he said, `You got it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But he hadn't, although there was an unbearable wait as the tote
board flashed the signal for a steward's inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stevens, who deprived Baffert of his Triple Crown on
Saturday and lost it for him on Silver Charm a year ago, had filed
a complaint that turned out to be unneeded. When Victory Gallop
roared from seven lengths back in the final eighth of a mile, the
two colts were so close, the distance so short, it wasn't possible
to see that Real Quiet veered to his right and bumped his rival
twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told one of the outriders to hold the race,'' Stevens said,
``that my horse had been fouled. He came back and said it didn't
matter, we had you winning, and congratulations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they didn't have to take the horse down,'' Baffert
said. ``That would have been the worst possible finish.''
</P>
<P>
   To quote that famed turf writer, Bill Shakespeare _ pardon us
for name-dropping _ ``It would be argument for a week, laughter for
a month and a good jest forever.'' (Henry IV, Act II.)
</P>
<P>
   But with Real Quiet going for all the worldly goods, and a long
shot named Thomas Jo sneaking through the field to take third,
there was serious theater.
</P>
<P>
   This day this Long Island hamlet was clearly a two-horse town,
with a broken heart for every light on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   There was Kent Desormeaux, Real Quiet's excitable jockey, who
kept beating himself up because he made his move exactly where he
had at Churchill Downs and Pimlico. This time the track was a
quarter-mile longer.
</P>
<P>
   But Baffert defended his rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will say he went too early,'' Baffert said. ``He didn't
go too early. That's the horse's style. The Fish (his nickname for
the colt with the narrow chest) floundered. He was tired. He ran
his heart out. I thought Kent ran a great race. And Gary Stevens
ran a great race.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbridled emotions
</P>
<P>
   If ever a jockey had been there and done that, and knew the
whirlpool of emotions, it was Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Kent in the paddock,'' he said, ``and I know exactly
what he is feeling right now. He feels like he let the whole nation
down. But he didn't. Last year I was devastated. Silver Charm
didn't see that horse, didn't see Touch Gold.''
</P>
<P>
   As a footnote to the day's drama, Houston is once again the
capital of horse racing upsets. Last year's Belmont winner, Touch
Gold, is owned in part by Bob McNair, who is heading the city's
effort to acquire a pro football franchise. Victory Gallop, of
course, is owned by the Jack, Art and J. R. Preston, of The
Woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear the Prestons were as thrilled, and speechless, as
Baffert was disheartened and, well, not so speechless. Two years in
a row, he has missed a Triple Crown on the last leg, this time in a
finish that ties the two closest in Belmont history. Victory Gallop
joins Granville in 1936 and Jaipur in 1962 in winning by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't possible to win a race by less of a margin because
horses have longer noses than eyelashes. On that cosmetic note, let
the second-guessing begin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
