<HEADLINE>
DESORMEAUX IN FAMILIAR POSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ When you've been the goat as often as Kent
Desormeaux, you learn just how to wear the horns.
</P>
<P>
   So Desormeaux placed them on himself Saturday _ before anybody
else could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to do it again,'' the jockey said of the Belmont
Stakes, which he and Real Quiet lost by a margin so narrow that any
little mistake might have made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you saying it's your fault?'' somebody asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhat, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux is 28, the most decorated young rider in the nation,
yet he has been in positions like this so many times already, they
are in danger of defining his career.
</P>
<P>
   There was the day in Japan, in 1993, when he misjudged the
finish line in a multi-million-dollar race and Kotashaan finished
second. It wasn't clear the horse would have won without the
blunder. Still, given that Desormeaux was already under fire at
home in California for easing up on beaten horses and costing
bettors exacta and trifecta payoffs, the Kotashaan incident seemed
to fit the image of a brilliant but mistake-prone athlete.
</P>
<P>
   There was the day at Santa Anita Park, in 1994, when Desormeaux
and The Wicked North entered the stretch with the lead in the Santa
Anita Handicap but they tipped slightly toward the rail and
bothered another horse and were disqualified. The stewards'
decision was controversial in its own right, and nobody could say
for sure that Desormeaux's steering was a factor, but by then the
fans loved to hate him and everybody piled on.
</P>
<P>
   And now there is the day at Belmont Park when Desormeaux and
Real Quiet rushed into contention with half of the 1{-mile race
left to run, when they opened a four-length lead in the stretch
instead of conserving energy, when they zig-zagged through the
final yards and risked the stewards' wrath.
</P>
<P>
   In the three weeks since a dazzling victory in the Preakness
Stakes put Real Quiet on the verge of the first Triple Crown since
1978, Desormeaux must have thought about the possibility he would
lose and you-know-who would get the blame. He had admitted that as
the Belmont approached, he had trouble sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knew the feeling better than Gary Stevens, the jockey who
lost the Belmont and the Triple Crown aboard Silver Charm a year
ago and the jockey who outrode Desormeaux Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go out of the jocks' room and go out to ride with the
weight of the world on you, there's so much pressure on you, you
don't even realize how much until afterwards,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens told reporters that Desormeaux ``has nothing to be
ashamed of.... He did, obviously, what he thought was right at the
time. That's what we get paid for. I think if he is knocked for his
ride, if I was in his position, I wouldn't pay attention to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier, Desormeaux had been consoled by Chris McCarron,
who was criticized for his ride when Alysheba lost the Belmont and
the Triple Crown in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux heard McCarron tell him: ``You're going to feel
horrible for the next week and a half. But it absolutely is just
another horse race. There's one (a Triple Crown) with your name on
it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet trainer Bob Baffert was careful not to criticize
Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy had a lot of pressure on him,'' Baffert said. ``Maybe
he moved (from sixth to third to first with a quarter-mile left)
because the horse wanted to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Desormeaux said, when he made the first surge on the
backstretch, Real Quiet was ``just cantering'' _ it was the horse
who wanted to go. They made their move at the same point on the
track as they did at Churchill Downs and Pimlico. The difference is
that on those one-mile ovals, that point is half a mile from the
finish, while on this 1{-mile strip, it's three-quarters of a mile
from the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Turning into the stretch, perched on the outside of Chilito and
Grand Slam, that's when Desormeaux thought he pushed the
accelerator too hard.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with Real Quiet running on fumes and Victory Gallop
gaining, that's when Desormeaux feared he yanked too hard on the
right rein, turning his colt's head to make sure he saw the
challenger coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled his head out a little too hard,'' said Desormeaux,
whose share of the $5 million Triple Crown bonus might have been
close to $500,000. Had Real Quiet won, he would have been
disqualified for impeding Victory Gallop, or so the Belmont
stewards say now that the point is moot.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Real Quiet had nothing left but his rider's
ingenuity, and who could blame Desormeaux if, perhaps, he intended
to intimidate Victory Gallop a bit. That's race-riding.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't a terrible ride. But this wasn't Desormeaux's best
either. And because of that he knows, after losing by a nose, it's
on his head. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
