<SLUG> BC-AZ-BASEBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S MAGIC IMPROVED LIFE IN ARIZONA'S MINING TOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The townspeople eagerly awaited the first home game of the
baseball season. The newspaper carried stories that heralded the
dawn of a new season, told readers about the magic of baseball and
how it improved the quality of life in a town that desperately
wanted to feel good about itself.
</P>
<P>
   The community's leaders, concerned about the sheer size of the
expected crowd on opening day, cautioned people to use the free bus
transportation to the ballpark. The team's manager and players,
meanwhile, were hoping to prove themselves worthy of the hype.
</P>
<P>
   This was Jerome in 1924. Before signage, revenue streams and
luxury suites became part of the game's language. Back when people
drank water from the same ladle dipped from the same bucket, not
from sealed plastic containers that cost $4.75. Back when smallpox
and a plunge in copper prices could make a tough town cower.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's baseball history stretches back to the last century,
and the game was as crucial to fans then as it is today to the
approximately 3.5 million people expected to attend Diamondbacks
games this season in Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty important thing, when you think about the
dynamics of a (mining camp),'' said Lynn Bevill of Tucson, a
baseball historian. ``It was a channeling of the aggressiveness and
the anger.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport was popular throughout the state, from Flagstaff to
Douglas, from Kingman to Winslow.
</P>
<P>
   In 1883, just three years after Doc Holliday and Wyatt Earp left
Tombstone, a baseball game was a highlight of the town's Fourth of
July celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's 25th Infantry, a Black regiment, was stationed near
Nogales in 1919 and fielded one of the finest teams ever in
Arizona. Seven soldiers from that club later joined the Kansas City
Monarchs, one of the most dominating teams in the early years of
the Negro Leagues. &QL; 
INTENSE RIVALRIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1900s, baseball was being played in all parts of
the state. But nowhere was the sport taken more seriously than in
the state's mining camps, where games sometimes were as raucous as
the camps.
</P>
<P>
   As the sport grew, ballparks were built and rivalries
intensified. And opening day was as eagerly anticipated as it is
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need everything we can in the way of clean sports and
amusements in the district,'' Jerome's ``Copper Verde News''
editorialized in the spring of 1925, ``and one might spend a couple
of hours on a Sunday afternoon in many ways less healthful and less
beneficial generally than watching a good ballgame _ and giving his
lungs some needed exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   These remote outposts also attracted players no longer welcome
in organized baseball. Hal Chase, who led the National League in
hitting in 1916, played in Arizona after leaving the major leagues
amid gambling scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the infamous Chicago Black Sox, Charles ``Chick''
Gandil and George ``Buck'' Weaver, played in Douglas with Chase
after they were banned from the big leagues over allegations they
conspired to throw the 1919 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In most mining towns, the company promoted the sport to provide
recreation for the miners and their families. Baseball proponents
today argue that a major league team enriches a city's quality of
life. That, too, was the mine owners' goal.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted workers to put down roots, and they figured baseball
and other sports added to a sense of community. So they organized
teams and built ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   In Bisbee, the Calumet &AMP; Arizona Mining Co. created a
subsidiary, ``The Warren Co.,'' to develop the suburb of Warren as
a company town. Officials decided a ballpark was in order, and at a
cost of $5,000, the Warren Ballpark was built in 1909.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the oldest ballpark in the country still being used
for its intended purpose _ playing baseball _ according to David
Skinner, a baseball historian who lives in Bisbee. Rickwood Field
in Birmingham, Ala., built in 1910, is regarded as the oldest such
facility in the country, but Warren Ballpark opened a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In its early years, the ballpark was home to teams playing in
``outlaw leagues,'' those outside the structure of major league
baseball. From 1928 to 1955, it was home to several minor league
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Ballpark looks nearly the same as it did in the early
1900s, and it's still used by Bisbee High, youth leagues and a
semi-pro team that recently started playing.
</P>
<P>
   The mine company's reason for building the field was not
altogether altruistic. The ballpark was at the end of the trolley
line, and the company wanted to attract people from Bisbee.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ballpark was built, it was a source of civic pride,''
Skinner said. ``The mining company worked hard to bring in
professional players from outside the area.'' &QL; 
INFAMOUS MOMENT &QL; 
Although baseball has been played at the field for nearly 90 years,
the most famous moment in the Warren Ballpark's history had nothing
to do with the game.
</P>
<P>
   In 1917, there was a miners' strike by the Industrial Workers of
the World, or ``Wobblies.'' On the morning of July 12, using the
cover of darkness, a posse led by the local sheriff rousted nearly
2,000 people out of their beds and marched them to the ballpark,
where they were held under armed guard.
</P>
<P>
   Any miner who vowed to return to work was excused, and the
remaining 1,200 were loaded into cattle cars that were parked on
the tracks beyond the outfield fence. The miners were taken to the
desert of New Mexico, freed but not allowed to return to Bisbee.
</P>
<P>
   As baseball grew in importance, the town rivalries became
heated, with none more intense than the one between Jerome and
Clarkdale.
</P>
<P>
   Jerome is about five miles up Mingus Mountain from Clarkdale,
and the teams from the two towns often played Sunday doubleheaders,
with a game in each city. The United Verde Copper Co. sponsored
baseball teams in each town, and the communities took the games
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The towns of the district are isolated and of necessity the
people are deprived of much of the entertainment that is available
in the largest cities,'' the ``Verde Copper News'' editorialized in
1924. ``This makes it all the more incumbent on us to make the most
of what we have and to give every recreational opportunity our
hearty support.'' &QL; 
KEG EXACTS A TOLL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, the men of Jerome would hitch up wagons and
drive to Clarkdale, where a field was built on the west bank of the
Verde River.
</P>
<P>
   According to ``They Came to Jerome,'' a book about the town's
history, a keg of beer was placed behind home plate, and a team
could imbibe only at the end of innings in which it had scored. If
a team was held scoreless, their opponents' quenched their thirsts.
</P>
<P>
   Games were usually high-scoring affairs, with most of the runs
coming in the later innings, when the beer had exacted its toll.
</P>
<P>
   When the company built a new field in Clarkdale, the people of
Jerome demanded one, too. A spot on a ridge above the mines was
bulldozed and a grandstand was built. Admission was 50 cents, and
some fans traveled to the game on a bus that picked them up near a
downtown hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Most games were played on Sunday afternoons, and they were
sometimes wild affairs. Gambling was prevalent, as were fights
among fans. And it was not only the men who argued. Women resorted
to ``hat snatching, hair pulling and name calling,'' according to
``They Came to Jerome''. &QL; 
BICKERING OVER UMPS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The local paper editorialized against the lack of civility, but
it also contributed, constantly questioning the integrity of the
umpires when the home team lost. In game stories chronicling
victories, the umpiring was usually praised.
</P>
<P>
   ``As nearly perfect as it is possible for umpiring to be,'' the
``Copper Verde'' ``News'' wrote after a 6-4 victory by Jerome.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the two towns bickered over other issues. At
various times, each team was accused of importing illegal players
for important games.
</P>
<P>
   The 1924 season was a particularly contentious one for Jerome
and Clarkdale. Jerome was just emerging from a smallpox outbreak
that claimed 11 lives, and opening day was eagerly awaited.
</P>
<P>
   Clarkdale opened the year by winning three straight against its
rival, and there was great concern in Jerome. Somehow, Jerome
enticed the great Hal Chase to jump from the Williams team to play
for Jerome.
</P>
<P>
   Chase was one of the greatest characters in baseball history.
While with Cincinnati, he led the National League in hitting in
1916. But he fell into disfavor in the seasons after. His manager,
Christy Mathewson, accused Chase of laziness and betting against
his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Chase was cleared of the charges but when the Black Sox scandal
came to light a year later, Chase's named was associated with it
and he was no longer welcome in big league baseball.
</P>
<P>
   So he played in outlaw leagues, those not under the umbrella of
organized baseball. There was no better place for a man like Chase
to play than in Arizona's mining communities and border towns,
considered smack in the middle of nowhere. Beginning in 1923, Chase
played or managed teams in Nogales, Williams, Jerome and Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Chase was a notorious drinker, womanizer and gambler, but he was
popular in almost every town in which he played.
</P>
<P>
   With Chase playing first and managing, Jerome's team improved
greatly. It tied Clarkdale for the league lead and later beat its
rival for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Chase didn't last long around those parts. He was soon fired
after being accused of stealing supplies through his job at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1920s, the mining company decided the rivalry had
grown out of control, and chose to sponsor only one combined team
from Jerome and Clarkdale. Players who didn't want to work at a
real job moved on. &QL; 
POPULAR ALONG BORDER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rivalries in southern Arizona were just as heated. Baseball was
popular in Bisbee, Nogales and Douglas and also across the border
in Mexican towns such as Nogales, Naco and Cananea.
</P>
<P>
   In 1921, a game between the Douglas White Sox and the Nogales
Cuervos ended in a riot, according to a 1984 story in ``Sports
Illustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   After a controversial call, several Douglas fans came on to the
field and chased the umpire toward center field. Nogales fans
intervened, which brought armed ``federales'' onto the field. They
were engulfed by the crowd, and shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   One person was killed and dozens of others were injured. The
field was eventually cleared, and despite the bloodstains near the
mound, play resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas won and its players and fans were eager to return home.
But they ran into a roadblock on the outskirts of town and asked,
at gunpoint, if they were interested in a rematch the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox agreed, and wisely lost the rematch, 15-8. They
were happy to go home with a split _ and their health.
</P>
<P>
   While the sport had its extremes, most games in those days were
civil, as they are today.
</P>
<P>
   And just as youngsters do today, some players hoped to draw a
scout's attention and one day make it to the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dreamed,'' Bevill said. ``No matter how unrealistic it
was, they dreamed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 0032EDT &QL; 
