<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUEVALUE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOAT SCORES VICTORY WITHOUT A FIGHT IN TRUE VALUE 500K
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ One year later and minus the fisticuffs,
Billy Boat found victory _ and vindication _ at Texas Motor
Speedway last night.
</P>
<P>
   Denied the first victory of his Pep Boys Indy Racing League
career last June by a scoring snafu, Boat took no chances during
the second annual True Value 500K. Lapping as high as 227.273 mph,
Boat raced record-setting pole sitter Tony Stewart into the
pavement with a blown engine, and outmuscled Plano's Greg Ray to
give himself and car owner A.J. Foyt a second visit to TMS' victory
lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came back and really wanted to win this one bad,'' said
Boat, who exited victory lane last year as the winner but woke up
the next morning to learn that Arie Luyendyk had been declared the
champion after an all-night scoring audit by the U.S. Auto Club.
``I wasn't going to let that happen tonight. We rolled off the
trailer fast and with a good setup. I had a race car that never
gave up all night long. I was flat out most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat's big moment last year also was marred when Foyt, angered
that Luyendyk had invaded his team's celebration, slapped the
Dutchman in the face and knocked him to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt has spent the past year apologizing for that Saturday night
short-track indiscretion.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I felt we won it last year and I hope nobody hollers this
year,'' said Foyt, brought Boat to TMS last year as a replacement
driver for the injured Scott Sharp. ``I've been there before. Been
there happy and been there sad. I think it's official, but you
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's exit on lap 176 with a blown engine _ the same
circumstance that knocked him out of the Indy 500 last month _ set
up a three-car sprint to the finish among Boat, Ray and Kenny
Brack, Boat's teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Ray drove up under Boat's rear wing entering Turn 1 of the
revamped 1.5-mile trioval on lap 200 of the scheduled 208 and swept
into the lead down the backstretch with the help of backmarker Buzz
Calkins' car on lap 201. But Boat regained the point a lap later
with a pass on Ray exiting Turn 4. On lap 203, Ray moved high and
low, messing with Boat's head at 224.785 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But Boat's car was hauling through the preferred low line,
allowing him to pull to a lead of 0.433 seconds on lap 206. Boat
took the white flag on lap 207 and ripped off a circuit at 224.318
mph, compared to Ray's 222.616. At the checkered flag, that
translated into a margin of victory of 0.928 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy was faster on the top end,'' said Ray, who took
consolation with his best IRL finish. ``We had a better handling
car, but I didn't have enough gear. Boat was running a bigger gear.
But this is like a victory for us. I can't say enough about this
small team, Thomas Knapp Motorsports. This is very exciting for us.
This is second place, but if you can't win the Indianapolis 500,
this is the next best thing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat, driver of the No. 11 Conseco Dallara/Aurora, started
second in the two-car front row after qualifying at 223.547 mph.
But he was knocked off the pole by Stewart, who turned a track
record lap at 224.448 mph in the No. 1 Glidden-Menards
Dallara/Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart led 57 laps before the engine quit, same as it did in
the waning laps a year ago. Until that point, Stewart and Boat
settled into a one-on-one reminiscent of their dirt-track days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like old times at Ventura (Calif.),'' said
Stewart, the reigning IRL champion. ``We had an overheating
problem. We were good the whole race, just cruising in sixth gear.
There wasn't any urgency to lead the race, but the car was so good
we were just there the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who finished 33rd and last at Indy last month, was
credited with a 14th-place finish here. But he also racked up the
race's fastest lap _ 228.012 mph on lap 86. Boat's fastest lap was
227.273 mph, which also was the fastest lead-lap (142).
</P>
<P>
   Boat's previous best finish this season was third in the
Dura-Lube 200 at Phoenix International Raceway. He led 81 of the
208 laps here, and averaged 145.388 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Boat and Ray were followed across the line by Brack, Scott
Goodyear and Scott Sharp _ the last car on the lead lap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
