<HEADER>
A7924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-HNS &LR;      06-07 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Nose's difference keeps Real Quiet from taking Triple Crown
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ELMONT, N.Y. _ There's no Triple Crown this year, but Houston has a
champion, albeit one with Canadian breeding, in Victory Gallop,
winner of Saturday's 130th Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The long-running colt by Cryptoclearance finally had enough of
second place, having finished behind Real Quiet in the Kentucky
Derby and the Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet, who is nicknamed ``The Fish'' because of his narrow
front end, put up a gallant attempt to be racing's first Triple
Crown winner since Affirmed 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But he was nosed out at the wire by Victory Gallop, who is owned
by Jack, Art and J.R. Preston, who live in The Woodlands and
operate an oil company there.
</P>
<P>
   Many people, including a majority of the crowd of 80,162 _
second largest ever at Belmont Park _ thought Real Quiet would be
another Affirmed and Victory Gallop another Alydar, who managed a
second-place sweep in the 1978 Triple Crown races.
</P>
<P>
   But Victory Gallop acted more like Easy Goer, who was second to
Sunday Silence in the '89 Derby and Preakness but won the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stevens, who finished 2\ lengths behind Kent Desormeaux and
Real Quiet in the Preakness, sensed a new attitude in his horse
during the post parade on a sunny afternoon on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like a different horse today,'' Stevens said. ``He
grabbed hold of the bridle like he was really eager to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the race was so close it took a photo to determine the
winner, Victory Gallop, the second favorite at 9-2 odds, was the
superior horse in the 1{-mile Test of Champions.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet had the advantage of post position _ eighth as
opposed to Victory Gallop's 11th. And the sluggish pace (the
half-mile of 48.6 seconds was the third-slowest Belmont in the past
10 years) worked to the detriment of the come-from-Pluto style of
Victory Gallop.
</P>
<P>
   It was no easy trip for Stevens, who finished second on Silver
Charm in last year's Belmont. Victory Gallop was bumped by Yarrow
Brae at the start and was 10th _ eight lengths behind _ at the
half-mile marker, when Real Quiet began his move.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the leader was Chilito, who is owned by
Houston/Washington, D.C., attorney Joe Albritton.
</P>
<P>
   Chilito's jockey, Robbie Davis, said, ``I thought we had it when
we started opening up around the far turn. Then I saw Real Quiet
draw alongside of us and pull away. I thought there was going to be
a Triple Crown winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I saw Victory Gallop pass us with his ears pricked. When
I saw that, I said to myself, `Oh, man.' He made such a powerful
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet took the lead with a quarter-mile to go. Desormeaux
said he had ``a perfect spot early, running between horses. There
was no sand in his face. He was in a canter. He was breezing to the
front.''
</P>
<P>
   But with one furlong left, Desormeaux knew he ``was in trouble.
The momentum was changing; he was starting to slow down. I do think
I was a bit premature with my move.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop's trainer, Elliott Walden, said, ``We wanted Real
Quiet to make his move, expend the energy and see if we could pick
up the pieces late. And that's how it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   With a mighty surge through the middle of the track, Victory
Gallop reeled in The Fish. But as he tried to pass, a tiring Real
Quiet lunged out, bumping Victory Gallop and upsetting his stride.
</P>
<P>
   And three lengths from the finish, Real Quiet stepped out of
line again, body-blocking his rival and prompting an objection from
Stevens, who didn't know for sure if his closing act was enough to
nip the 4-5 favorite at the wire.
</P>
<P>
   It really didn't matter whose nose was in front, because Real
Quiet's foul was so flagrant that the stewards said they would have
disqualified him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he'd feel about taking down a Triple Crown, John Joyce
of the New York State Racing and Wagering Board said, ``The
judgment can't be interpreted because of the Triple Crown. The
facts speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet's trainer, the not-too-quiet Bob Baffert, had
``guaranteed'' a win but offered no excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fish floundered,'' he said. ``He flattened out in the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden was not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bred for distance,'' he said. ``They're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Real Quiet's sire, Quiet American, was a fine miler but
not a long-distance runner. But Cryptoclearance, who stands at the
Tall Oaks Farm in Canada, was second to Bet Twice in the '87
Belmont. His son did him one better.
</P>
<P>
   The Prestons bought Victory Gallop last November with pedigree
in mind. Although they own one of the nation's top-ranked sprinters
in Distorted Humor, they are more involved in breeding than racing.
They own about 50 broodmares and six stallions.
</P>
<P>
   Art Preston, 58, said, ``This brings a lot of visibility to our
breeding operation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Prestons sell all their yearlings and race only horses that
already have established their ability to run.
</P>
<P>
   Victory Gallop was originally sold as a yearling for $25,000,
but Prestonwood Farms bought him last November after other owners
refused to meet the asking price of $500,000. The colt had an
enlarged sesamoid bone in his ankle, and some horsemen thought he
would soon break down.
</P>
<P>
   But the Prestons had the colt inspected by veterinarians and
determined the condition was not career-threatening. They believed
Victory Gallop, a late foal (born May 30, 1995), would steadily
improve, and they've been proved right, as Saturday's $600,000
payoff would attest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, we win in a photo,'' Art Preston said. ``How exciting
can it get?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Real Quiet's bid for immortality, Preston got the last
word.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a fine horse,'' he said, ``but he's not a Triple Crown
champion, or he wouldn't have let us beat him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
