<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRUE </SLUG>
 VALUE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Boat's True Value victory indisputable
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
FORT WORTH _ A.J. Foyt didn't have to fight off anyone in Victory
Circle this time.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat, who drives the Conseco Dallara/Aurora for Foyt's
team, left no doubt about who the winner was in the True Value 500
on Saturday night at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd of 105,000 on its feet, Boat outdueled Plano's
Greg Ray in the final laps to win the race one year after victory
was taken away from Boat in a bizarre scoring snafu.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is vindication for us,'' Boat said after earning his
first victory in the Pep Boys Indy Racing League. ``We really
wanted to win worse than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left here a winner last year, and I woke up the next morning
in second place. I wasn't going to let that happen this year. We
never gave up all night long. I had a great race car, and I ran it
to death.''
</P>
<P>
   After the race, Foyt was all smiles as he hugged Boat, who won
$130,250 for the victory. It was much different from one year ago
when Foyt slapped Arie Luyendyk to the ground as Luyendyk walked
into Victory Circle and screamed he was the real winner. Luyendyk
was declared the winner the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we won it last year,'' said Foyt, the Houston racing
legend who won the Indianapolis 500 four times. ``All I can say is
Billy drove a hell of a race in this one. Today was our day.''
</P>
<P>
   Foyt also was proud of his other driver _ Kenny Brack _ who
finished third in the No. 14 Power Team car. Boat, Ray and Brack
finished Saturday's race the way they started on the front row at
Indianapolis two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Boat and Ray who went wheel-to-wheel in the last 10
laps of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who drives the AT&AMP;T Wireless Dallara/Aurora, used the
slower car of Buzz Calkins to get past Boat in turn 3 with seven
laps left in the 500-kilometer, 208-lap race. But Boat regained the
lead for good one lap later when he passed Ray at almost the same
spot on the track as Ray got by him. Boat finished .926 seconds
ahead of Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy was just faster on top and I could barely stay with him
in the draft,'' said Ray, who had his best finish in an IRL event.
``But second place is a victory for us. We're very excited. This is
a Cinderella story for us. This is a victory for the small teams.''
</P>
<P>
   A two-car battle between Boat and pole-sitter Tony Stewart came
to and end with 33 laps to go when Stewart blew an engine while
running second behind Boat.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second consecutive year at TMS that Stewart lost an
engine late in the race. It happened in 1997, when he was leading
with two laps to go. Stewart also blew an engine while leading the
Indy 500 two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was in control before he lost fifth gear, allowing Boat
to gradually make up a two-second deficit. Boat was making laps at
record speeds, including one lap at 227.273 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But Boat flirted with disaster when he bumped into the side of
rookie J.J. Yeley, who was several laps down. Stewart scooted back
in front of Boat on the restart at lap 149, but Boat regained the
lead when he got inside of Stewart on turn 1 on lap 155. The two
men continued to trade places, including two lead changes on lap
159, before Stewart's engine gave out.
</P>
<P>
   The race barely was under way when Billy Roe spun into the grass
as the green-flag was waved. But the real problem came on lap 5
when six cars were involved in a crash on the backstretch after the
restart.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Guerrero started to spin and hit the wall, causing a
chain reaction behind him. Donnie Beechler rammed into the back of
Stephan Gregoire and collected Indy 500 winner Eddie Cheever in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Boesel hit the wall and destroyed the right side of his
car, and Yeley lost the nose of his car in the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all my fault,'' Guerrero said. ``I got loose out of
turn 2 and lost it and caused all the confusion. We had clutch
problem, but unfortunately I can't use that as an excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero and Cheever ended up against the inside wall, and
Guerrero's Dallara/Aurora flipped over on its top. But Guerrero was
unhurt, and all the other drivers in the accident walked away
without an injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking ahead and saw Guerrero hit wall,'' Cheever said.
``Everybody started panicking, and I had no where to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeley, the youngest driver in the field at 23, felt some of the
older drivers should have been more patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got sideways and got into Boesel and cracked the gearbox,''
Yeley said. ``A lot of guys were a little rambunctious too early in
the race. It's a shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dismore, who hit the wall in turn 1 on lap 71, suffered a
mild concussion and was flown by helicopter to Parkland Hospital in
Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
