r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-IRL-FOYT-TEX     06-07 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-FOYT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOYT ENJOYS VICTORY WITHOUT CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A.J. Foyt has his True Value 500K trophy,
and he didn't have to beat anybody up to get it.
</P>
<P>
   All Foyt had to do was sit back and watch as Billy Boat beat the
field in the Conseco A.J. Foyt Racing Dallara/Aurora last night at
Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Foyt scuffled with Arie Luyendyk over a scoring gaffe
by the U.S. Auto Club, which stripped Boat of the inaugural trophy
a day later and gave it to Luyendyk after reviewing the scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was more fun last year,'' Foyt said with a smile,
alluding to the altercation.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there were no questions, no fisticuffs, no problems _
only sweet vindication for a proud Texan, as another of his
drivers, Kenny Brack, finished third in the Power Team Racing
Dallara/Aurora/Goodyear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this race as bad as we wanted Indy after what
happened last year,'' said Foyt, a four-time Indianapolis 500
winner. ``Last year, as far as I was concerned we ran 1-2, and this
year we ran 1-3, so you can't really holler. I thought last year
was the same way (a win), so we were going to make damn sure it was
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the revision in last year's finish, Foyt driver Davey
Hamilton had been scored as finishing second.
</P>
<P>
   But all that was history last night as Boat claimed his first
career victory in the Indy Racing League after winning the pole at
the Indianapolis 500. He finished 23rd in that race after suffering
gear-box problems.
</P>
<P>
   For Foyt it was a worthwhile homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Foyt raced Indycars at Texas World Speedway in
College Station, where he won Indycar and stock-car races. Foyt has
won more Indy-style races, at 67, than any other driver and was the
first inductee in the Motorsports Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted to being slightly nervous about racing again in his
home state; Foyt's racing operation is in his hometown of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you're in your home state, you want to do good, but
normally that's where you do the worst,'' Foyt said. ``So this
means a lot to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
