<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7927 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      06-07 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' Lima shuts out Royals
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Spring-training exhibitions rarely hold much meaning.
</P>
<P>
   But Jose Lima remembers every detail.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to forget a pitching line that included nine hits,
nine runs and two walks _ in 2 innings. That's the damage the
Kansas City Royals inflicted on Lima during a 15-0 pounding in
March.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was payback,'' Lima said Saturday after pitching a
five-hitter for his first career shutout in a 6-0 victory over the
Royals at the Astrodome. ``It isn't that I have anything against
the Kansas City Royals, but I remember how embarrassed I was when I
gave up nine runs. My career was in jeopardy. I almost blew my
chance to be a starting pitcher this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three months later, Lima has emerged as the biggest
surprise of the season for the Astros, who remained in a
first-place tie with the red-hot Chicago Cubs in the National
League Central. The shutout was the fifth of the season by an
Astros pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio went 2-for-5 with three runs batted in, including a
two-run homer in the third inning that provided Lima all the
offensive support he needed.
</P>
<P>
   Lima (7-2), who also lost to Kansas City in his major-league
debut with the Detroit Tigers in 1994, retired nine of the first 11
batters he faced and only allowed one runner to reach third base.
The 25-year-old Dominican walked one and struck out seven for his
first victory in nearly a month. Lima hadn't won since May 10 at
Milwaukee, a span of one loss and three straight no-decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Not until he struck out Dean Palmer to end the game and the
crowd of 25,516 erupted into a loud cheer did Lima realize he had
thrown his first complete game in the majors. Having spent most of
his career as a reliever, Lima needed 34 starts to go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even think about it,'' said Lima, who lowered his ERA
to 2.99. ``I knew about the shutout, but I didn't even think about
the complete game because with it 6-0, I thought they were going to
take me out. Look how I finished. Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lima walked with one out in the third inning, the Astros
brushed the cobwebs off their bats with Biggio's eighth home run of
the season, a two-run shot to left field off Royals lefthander Jose
Rosado (1-5), a former junior-college standout at Galveston
Community College. Biggio, who is batting .316, added a two-out RBI
single in the fifth to put the Astros ahead 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the third inning, the Astros had scored only one run in
their last 22 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to stay back, swing hard, and I got a pitch to
hit. I was lucky,'' Biggio said of his home run.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros erupted for three more runs in the sixth inning,
highlighted by Carl Everett's two-run single. Jeff Bagwell led off
with a single to center field, and Moises Alou reached base when
Kansas City shortstop Luis Rivera, a former Astro, bobbled a
grounder. Bagwell advanced to third when Rosado's pickoff attempt
at second landed in center field, and Everett cleared the bases
with the first of his two hits in the game. Ricky Gutierrez added
an RBI double for Houston's final run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to wake our bats up. We've had three great starts by
our pitchers, and it was a night when we helped them,'' said
Everett, who added a pair of defensive gems in center field. ``If
this team hits and the pitching continues to do what it's doing,
we're going to be right where we are supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker continued his approach of allowing
his starters to go as deep into the game as possible by allowing
Lima to throw 126 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Lima, who had never pitched beyond 7 innings, was
never in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The only runner to advance to third for Kansas City came in the
fifth inning when Jermaine Dye reached base on an infield hit and
advanced two bases on Lima's wild pickoff throw to first. Lima
struck out Sal Fasano and got Rivera to ground out to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff King doubled for Kansas City to lead off the seventh, but
Lima struck out the next two batters and retired pinch hitter Larry
Sutton on a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   With nine more innings to their credit, Astros starters are
second in the NL behind Atlanta with 390 innings pitched.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last seven innings were the best I've ever seen him
pitch,'' Dierker said of Lima. ``(Kansas City) doesn't have the
most powerful lineup, but the way he was pitching he could have
pitched a shutout against anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That confidence, Lima said, has allowed him to concentrate
solely on pitching, instead of worrying about whether his days as a
starter are numbered like he did in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew if they gave me the opportunity, I was going to take
advantage,'' said Lima, who has pitched seven or more innings in
eight of his 13 starts. ``That gave me the confidence to go out
there and finish the game. I thank my teammates, especially
(catcher) Brad Ausmus and (pitching coach) Vern Ruhle. They've been
the key for me all year and helped keep myself under control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 0114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
