<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     06-07 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TMS EARNS STRIPES FROM INDY DRIVERS; NASCAR'S NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The official benediction won't come until
Rusty and Dale and the boys mosey back into town sometime next
year, but let me be the first to declare, from this day forward,
that Texas Motor Speedway is now an authorized whine-free race
track.
</P>
<P>
   Forevermore, side-by-side racing, speed without end, amen.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least until a blown engine do us part.
</P>
<P>
   Please, no more crying from the Winston Cup boys about how Texas
tough this track is. No more sniffling about unforgiving Turn 4. No
more fretting about the sweating in Turn 1.
</P>
<P>
   No more crabbing and sniveling, period.
</P>
<P>
   Dare we say it? Of course we dare.
</P>
<P>
   Just shut up and drive.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Pep Boys Indy Racing League did last night in
the True Value 500K, and if these guys can do it at 225 mph and
more, it ought to be good enough for the Winston Cup laddies, too.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat, withstanding a late challenge from Plano resident
Greg Ray, won the True Value 500K for the A.J. Foyt racing team.
And this time there were no challengers to provoke a post-race,
winner's circle brawl. This time Boat, who was initially declared
the 1997 winner, won't lose to a computer recount.
</P>
<P>
   Boat's victory on a night when lap speeds at times topped 227
mph added to the irony that hung over TMS all weekend like a cloud
of gas fumes. Two months after the ongoing feud between the Winston
Cup drivers and the speedway threatened to break out into outright
hostilities in April, a ``new'' Texas Motor Speedway debuted.
</P>
<P>
   Almost $3 million in renovations _ the turns were torn up and
reconfigured, the track was repaved and a drainage system was
installed _ had drivers in the Pronto Auto Parts 400K and the IRL
True Value 500K raving about the track to the point that many were
all but complaining about how boring it was to drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get around here,'' Tony Stewart said, almost
yawning, after winning the pole for the True Value 500K in
qualifying Friday. ``I was thinking what I wanted to eat for lunch
after I got done.''
</P>
<P>
   A bologna sandwich, maybe, but a nice little dig at the NASCAR
boys just the same.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, running full-out almost all night, kept his
Glidden/Menards Special near the lead until blowing an engine on
the 176th lap of the 208-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart had talked lovingly of the ``gentle transitions'' while
television analyst Tom Sneva cautioned that the drivers could be
lulled into a false sense of security by the smoothness of the
track. ``It becomes a focus problem,'' Sneva said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously we're not talking about the same track that one
Winston Cup driver suggested in April should be ``padlocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe we're just not talking about the same kind of drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all those NASCAR drivers to blame their crashes on the
racetrack, that's pretty sad. That's what a steering wheel is
for,'' Ray said after his best IRL finish ever last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys (the IRL drivers) said last year that this was a
fun, easy track for them,'' TMS general manager Eddie Gossage
shrugged as the True Value 500K unfolded in front of an estimated
100,000 race fans. ``The changes have only made it better.
Obviously, we're quite pleased with what we're hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gossage realizes that this is only the prelims. The final
word should and must come from the Winston Cuppers. That's what
will make or break this track, and everyone understands and
concedes that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until Dale (Earnhardt) and Rusty (Wallace) and that bunch cast
their vote,'' Gossage said, ``we'll just take a wait-and-see
attitude. For us to hear what we've heard this weekend is
gratifying, but it doesn't mean the Winston dilemma is solved.
We'll have to hear it from them.''
</P>
<P>
   A concern here was that TMS, in finally grasping that it could
not win a public relations war with Winston Cup drivers, would lose
its character as it reconfigured to make things easier. While the
NASCAR drivers talked longingly about the wide-open spaces on
tracks in California and Las Vegas, some of us didn't see anything
wrong with a track that was barbed-wire tough and challenging.
</P>
<P>
   But in making the changes, without giving up its beloved
24-degree banks, TMS may have finally gotten the best of both
worlds _ a rugged, challenging track that allows
pedal-to-the-metal, side-by-side, thrill-a-minute racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listened to the drivers and tried to give them what they
wanted,'' Gossage said. ``A smoother track, easier transitions,
wider turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're running at 190 miles per hour, that's not easy no
matter where you're at or what you're doing. By design, this track
is not nearly as wide or as much like a boulevard as (California
and Las Vegas) are.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should it be.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong with a little Texas character, you see.
</P>
<P>
   Come on back to town next April, boys. We'll be tickled pink to
see you again.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember, this is now an official whine-free zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
