<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, THE EVENING WAS A WRECK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For the first 33 laps of last night's True
Value 500K, a bigger, renovated and rejuvenated Texas Motor
Speedway was like a bully walking through a playground.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the 28 Indy Racing League drivers who started the race
had their lunch stolen early.
</P>
<P>
   After three early caution flags produced a smaller field, TMS
turned into a kinder, gentler speedway the rest of the night. The
race finished with six cautions for a total of 45 laps and seven
drivers out of the race because of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine out there, but there is nothing you can do if people
are spinning in front of you,'' said Raul Boesel, who crashed early
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The first crash came on the fifth lap and knocked Roberto
Guerrero, Stephan Gregoire, Donnie Beechler, Raul Boesel and
Indianapolis 500 champion Eddie Cheever from the race. J.J. Yeley's
car sustained nose damage, but he returned to the race.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero, in the No. 21 Dallara/Aurora with new sponsorship from
Nokia, spun as he exited Turn 2 and hit the wall. As his car came
off the wall and back toward the middle of the track, a pack of
four cars started spinning to try to avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever, in the No. 51 Rachel's Team Cheever Dallara/Aurora, and
Gregoire's No. 77 Blue Star Batteries G Force/Aurora, braked when
they saw Guerrero spin ahead of them. That left Beechler, in the
No. 98 Cahill G Force/Aurora, nowhere to go, and he ran into the
back of Gregoire's right rear tire, flipping him over. Cheever and
Boesel, who started together in the 10th row, tried slowing down
but couldn't avoid the wreck. Boesel, in McCormack Motorsports' No.
30 G Force/Aurora said he was hit from behind, which caused him to
spin and crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all my fault,'' Guerrero said. ``I just got loose out
of (Turn) 2 and spun. We developed a clutch problem early, but I
can't use that as an excuse. I have no idea what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the smoke cleared and emergency crews made it to the
scene, Beechler's car was turned upside down. The other four cars
had too much damage to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those deals where you're so close at speeds so
fast that if anything happens, it's going to take out a few cars,''
Beechler said. ``We happened to be the unlucky guys involved in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero, who started in Row 4, was the highest qualifier to
crash.
</P>
<P>
   None of the drivers were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a group of four cars, everyone trying to avoid it,''
Cheever said. ``At 200 mph, you don't have much choice of what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Elisio Salazar, in the No. 15 Reebok Riley and Scott/Aurora,
caused a fourth caution at lap 33 when he had engine failure in
Turn 1 and went up against the wall. Drivers ran the 39 laps
without a caution before Mark Dismore spun his No. 28 Kelley
Automotive Dallara/Aurora in Turn 1, hit the wall and could not
return.
</P>
<P>
   Dismore sustained a slight concussion and was taken to Parkland
Memorial Hospital in Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
