<SLUG> BC-BBO-PADRES-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SHUT OUT PADRES, 3-0
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ San Diego Padres second baseman Quilvio Veras
stepped to the plate with two outs and the bases loaded in what
would be the pivotal seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers left-hander Eric Gunderson and right-hander Danny
Patterson continued throwing in the bullpen, yet manager Johnny
Oates summoned neither. The manager stayed with right-hander John
Burkett, who entered this contest with the second-highest
earned-run average among American League qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett justified the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Veras took a called third strike on a 1-2 fastball from Burkett
in what would be the Padres' best and only threat during the
Rangers' 3-0 victory last night at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went on the way Burkie was throwing the ball,'' Oates said.
``Certainly, the numbers suggest you want to turn Veras around in
that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Veras, a switch hitter who entered the game hitting 38 points
better against right-handers, came to the plate with one hit in
three previous at-bats against Burkett. However, Veras sent center
fielder Roberto Kelly deep into the gap in right-center field
during his third-inning at-bat and forced left fielder Rusty Greer
into a sliding catch with a sixth-inning line drive.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, though, opposed Gunderson entering that seventh-inning
situation with Ken Caminiti and Ruben Rivera available on the
Padres' bench and never considered Patterson to face Veras.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that (Burkett) was the best pitcher for that situation,
regardless of what the outcome was,'' said Oates, whose Rangers
possessed a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett (4-5) also received support three batters earlier from
catcher Ivan Rodriguez in what Oates described as ``the defensive
play of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres first baseman Wally Joyner began the seventh inning with
a single and advanced to second on a single by right fielder Mark
Sweeney. Padres manager Bruce Bochy then attempted to advance both
runners into scoring position by calling for a sacrifice bunt from
third baseman Ed Giovanola.
</P>
<P>
   Giovanola got the bunt down, but Rodriguez sprang from behind
the plate and, despite being off balance, fired a strike to third
baseman Fernando Tatis to retire Joyner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodriguez made a great play on the bunt,'' Bochy said. ``He
might be the only catcher able to make that play. It was a big play
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Reserve infielder Luis Alicea, who replaced injured second
baseman Mark McLemore in the fourth inning, delivered the decisive
base hit _ a two-run, fifth-inning double against Padres
left-hander Sterling Hitchcock (3-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed that he was throwing a lot of off-speed pitches so I
was looking for one that wasn't too low,'' said Alicea, who shot a
2-1 pitch between Giovanola and the foul line. ``He gave it to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland pitched a scoreless ninth inning to record
his 16th save in 17 opportunities this season, but this evening
belonged to Burkett (4-5).
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander, who retired 11 consecutive batters during a
stretch between the first and fourth innings, allowed only five
hits and one walk in his 118-pitch appearance. It also gave hope
that he may be nearing the pitcher who dominated in spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw very well the other night in Tampa,'' Oates said in
reference to the Rangers' 4-1 loss to the Devil Rays. ``If you
could take back one pitch (a three-run homer to center fielder
Quinton McCracken), he might have pitched a shutout the last time,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Burkett credited pitching coach Dick Bosman with an alteration
in his delivery from the stretch for the recent improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``My control has gotten a lot better, and my slider has been 10
times better,'' Burkett said. ``It was useless before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three or four games, I've been throwing a lot better.
It's been a slow process, and we've got a long way to go. This is a
nice sign. Hopefully, I can be consistent from here on out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
