</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-RAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY COMES UP SHORT, BUT IMPRESSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIM PEDLEY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Shoes don't last long on the feet of Ginger
Ray.
</P>
<P>
   ``See these?'' she said. ``I got them just before the
Indianapolis 500,'' two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``And look,'' she said displaying a sole with a large hole worn
away.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is pacing. Nervous pacing. The kind of nervous
pacing that comes with being the mother of a son who makes his
living driving 225 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Ray secretly hopes her son Greg's Indy Racing League
career is a short but healthy one. ``He has two kids and a wife,''
Ginger Ray said. And a mom who gets sick to her stomach on race day
and wants her son to return to the family marine business in Plano,
even though he finished second last night in the True Value 500K at
Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``She may have to wait a while,'' said Greg Ray, after his
impressive performance at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Ray started from the 14th spot and steadily worked his way up
toward the front, running among the top three for most of the 208
laps of the event.
</P>
<P>
   He ran second for a good chunk of the final few laps, and
battled with race winner, Billy Boat, when the race was on the
line. On lap 200, he passed Boat to take the lead, but was repassed
a short time later and had to settle for second place _ which he
gladly did.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a victory for us,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Preventing a better run at Boat was the fact that the winner had
a bit more gear, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Making Ray even happier was the fact he qualified poorly and
also overcame a problem in the pits during the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our qualifying effort just didn't go the way we wanted it
to,'' he said. ``Then, we killed the motor on pit lane. We made
some mistakes, but we were still able work our way back from 18th''
place, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there was having a huge night on a track a few miles from
his hometown of Plano.
</P>
<P>
   ``This, in front of the hometown fans, this is great,'' Ray
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's place in the IRL series appears to be solidifying. He
earned a place on front row at Indy and was running strong in the
race until a broken gear ended his chance for what he believes
would have been a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like we were going to win Indy,'' he said. ``I thought
we were the best car out there. Now, we are second-best here. You
are going to see some pretty good results from this car.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray hopes sponsors and potential sponsors are seeing those
results right now. His team lost a major sponsor before Indy. That
sponsor, he said, wanted his team to change personnel and tire
brands. Ray refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a small team,'' Ray said. ``The first thing we needed
to do was focus on people. The former sponsor wanted to get rid of
Firestone and (team manager Tom) Knapp. I believe in them, so'' Ray
walked away.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up another major sponsor before the TMS race, but the
deal with that company, ATT Wireless, was just for last night's
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this performance gets the excited,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't appear to get Ginger Ray too excited. As her son
battled for the victory over the final laps, she buried her head in
her hands, and her hands into the iron fence that surrounds the
victory circle. She sobbed and shook as she did so.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's my biggest fan,'' Greg Ray said, a touch of sarcasm in
his voice.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not ``the'' biggest. The Rays had to get 75 tickets
for friends from Plano, and his garage area has been besieged by
well-wishers this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see him do good,'' Ginger Ray said, ``and get
what he wants out of it, and then get out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greg Ray's probably right. It could be a while.
</P>
</TEXT>
