<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARL CAN TALK TO CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ George Karl has been given official permission by
the Seattle SuperSonics to talk to the Clippers about their
head-coaching vacancy.
</P>
<P>
   Although Karl, who was fired by the Sonics last month, is under
contract to Seattle until July 1, he is allowed to speak to the
Clippers and Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   But if any other team _ such as the Lakers or Chicago Bulls _ is
interested in Karl, it must still receive permission from the
Sonics until his contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   Karl's interest in the Clippers remains debatable, as he waits
to see what other coaching positions become available.
</P>
<P>
   Karl, who could seek as much as $5 million per season, said in
an interview this week he was willing to lower his asking price for
one of the league's plum jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money has never been a part of my philosophy in looking for a
job. I would go someplace where we have a chance to win a
championship for a lot less money,'' Karl told the Seattle Times.
``It's never been money. I think it will happen. I will coach in
the NBA next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers already owe former coach Bill Fitch $2 million for
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Clippers have appeared to be in no hurry to hire,
they might have to move up their timetable.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers' second choice, Paul Westphal, is now a candidate
to replace Karl in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal, who is good friends with Seattle general manager Wally
Walker, said he thinks both teams will hire a coach in the next two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect something will happen pretty soon,'' Westphal said.
``Both teams have said they want to have a coach in place before
the draft (June 24).''
</P>
<P>
   There has been some speculation that Westphal expects to land
one of the two openings because he has put his house in Phoenix up
for sale. But Westphal said he has always intended to move, because
his son is about to graduate from high school.
</P>
<P>
   Draft workouts: The Clippers, who have two first-round picks,
have been busy working out players as the draft nears.
</P>
<P>
   Their expected No.1 pick, Arizona point guard Mike Bibby, will
come to Los Angeles this week for his pre-draft workout. He will be
represented by super-agent David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have already worked out Kansas swingman Paul
Pierce, Pacific center Michael Olowokandi, Michigan forward Robert
Traylor, UCLA center Jelani McCoy, Ball State guard Bonzi Wells and
Cincinnati guard Ruben Patterson, among others.
</P>
<P>
   According to several sources, Pierce has had the most impressive
workout so far. If the Clippers aren't desperate for a point guard,
he might sneak into their plans.
</P>
<P>
   Vice president of basketball operations Elgin Baylor was in
Chicago this weekend for the pre-draft camp that included more than
60 potential draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players that Baylor was able to watch were McCoy,
guard Bryce Drew of Valparaiso, Arizona guard Miles Simon, high
school star Korleone Young, St. John's guard Felipe Lopez and
UCLA's J.R. Henderson and Toby Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   Beside the No.1 overall pick, the Clippers also have the 22nd
selection, acquired from Miami in the Isaac Austin-Brent Barry
trade.
</P>
<P>
   Someone like Drew, who improved his stock with good performances
in Chicago, would help the Clippers strengthen their backcourt and
should be available. Drew can also play the point, another plus for
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   They also wouldn't mind seeing McCoy drop to No.22, which would
provide insurance in case free-agent center Austin signs with
another team.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were also in Chicago, with executives Jerry West and
Mitch Kupchak and coach Del Harris all in attendance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
