<SLUG> BC-BBC-SERIES-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN DEVILS SHOW METTLE IN TITLE LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ Usually when the score is 21-14, the bands march
onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   The game was over.
</P>
<P>
   After one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, ``nine''
home runs that lit up the scoreboard like touchdowns, the College
World Series finally came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with 7-foot radio announcer Tom Dore wondering whether
it ever would. ``When the game started,'' Dore mused, ``I was
6-5.''
</P>
<P>
   It ended after four head-shaking, record-breaking hours, with
the Sun Devils telling themselves before their last at-bat that
maybe they still could find a way to do it. To come back. Again.
One more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Nine.'' That was Arizona State's motto this year. Never
concede. Fight to the finish. Play all nine.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Murphy's team showed that unsinkable spirit in Saturday's
national championship game. ASU trailed Southern California, 8-0,
before starting pitcher Ryan Mills could break a sweat. The Sun
Devils made the score 8-5. The Trojans went up, 9-5. The Sun Devils
closed to 9-8. The Trojans struck again, 14-8. The Sun Devils
answered, 14-13.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Michael Collins, who hit a grand slam, and his
teammates were like those irrepressible salesmen Dagwood Bumstead
is always battling. The Trojans couldn't shut the door because of a
hand, a knee, an elbow, a foot.
</P>
<P>
   But ASU finally lost the battle. This dream season ended,
ironically, in the ninth when USC's Jason Lane came to the plate
with the bases loaded and ripped an offering from ASU's Chuck
Crumpton to the deepest part of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ASU center fielder Rudy Arguelles went to the wall. Eyed the
ball. Jumped for it in vain. His raised glove looked like a hand
disappearing in the deep. Four more runs. Trojans, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
   This is a curious business, sportswriting, deciding whom to
bless and whom to blame. Some will pin it all on Mills. In the
final and biggest game of his college career, the ASU ace wasn't
the pitcher who overpowered the Trojans the last time he faced
them, striking out 15. Mills didn't have his fastball. At the end
of this long season, his arm was on empty.
</P>
<P>
   Mills couldn't get anyone out. But neither could the Sun Devils'
other pitchers, and they used five.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a good hitting team,'' Mills said in the
understatement of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans won because they pounded out 23 hits and made big
plays, and perhaps none was bigger or bolder than their triple
steal with two outs in the seventh inning. One run scored. Two more
followed when Wes Rachels hit a single. For you investors, Rachels,
who went 5 for 7 with seven RBIs, is listed on the stock exchange
as Hitters Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans were the better team. ASU's Pac-10 rivals earned the
right to celebrate, and when the game finally ended, here they
came, racing from the dugout and jumping into a joyous pile.
</P>
<P>
   For those in the ASU dugout, the scene was difficult to watch.
The defeat left this team feeling hollow inside. But nothing is
more resilient than youth. In time, the Devils will be able to look
back on this season and smile. They should feel good about what
they accomplished and what they became, a team.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unique group. Arguelles, the center fielder, is 26
years old. Andrew Beinbrink, the third baseman who hit three home
runs in four games, makes his own clothes. The catcher, Greg
Halvorson, from Tucson, was drafted as a pitcher. Mikel Moreno, a
former two-time all-state quarterback at Mesa High School, plays
baseball as if every play, every at-bat, is a crucial third down in
the fourth quarter of a tie game.
</P>
<P>
   Collins? His baseball cap is stained with the whitish residue of
a season of perspiration. ``I've washed it a few times,'' he said
the other day. But Collins never asked for a new one. Didn't want
one. This one said what he, and this team, is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ASU played one of the nation's toughest schedules. The Sun
Devils won three in a row in the regionals to stay alive. They came
to Omaha as the No. 6 seed and won three games and were in the last
one until that metallic thonk in the ninth sent the ball rising
into the blue sky and it disappeared over the center field wall.
</P>
<P>
   Crazy game. Great season. The Sun Devils did what Murphy asked.
They kept their heads down, and played hardball. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
