<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAILMAN NOT DELIVERING BIG PACKAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Once is OK. Twice is a trend. A few more times and his
legacy drops to garden-variety postal clerk.
</P>
<P>
   For the third straight year, Karl Malone is struggling when
needed the most. Clanking shots. Looking skittish. A shadow of his
statistical self. And you have to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence or pattern? Champion or Charles Barkley?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any excuses,'' Malone said. ``But we will not win
this series if I don't play better.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Utah Jazz flushed away home-court advantage on Friday,
it marked the first time in 60 games they had lost when entering
the fourth quarter with a lead. It also happened to be a game where
Malone didn't score a field goal in the final 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   You can rave about the Bulls' rotating defense, Dobermans
interfering with normal delivery, double teams arriving like a
steady swarm of mosquitoes. But superstars find a way to get it
done. When the shot isn't working, they navigate their way to the
foul line. They do something.
</P>
<P>
   Malone is doing nothing, and it's not like he's bumping heads
with Bill Russell, either.
</P>
<P>
   He is being checked by Luc Longley, a wonderful fellow with his
feet stuck in cement. He is being stymied by Dennis Rodman, a
creature he used to pancake in the past. In a singular moment, he
couldn't even control the blocks against Scottie Pippen, instead
drawing an offensive foul.
</P>
<P>
   So Malone is taking the easy way out, launching jumpers, hoping
instead of competing. He is shooting under 35 percent for the
series, and that number is inflated thanks to an array of layups
and dunks courtesy of John Stockton. And his production in Game 2
was more Muresan than Malone: Five baskets, five fouls, four
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether I'm more content to be
perimeter-oriented,'' Malone said. ``But all year long, I've made
those shots. Kind of comes at a (expletive) time to not make them.
. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the core of Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he didn't fare well in the Western Conference Finals
against Seattle. Last year, after carting off his first MVP trophy,
questions arose about his mental toughness in a subpar series
against the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Now this.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder if it's just a slump. Or the indomitable presence of
Michael Jordan. Or the big stage simply shrinking the country boy
from Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Malone admitted he was nervous last year, but a six-game tour of
the NBA Finals should've been enough to dislodge the apple in his
throat. Malone stunk in Game 1, although that performance was
easily attributable to a 10-game layoff. But he cost his team
dearly in Game 2 because if Malone had any kind of night, the Jazz
might have the Bulls in a half-nelson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one time that you want to have excuses, this would
be my time to make up some,'' Malone said. ``But I don't have any.
I'm just not playing well right now, and its come at an unfortunate
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Malone wasn't alone in Game 2. He and his friends were
spectators in the first half, a team that waved their capes when
the Bulls charged to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Toni) Kukoc drove around us like we weren't even on the
floor,'' Utah Coach Jerry Sloan said. ``That tells you right away
that you're not ready to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Jazz got it right. Except for Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of things I could've done,'' he said. ``I take
responsibility for that. It's on these shoulders, and when I don't
do it, I face the firing squad.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he has always been a stand-up guy.
</P>
<P>
   But for more than a decade, Malone has prided himself on a
subjective concept, the traits that make one a man. For Malone, it
has been a collection of steely confidence, impenetrable will,
fierce independence and a garage full of motorcycles. But more than
anything, he has presented himself as a man who will do his job
with amazing consistency, unburdened by fear or intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   No one would dare argue. Until now. And with the postage long
overdue, you have to wonder. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
