A7938 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-GAME3-ADV-     06-07 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS-GAME3-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERPLEXED SLOAN WANTS MORE EFFORT FROM JAZZ  
 `WE LOOKED LIKE WE WERE PLAYING IN TUXEDOS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the rest of the Jazz slipped out of the practice gym
Saturday in Salt Lake City, Coach Jerry Sloan and forward Karl
Malone remained behind.
</P>
<P>
   Malone wanted to shoulder most of the blame for Utah's Game 2
loss to Chicago that allowed the Bulls to achieve a split at the
Delta Center in the first two games of the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Sloan was willing to put the blame on just about anything except
Malone _ including his own coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't get them to play harder than that, maybe they need
another coach,'' Sloan said. ``That's my job. That's why coaches
get fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan is tough on his players, even when they win. He seemed
downright perplexed at their effort in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked like we were playing in tuxedos,'' Sloan said. ``We
didn't want to get touched. On their last three-point play, we
looked like we were in a pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   ``John (Stockton) said he was fouled when they stole the ball. I
don't care if there was a foul or not. You would think at this
point of it, you may want to run down the floor like we care if we
win or not.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the theme of Sloan's 40-minute meeting with his players
Saturday morning. They weren't physical enough. They didn't hustle.
They gave up too many offensive rebounds because players were more
interested in leaking out early to get an easy shot than in
crashing the boards.
</P>
<P>
   When someone pointed out to Malone that Sloan had been ``a
little short'' with reporters, Malone laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad you're getting some of it, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has become the focal point of Utah's loss. He has made
only 14 of 41 shots in the first two games, and he gave himself a
``D-minus'' for his performance so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an `F' in some schools,'' he said. ``But maybe the
teacher likes me a little.''
</P>
<P>
   When Malone got off to a poor start in the Finals last year, he
cleared his mind with long rides on his Harley-Davidson. But Malone
said that causes such a stir in Salt Lake City now that he doesn't
do it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's the problem,'' he said, evoking more laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Malone admitted he hasn't played ``relaxed'' in the Finals. He
worries about forcing shots instead of getting them within the
offense. And he still believes he's going to rediscover his touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I miss a couple, I expect to make the next two or three in
a row,'' he said. ``I still believe in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Malone said, he thought he had hit a 17-foot shot that
would have given Utah the lead back after Michael Jordan's key
three-point play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' Malone said. ``So did the other 30 shots I've
missed in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sloan's mood wasn't quite so light, he insisted that
Malone's shooting isn't Utah's biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still shot 49 percent,'' he said. ``Are we supposed to
shoot 80 percent?
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned the ball over, how many times?''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty, Sloan was told, for 33 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned it over because we didn't know what we were doing in
our offense. We didn't defend them. And we gave up, what, 18
offensive rebounds? I have a problem with that. I have a problem
with playing like that in our own building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset. If they don't want to play hard, I don't know what
can be done about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sloan said the series is far from over. The Jazz won the
first game with Malone struggling, and Utah was in position to go
up 2-0 before crumbling down the stretch in Game 2. Again, Malone
was off his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up by a point with 48 seconds to play, and he hasn't
shot the ball well yet,'' Sloan said. ``That's the exciting thing
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz must win at least one of the next three games at the
United Center to bring the series back to Utah. The Jazz get the
first opportunity today in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back and remember, I said before this started that
the little things are what win these games,'' Sloan said. ``Twenty
turnovers and 18 offensive rebounds, that's what I'm talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Jazz players) are the ones talking about wanting to
win a championship, about getting to that next level. Talk won't
get it done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
