<SLUG> BC-BKW-MERCURY-STARZZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY OUTWORKS STARZZ AGAIN  
 MILLER READY FOR STARS' RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The return of Michele Timms and five other
players from the World Championships next week is like Christmas
Eve to Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's in the big box under the tree, and you can't
wait to open it,'' she said of a package that holds not only the
veteran Australian point guard Timms but 6-foot-8 first-round draft
pick Maria Stepanova, 6-5 Marlies Askamp, sharpshooter Mikiko
Hagiwara and two other Australians.
</P>
<P>
   They will only add to the stash of presents Miller already has
opened and found delightful.
</P>
<P>
   That team outworked the Utah Starzz for the second time in five
days, winning, 82-64, Saturday night at the Delta Center. In the
exhibitions, the defending WNBA Western Conference champions had a
combined 35-15 edge in steals and forced twice as many turnovers
(56) as they committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defensive intensity has been phenomenal,'' guard Bridget
Pettis said. ``Our shots aren't falling (Phoenix shot 39.2 percent
from the floor), but if the offense isn't flowing we've always got
the defense to fall back on.''
</P>
<P>
   Toni Foster and Brandy Reed combined for nine of the Mercury's
19 steals. Reed, a third-round draft pick, had eight steals Tuesday
in a 74-66 win at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Starzz, last in the West in 1997 and therefore recipient of
the league's No. 1 draft pick, 7-2 Malgorzata Dydek, led by seven
with 6:33 remaining in Phoenix. But the Mercury was less
intimidated by Dydek in the rematch.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-1 run led to 46-33 halftime lead, which Utah cut to six
(53-47) with 13:07 remaining. Phoenix scored 12 of the next 14
points, including four by second-round draft pick Andrea Kuklova,
and the 4,696 Starzz fans spent the rest of the night rehashing the
Jazz-killing Steve Kerr rebound from Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andrea has a sensational game (eight points, five rebounds,
two steals),'' Miller said of the Slovakian guard/forward. ``That's
the most comfortable I've seen her and a sign she's turned the
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercury 6-3 centers Jennifer Gillom (19 points, seven rebounds)
and Pauline Jordan (15 point, nine boards) and 6-1 power forward
Foster (12 points, four boards) played big against Dydek in spite
of her six blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Dydek also had 11 points and eight rebounds, but again did not
attempt a dunk. The teams do not play the first of four
regular-season games until June 26 so seven other opponents must
defend against the inaugural slam in U.S. women's pro basketball
before the duty returns to the Mercury.
</P>
<P>
   ``She (Dydek) is doing more and more things,'' Miller said.
``She took two nice long shots, was looking to be aggressive and
defensively challenged everything. You could see her confidence
growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller expects most of her returners at practice Tuesday and
must reduce the roster from 18 to 11 by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix begins its 30-game regular season Thursday at
Sacramento. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
