<HEADLINE>
ROCKY TIMES  
 DISAPPOINTING START LEAVES BAYLOR'S JOB IN JEOPARDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arguably the biggest disappointment in the major leagues resides
in Denver's Coors Field, home of the underachieving Colorado
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, expected to seriously contend this season _
especially after acquiring pitcher  &UR; Darryl Kile and second baseman
 &UR; Mike Lansing, &UR; and keeping pitcher  &UR; Pedro Astacio _ have done
little besides lose games since a 4-1 opening week.
</P>
<P>
   It has gotten so bad that some of the most faithful fans in the
game have taken to loudly voicing their displeasure with the
Rockies at home games, which has definitely caught the players'
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun,'' reigning MVP  &UR; Larry Walker said. ``It's not
fun for us, it's not fun for our manager and it's sure not fun for
our fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of boos going on, and these fans are probably
the most loyal fans in the game. To hear boos from them, it's very
frustrating. At the same time, I don't blame them.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Rockies lost the first two games to the Diamondbacks
last week _ looking awful in the process _ the talk shows in Denver
started calling for Manager  &UR; Don Baylor's head.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was obviously embarrassed after watching his club get
whipped by a combined score of 15-7, games in which Rockies left
fielder  &UR; Dante
 &UR; Bichette committed an ugly error when a single went under his glove
and the team generally looked flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the worst game we've played here in a long
time,'' Baylor said. ``To watch as spectators and watch as a
coaching staff and players, yeah, it's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Belief is growing that if Baylor does not straighten out the
Rockies by the All-Star Game, which will take place in Denver, he
may find himself out of a job shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest problems afflicting the Rockies include the
perception that there are two sets of rules for the players, one
for the veterans and the other for the less established players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guys that never stretch or practice defense before
games,'' one Rockies player said. ``It's a joke. We're just not
that good a team.'' &QL; 
Unit offerings &QL; 
By all accounts, Seattle's  &UR; Randy Johnson is not enjoying much of a
season, at least not by his high standards. Just check out who has
hit home runs off him so far.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list is the Chicago White Sox's  &UR; Greg Norton, who
has hit two home runs off Johnson. Other notables on the list
include Detroit's  &UR; David Bell, Texas'  &UR; Damon Buford, Texas'  &UR; Bill
Simms and Anaheim's  &UR; Damon Mashore.
</P>
<P>
   They have hit six of the 10 home runs Johnson has allowed.
Otherwise, they had combined for seven other home runs entering the
weekend. &QL; 
Royal problems ahead? &QL; 
The Kansas City Royals, who have not had solid ownership since
 &UR; Ewing &UR; Kauffman passed away and have looked the part of a
small-market franchise, drafted three high-profile pitchers in last
week's draft.
</P>
<P>
   While Royals fans were bubbly with the news that Kansas City
selected
 &UR; Matt Burch, Jeff Austin and  &UR; Christopher George in the first round,
agent  &UR; Tommy Tanzer, who represents Burch, wondered aloud what the
tight-fisted Royals were doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Austin's going to want $3 million,'' Tanzer said. ``The other
kid (George) told everybody he wanted $2 million, which is why he
fell to where he was. We didn't really set our sights on a dollar
figure. I don't think Austin has any relevance to us. The relevance
is George.''
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Austin is being advised by  &UR; Scott Boras, who
advised
 &UR; J.D. Drew to hold out all of last year. &QL; 
One man's view &QL; 
Hall of Fame pitcher  &UR; Bob Feller is often viewed as an ornery cuss
who has a strong disdain for the modern player. Then again, Feller
may have something valid to say when it comes to evaluating today's
players.
</P>
<P>
   The following are some of his views of Feller, now 79, who began
his big league career as a 17-year-old in 1936:
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the problems we have in this country today is that kids
can't handle the money and notoriety. Some of them think they're
invincible, and nobody is. You have to remember the good Lord gave
you a great arm. And maybe your success has a lot to do with your
upbringing, the people and coaches who developed you along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't just fallen off the turnip truck when I started
playing. I'd played a lot of semi-pro ball in Iowa. I knew I didn't
want any hangers-on, any of the ne'er-do-wells that start coming
around. When you say no, mean it. Not everybody is able to do
that.'' &QL; 
Home improvement guy? &QL; 
Kansas City catcher  &UR; Sal Fasano was recently talking about how
obscure a player he is when he dropped this gem:
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going out one night with  &UR; Mark Gubicza and  &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Montgomery when we were in California,'' Fasano said. ``A guy
walked up to us and said, `Hey, you're Mark Gubicza. Hey, you're
Jeff Montgomery.' Then he walked up to me and said, `Hey, didn't
you work on my house?' '' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
