r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR &LR;      06-07 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS PITCH FITS AFTER SMOOTH STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ For the Diamondbacks, it was a 17-hour period worth
throwing straight into the incinerator.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after suffering a demoralizing loss the night before, the
Diamondbacks showed amazing energy for four innings Saturday
afternoon before succumbing to a so-so Oakland Athletics club,
getting walloped, 10-5, in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks starter Andy Benes, one of the handful of veterans
on the club, had a chance to pull the psyches of his young
teammates out of the stupor they were in after Friday night's 2-1
loss.
</P>
<P>
   But Benes fell apart in the fifth inning and never made it to
the sixth, heading for the showers in his shortest outing of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a first- or second-year guy throwing, you might
say, `OK,' '' Benes said. ``But I'm not a first-year guy. There's
no one to blame for this loss except me. I had to shut the door. We
needed a win today, especially when it was coupled with (Friday)
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks got slammed in the teeth the previous night
when they had Oakland beaten only to watch first base umpire Mike
Reilly refuse to call Mike Blowers out on strikes after the head of
his bat clearly went through the strike zone on a check swing that
should have ended the game and preserved a 1-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Blowers lined a single on the next pitch, and the A's
eventually won the game in 11 innings, setting the stage for a
Saturday game where the Diamondbacks' young players were in dire
need of direction.
</P>
<P>
   Benes, clearly the pitcher Manager Buck Showalter would have
hand-picked for Saturday's start, was on the mound and retired the
first 11 batters in a row as Arizona clung to a 1-0 lead. The
player who wants to be a clubhouse leader was leading.
</P>
<P>
   All seemed right for the fragile minds of the young players
until Benes allowed five consecutive RBI singles, and the
Diamondbacks wound up getting body-slammed.
</P>
<P>
   The frustrations from the night before were evident for all to
see in the postgame clubhouse Friday when Showalter went into a fit
inside his office shortly after meeting with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Loud, foul language and doors slamming were the highlights, as
were the stunned players in the clubhouse who heard the rare tirade
from their manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just frustrations boiling over,'' pitcher Willie Blair
said. ``Heck, we're all frustrated. There's nothing wrong with
showing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's show of emotions stemmed from his club losing a game
it practically won if Blowers is properly rung up. Showalter knows
how precious and difficult each of his club's 19 victories have
been this season. He did manage to calm down later.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family's here,'' Showalter said. ``So I went back to the
hotel and saw my children sleeping. It made me think that life's
too short to dwell on things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is his livelihood, and winning is the barometer by
which every major league manager is measured, even if it is an
expansion club.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's message was to let his players know it is acceptable
to let your emotions get the best of you for a moment. After all,
baseball is an emotional game, and the constant losing is getting
to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's loss set up what should have been a flat all-around
performance on Saturday. Mostly because the fragile minds of the
young players hadn't really gone through a situation like Friday's,
where a victory was taken away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while for young players to basically learn how to
have the same concentration level every day, the one we're always
trying to obtain,'' Blair said. ``We haven't had a lot of things go
our way this year. The toughest thing in this game is to grind
every day and find ways to win. When things aren't going well, you
tend to find ways to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's outburst Friday night also came from knowing the
Diamondbacks could have been in line for a three-game sweep if they
had won Friday. It would not have been out of the question for the
A's to shrug their shoulders and say, ``Oh, well, it's just not
going to happen,'' if they had lost 1-0 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Diamondbacks are left with simply trying to salvage one
victory from Oakland this afternoon. Like their season, this series
has turned into ``what could have been.'' &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
