<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ'S ROLE MAY DI MINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Diamondbacks reliever  &UR; Felix Rodriguez was starting to
work his way back into the good graces of Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter
and pitching coach  &UR; Mark Connor when disaster struck Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander entered the game against Oakland in the seventh
inning but gave up four runs on four hits and walked one, putting
the Diamondbacks into a hole out of which they couldn't climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix was quietly working his way back,'' Showalter said. ``He
was pitching effectively. We hope he'll be able to come back
again.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely that Rodriguez will get a chance to be the
closer for a while. Veteran right-hander  &UR; Gregg Olson has a claim
to that role, and recently acquired right-hander  &UR; Willie Banks also
will see a considerable amount of time in middle relief, Showalter
said. &QL; 
Murphy gets greeting &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks first base coach  &UR; Dwayne Murphy, who was an
outfielder with the Athletics from 1978-87 before moving on to
Detroit in 1988 and Philadelphia in 1989, was given a warm
reception by the Oakland fans during the first two games of this
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Other than an old-timers' game here in the early 1990s, this is
the only time Murphy has been back to the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of good memories here,'' Murphy said. ``It's been
a long time since I've been here and you wonder if the people
remember, but it was a nice surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy won Gold Gloves from 1980-85 while patroling center field
for the Athletics. &QL; 
Trojan triumph &QL; 
First baseman-outfielder  &UR; Mike Robertson, whose contract was
purchased by the Diamondbacks from Triple-A Tucson on Wednesday,
had his eyes glued to the TV set before Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   He was watching his alma mater, Southern California, face
Arizona State in the championship game of the College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still keep in contact with (Coach  &UR; Mike) Gillespie, but I
don't follow the team like I should,'' Robertson said. ``It is nice
to see them doing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is the pitching. We never seem to have been able to
close it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojan pitchers had a bit of difficulty again Saturday, but
the hitters more than made up for it by pounding the Sun Devils,
21-14. &QL; 
`Coach' Bell? &QL; 
For only the second time this season,  &UR; Jay Bell did not start at
shortstop as former Oakland player Tony Batista stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Bell worked off excess energy before the game by hitting ground
balls to infielders during infield practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I've got to do something,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
