<SLUG> BC-BBC-ASU-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAL OF HOME JOLTS SUN DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAHA, Neb. _ It was rare. It was gutsy. And it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California executed a triple steal Saturday in the
College World Series championship game that scored the first of
three seventh-inning runs and seemed to take some life out of
Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, the Trojans'  &UR; Morgan Ensberg sprinted from third
base with  &UR; Chad Pennington on the mound and beat the tag. Catcher
 &UR; Greg
 &UR; Halvorson thought he had Ensberg, but umpire  &UR; Dick Runchey said no.
Base runners  &UR; Jeremy Freitas and  &UR; Seth Davidson also advanced and
later scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never been accused of being smart,'' USC Coach  &UR; Mike
Gillespie said. ``Although it's a very unusual situation, I can
tell you we've done it before on more than one occasion. &QL; 
``In spite of the fact that it makes absolutely no sense, it's
remarkably successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie said before the Trojans ran the play, they ``ran a
little bluff at third'' on the pitcher to see how he would
respond. &QL; 
Go figure &QL; 
How's this for a stretch?
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, Kentucky won its first national championship in
basketball, Michigan its first in hockey and USC its first in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, national titles were won by Kentucky in basketball and
Michigan in hockey. USC's victory completes the trifecta. &QL; 
Sign of the times &QL; 
It proved inconsequential Saturday, but comments made Friday by ASU
Coach  &UR; Pat Murphy still were creating a stir.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy believes USC's adeptness at stealing signs played a major
factor in pitcher  &UR; Ryan Mills' effectiveness against the Trojans in
two previous starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time, Ryan got rattled because they called
pitches,'' he said. ``They got their on-deck hitter really close to
the plate and their guy in the first base box calls pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of affected Ryan, plus he really wasn't pitching
well at that point. The second time, he kind of blocked it out and
just pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said that ``Ryan was tipping his pitches and our catcher
was tipping some things, too. USC is great at it (stealing signs).
They get them from all different angles and they practice it. It's
something that they've perfected, and it's part of the game. In
college ball, there's really not much you can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   USC Coach  &UR; Mike Gillespie downplayed the comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're familiar with their signs,'' he said. ``We've
played each other six times, and we've been able to watch each
other play here. There are no secrets who can do what and how they
do it.'' &QL; 
And another thing &QL; 
Arizona State football Coach  &UR; Bruce Snyder and basketball Coach
 &UR; Rob &UR; Evans flew in for the game.
</P>
<P>
   _When  &UR; Aaron Kramer hit Ensberg in the second inning, it tied
the College World Series record of batters hit by pitches (24).
</P>
<P>
   _The 10-game attendance total of 204,361 was a College World
Series record.
</P>
<P>
   _ASU's  &UR; Andrew Beinbrink, Michael Collins and  &UR; Rudy Arguelles
were members of the all-tournament team. USC's  &UR; Wes Rachels was
named the Most Outstanding Player. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
