<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-OUTDOORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOVE, QUAIL NUMBERS RAISE HUNTERS' HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dove season doesn't open until early September and the Gambel
quail season opens in October, but already I'm getting excited.
</P>
<P>
   A good friend, Curt Rambo of Tonto Basin, called late last week
to report that he's seeing large broods of Gambel chicks following
their parents along the shoreline of Roosevelt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   That's more encouraging than you know, because he has probably
missed seeing a lot of birds because he's catching so many crappie
between peeks. For your information, the crappie are in 10 to 15
feet of water and holding near submerged vegetation, mainly
cockleburs.
</P>
<P>
   This is a bountiful year in the desert. A long dry cycle has
been broken by El Nino rains. The rains not only have helped
fishing (although bass fishing hasn't been all that great), but
also provided wildlife with exceptional habitat.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of birds, that abundant plant life provides abundant
seeds and cover and it spawns large numbers of insects that are an
important source of protein.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Engel-Wilson, small game biologist for the Arizona Game and
Fish Department, already has predicted an average or better Gambel
season. Average usually doesn't sound too good, but considering the
drastic decline in birds the past few years, it sounds wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   And because of the increased seed supply and stock tanks with
water, native mourning doves also should have a productive year.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean shooting will be that much better. It
might require some hunting for a change.
</P>
<P>
   In dry years, hunters can depend on agricultural areas for good
hunting. Doves flock to areas where there is a dependable supply of
food and water. They concentrate in agricultural areas where
irrigation supplies both.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Smith, migratory bird biologist for the department, said
reproduction probably will increase, but that doesn't mean large
populations when the shooting season begins.
</P>
<P>
   The birds born in April and May often leave the state before the
season and head south. Many of the available birds when the season
begins are part of a summer hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Monsoons can destroy nests and reduce the number of available
birds in particular areas.
</P>
<P>
   But the main thing is that good seed crops and more water allows
the doves to disperse. Doves should be scattered throughout the
desert.
</P>
<P>
   That means hunting them through scouting trips. Find areas with
mourning doves and keep watching them. Learn their flight patterns,
know where they are. Also find late-morning roosting areas.
</P>
<P>
   White-winged doves are another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said white-wings are more closely tied to agricultural
areas. They don't scatter into the desert. White-wings begin
migration in August, but there usually are a lot of them around
when the season opens.
</P>
<P>
   Arizonans who hunt migratory birds are required to have both a
hunting license and either a Harvest Information Program stamp or
HIP number on their license. This program is used to keep more
accurate records of migratory bird harvests.
</P>
<P>
   The stamps will be available on July 1, as will the numbers.
Both are free. The stamps can be obtained at any Game and Fish
office. For those who can't get to an office, the numbers are
available by calling (800) 938-5263.
</P>
<P>
   There should be considerable interest in those stamps this year
because it appears hunting will be good. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
