<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-CHASES-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION STATIONS REMAIN SPLIT ON COVERAGE OF LIVE EVENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bb) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Live television coverage of a man's suicide on a
freeway prompted outrage among viewers here in April. It also led
to an open discussion about whether it was time to rethink
standards and practices in news. KNBC received 2,000 complaints,
and called each of those viewers back to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   But a second incident quickly followed the first. On May 26, a
driver being pursued by police _ identified later as a 25-year-old
Los Angeles police officer reportedly distraught over a
relationship _ intentionally gunned her Chevrolet Suburban at a
freeway piling, killing herself on impact.
</P>
<P>
   The way the story was handled illustrates how various stations
are dealing with such incidents. Only one station _ KCBS-TV _
carried the event live, though KTLA and UPN showed tape of it
during their newscasts. KNBC did neither. Other stations did not
return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   After the April suicide, which occurred during ratings
``sweeps,'' several stations said they had become more cautious
about covering police chases. Jeff Wald, the news director at KTLA,
said his station is installing a device that will provide a
10-second delay between an event and its live broadcast. KNBC is
considering doing the same, and has installed a ``kill'' switch in
its helicopter so the pilot can cut away from a live broadcast
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Cohen, news director at UPN, and Larry Perret, news
director at KCBS, said the need to be vigilant during broadcasts of
police chases was reiterated, but no policies were revised. (Of the
recent incident, Perret said: ``It's news. So we carried the
news.'') And an effort by the Radio-Television News Directors
Association to gather Los Angeles television news officials to
discuss standards failed when no one expressed interest in the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think each news department and news management should make
their decisions of what they want to cover, how and when,'' Cohen
said. ``I'm not interested in having a consortium recommend to me
what we should or shouldn't do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
