<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CNN-MEDIA-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN HOPES FOR SYNERGY IN ITS `NEWSSTAND' SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is hard to know what came first _ the idea of partnerships
between Time-Warner's weekly magazines and Turner Broadcasting's
all-news network CNN, or the idea of changing CNN's humdrum
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   But when Time Warner Inc. and Turner merged in the fall of 1996,
both ideas began to percolate. And they really picked up steam a
year later, after CNN's chief executive, Tom Johnson, lured Richard
Kaplan away from ABC News to become president of CNN/U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan said he wanted to transform people's perceptions of CNN
as essentially all-news radio with pictures. To give the network
more depth and authoritative swagger, he decided CNN had to have
some ``must see'' shows in prime time, in addition to ``Larry King
Live,'' the network's highest-rated show.
</P>
<P>
   As a business proposition, too, Kaplan wanted to find a way to
hold onto those 1 million or so viewers who tune in to King's talk
show at 9 each weeknight _ most of whom tune elsewhere immediately
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting brainstorm made its debut Sunday night. ``CNN
Newsstand,'' a series of 10 p.m. news magazine shows, will mix the
expertise of some Time Inc. print magazines with CNN's television
resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newsstand: CNN and Time,'' anchored by Jeff Greenfield and
Bernard Shaw, will appear Sunday nights and be repeated Mondays;
Wednesday will bring ``Newsstand: CNN and Fortune,'' anchored by
Willow Bay and Stephen Frazier, and Thursday, ``Newsstand: CNN and
Entertainment Weekly,'' anchored by Ms. Bay and Judd Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's overall ambition, he said in an interview last week, is
to make CNN ``the default network'' for news aficionados, ``the
place they go first when they turn on the TV set.''
</P>
<P>
   That is already the case ``when there's a war or a crisis or a
calamity,'' he added. ``But when news isn't hot, we still want to
be the place news viewers go first. We want to have really smart,
news-oriented programming that people will make an appointment to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``appointment viewing'' has become a mantra for
programmers seeking to stand out in a world of 60 or 70 channels
and thousands of shows. But for serious news viewers, how many
appointments can be kept?
</P>
<P>
   At 10 p.m. alone, NBC's ``Dateline'' appears two nights a week,
ABC's ``20/20'' appears two nights, and CBS's ``48 Hours'' appears
once _ not to mention the 10 o'clock dramas that a serious viewer
might consider appointment viewing, like ``NYPD Blue,'' ``The
Practice,'' ``ER'' or ``Homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Sundays, when ``Newsstand: CNN and Time'' appears at 10
p.m., it will follow three other news magazines _ ``60 Minutes''
(CBS at 7), ``Dateline'' (NBC at 8) and ``20/20'' (ABC at 9).
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives believe this is where synergy will make a
difference. They think news-followers will be attracted by the
familiar names and reputations of magazines like Time, Fortune, and
Entertainment Weekly. ``It's a lot easier to get a show's mission
conveyed to viewers when you're associated with a well-known
magazine like Time,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Each show will have some stories developed by the magazine's
journalists and some by CNN's journalists. Eventually, Kaplan hopes
to have ``Newsstand'' programs seven nights a week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Rick comes from long form,'' said Roger Ailes, chairman of Fox
News Channel which, with MSNBC, is one of CNN's two rival 24-hour
news networks. ``He's a very talented long-form producer, so it's
natural for him to try to salvage a boring presentation of news
with special `appointment' shows.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN needs invigoration; its ratings have been stagnant, and in a
survey by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press,
being released Monday, only 23 percent of Americans surveyed in May
1998 said they watched CNN ``regularly,'' compared with 35 percent
in May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the news shows represented the most important and
most ambitious new steps taken by CNN since the creation of ``Larry
King Live'' in 1985 and ``Crossfire,'' an issue-and-debate program,
in 1982. Hiring Kaplan, he said, was ``by far the most important
decision I've made in my seven and a half years here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, who spent 17 years at ABC News, had helped re-invigorate
the ``Nightline'' program when he was its executive producer, from
1984 to 1989, and had created the ABC news magazine ``PrimeTime
Live'' after that. Johnson said he wanted CNN to have the same kind
of leadership _ innovative without being gimmicky or trendy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 1655EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980607.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMAIN-NAMES-ASSESS-8     06-07 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMAIN-NAMES-ASSESS-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: PUNTING AN INTERNET HOT POTATO 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration called it ``A Proposal to Improve the
Technical Management of Internet Names and Addresses.''
</P>
<P>
   But the report released on Friday by the Commerce Department was
much more than that. It had been long awaited by the Internet
community _ which these days means everyone from multinational
corporations to sandals-and-socks computer programmers to
grandmothers on America Online _ as the government's first real
attempt to specify a system of governance for the informally
organized global computer network born in federal laboratories
nearly three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   But after a year of intense study, peering into issues of
technology, trademark law, international politics, and competition,
the government turned to the Internet community and said: Here, you
do it.
</P>
<P>
   The government said it had decided to turn the management of
Internet domain names _ and thus the management of the Internet
itself _ over to an as-yet-unformed private corporation,
representing various Internet interests. That organization will be
responsible for fixing the escalating problem of assigning Internet
domain names _ the chaotic scramble for coveted cyberspace
addresses that was the impetus for the review in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Domain names and addresses are the computer network equivalent
of phone numbers, street addresses and trademarks, all rolled in
one. Each of the millions of computers connected to the Internet
requires a unique address, which enables electronic mail to get to
its intended destination and World Wide Web pages to be found in
what is rapidly becoming the world's main library. Each computer's
formal address is expressed as a series of numbers, for example,
166.84.0.209. But to make the addresses easier to use, companies
and individuals can ask to assign a name to the numbers, like
panix.com.
</P>
<P>
   The ``.com'' part of the address is called a top-level domain,
and it is roughly the equivalent of a telephone area code. The
current top-level domain system _ seven generic top-level domains
like .com and .org and .edu, plus a couple hundred two-letter
country codes _ was created when there were just a few hundred
computers connected to the Net. Nobody anticipated the phenomenal
growth of the Internet as a global network used by millions for
electronic commerce, communications and entertainment. Today, the
domain set aside for commercial activity _ .com _ is the largest
and fastest growing.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100,000 new commercial domain-name registrations
being added each month, the Internet is headed toward a traffic jam
that makes the overcrowding of phone area codes look benign.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than try to fix the problem by adding more top-level
domains, which it proposed doing in an earlier, much-criticized
draft of the report, the administration called for creation of a
private not-for-profit international corporation whose job it would
be to find a solution to the domain-name problem. If all went
according to plan, the new corporation would assemble an
international board of 15 directors from the private sector (the
report did not even specify how the board would be chosen, leaving
even that matter to the Internet community) and would begin
tackling the most fundamental questions about the future of the
global network by October.
</P>
<P>
   People hoping for more immediate action were left unsatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were going to do that, they could have done it a year
ago,'' said Carl Oppedahl, a patent and trademark lawyer in
Colorado, who has been a critic of the current system, which has no
formal structure for resolving domain-name trademark disputes. ``I
feel badly about the time delay. The Internet has not benefited
from having all these months go by.''
</P>
<P>
   The government reserved the right to overrule whatever choices
the private sector makes. And, while repeatedly professing its
desire to get out of the Internet oversight business, the
government left open the possibility that it might retain that
option until well into 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The government's proposal was bad news for those looking for
relief from domain congestion or seeking some improvement of the
current trademark dispute morass, and for dozens of domain name
registry businesses that had hoped to become rich selling names in
proposed new domains like .web, .inc, or .sex.
</P>
<P>
   But the government's network solution was good news for Network
Solutions Inc., the Virginia company that five years ago was
awarded an exclusive government contract to administer the .com,
.org and .net domains. When Network Solutions got the contract,
there was no fee to register names. Soon after, it got permission
to begin charging $50 for each name (recently reduced to $35).
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions' contract is supposed to expire on Sept. 30,
but the new report opens the possibility that the company will
continue to have a monopoly on the lucrative ``.com'' franchise
until the new corporation comes up with an alternative _ something
that everyone agrees will be no easy task. As a result, Network
Solutions' stock soared on Friday, up $6.75, to $39.25.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Viewed one way, the administration's decision to not make any
decisions was a vote of support for the Internet's old guard, which
has long argued that the Internet is capable of regulating itself
without government interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to read it as a victory for self-governance, a victory
for the Internet and a demonstration that the government has
developed a profound understanding of the way the Internet works,''
said Don Heath, president of the Internet Society, a trade
association.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed another way, the government looked at all the hulking
issues now pressing in on the Internet and punted. Critics say that
by essentially freezing the domain-name situation in its current
form for an indeterminate time, the problems facing the new board
will be even tougher when it convenes.
</P>
<P>
   Time was rarely a concern as the Internet grew organically from
its origins in the 1960s and 1970s. Keeping track of all the new
computers on the network, and all of the technical issues of the
emerging medium, was largely a volunteer effort. But in the early
1990s, when restrictions against commercial uses of the Internet
were relaxed, the environment changed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, millions of companies are investing billions of dollars
in Internet-related ventures. Millions of e-mail messages cross the
network every day, and it is rapidly becoming a conduit for much of
the world's telephone calls. Universities, grade school students,
farmers, scientists, lonely singles, traveling salesmen, busy
families, small businesses and giant corporations have come to
depend on it.
</P>
<P>
   Husbands and wives battle over domain names in divorce court,
companies pay six-figure amounts for rights to ``business.com'' and
``internet.com'' and million-dollar legal fees are increasingly
common in domain-name trademark disputes.
</P>
<P>
   With such large issues at stake, many people want a more defined
structure for the Internet _ not just an ad hoc group of
volunteers, albeit very diligent ones, running the show, as is
currently the case.
</P>
<P>
   The domain name issue is just one of many decisions that need to
be made quickly. Others include: Who is responsible for making
decisions? What parts of the structure are best left to the
marketplace, and what parts are best left to government interests?
In the latter case, whose government? Trademark law is based on
geography, while the Internet is the antithesis of geography. How
to reconcile?
</P>
<P>
   These are among the questions that the Clinton administration
expects a new, unformed, untested, international corporation of
indeterminate composition to answer as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is going to have to be accelerated because the
demand for domain names is astronomical,'' said Ken Stubbs,
chairman of the executive council of CORE, the Council of
Registrars, a group of more than 80 companies that handle
domain-name registrations for businesses and individuals worldwide
_and that all must funnel registrations to Network Solutions. ``If
domain names were ``800'' numbers or cell phone numbers, and
someone announced that there would be no more phone numbers issued
for 12 to 18 months, there would be concern.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
