<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING INDUSTRY HONORS ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Minn., N.J., N.Y., Ore., Texas, Utah, Wash.,
Italy, Sweden, U.K.)  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the fourth graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable
to some newspaper systems.) 
(bb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The advertising awards season continues in full swing as five
organizations have bestowed honors for television and radio
commercials, art direction, corporate citizenship and fragrance
advertising. Interestingly, many of those awards went to agencies
owned by Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   At the seventh annual show sponsored by the Association of
Independent Commercial Producers in New York, paying tribute to
work on television spots, Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners in San
Francisco won the most honors in the agency category.
</P>
<P>
   Goodby, Silverstein, a unit of Omnicom, received seven honors
for campaigns for clients like Hewlett-Packard Co. and Nike Inc. A
sibling Omnicom agency, BBDO New York, followed with six honors for
campaigns for such clients as the Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of Pepsico
Inc. and Visa USA.
</P>
<P>
   (AT)radical.media in Los Angeles and New York and Satellite
Films in Chicago, Los Angeles and New York won the most honors
among production companies, with eight each. Advertisers whose
commercials won the most honors were the Mercedes-Benz of North
America unit of Daimler-Benz AG and Nike, with four apiece.
</P>
<P>
   In the radio competition, FJCN/W&AMP;R in Salt Lake City took top
honors, winning the $100,000 prize for the best commercial, at the
seventh annual Radio-Mercury Awards presentation sponsored by the
Radio Creative Fund of New York.
</P>
<P>
   FJCN/W&AMP;R won the largest cash prize for a spot titled ``Lip
Ring,'' produced for a summer youth-pass program sponsored by the
Utah Transportation Authority. The humorous spot spoofed body
piercing.
</P>
<P>
   In the competition for the $20,000 Radio-Mercury Gold Awards in
five categories, Fallon McElligott in Minneapolis won in the humor
category for a spot for Miller Lite beer, sold by the Miller
Brewing Co. unit of Philip Morris Cos. Richards Group in Dallas won
in the nonhumor category, for a spot for Greyhound Lines Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In the music and design category, Outer Planet/Clatter and Din
in Seattle won for a spot for Brew Your Own Beer. In the category
of Hispanic commercials, Muse Cordero Chen &AMP; Partners in Los
Angeles won for a spot for the California Family Health Council.
And KUPL-AM/FM in Portland, Ore., part of the American Radio
Systems Corporation, won for spots produced by radio stations, for
a commercial for Clutch Doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Also, GSD&AMP; M in Austin, Texas, another Omnicom agency, won in
the public service announcement category for a spot for the Texas
Department of Transportation. And Keith Reinhard, chairman and
chief executive at DDB Needham Worldwide in New York, also part of
Omnicom, received the Radio-Mercury Lifetime Achievement Award.
</P>
<P>
   At the 77th annual Art Directors Club Awards in New York, the
New York and Venice, Calif., offices of TBWA Chiat/Day took top
honors, winning the most awards.
</P>
<P>
   TBWA Chiat/Day, owned by Omnicom, won six awards _ three in
Venice and three in New York _ for work for such clients as Apple
Computer Inc. and the Weather Channel, part of Landmark
Communications. Cliff Freeman &AMP; Partners in New York, a unit of
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC, followed with three awards for work for
clients like the Fox Sports Network, a unit of News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In a departure, the judges of the art directors awards agreed on
a best of show honor in only one category, graphic design. That
award was presented to Damien Hirst, the maverick British artist,
for the design of the book ``Damienhirst _ I Want to Spend the Rest
of My Life With Everyone, One to One, Always, Forever, Now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The awards for corporate citizenship, known as Good Eggs, were
presented by Advertising New York, the annual benefit event
sponsored by the American Advertising Federation, the Advertising
Club of New York and Advertising Women of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam New York won in the agency category, Price
Waterhouse in New York in the advertiser category and Scholastic
Inc. in New York in the media category. Publicolor, a nonprofit
organization that paints schools in inner-city neighborhoods,
received the Jack Avrett Good Egg Award, named after the late
co-chairman of Avrett, Free &AMP; Ginsberg who founded Advertising New
York. The winners of the third annual Good Eggs will be honored on
Thursday at the 1998 Advertising New York event at Rockefeller
Center in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And the Fragrance Foundation in New York presented its 26th
annual Fifi Awards for fragrance ads.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Herrera Perfumes in New York, a unit of Compar, and its
agency, Baron &AMP; Baron in New York, won the Fifi for the best
national print and television campaign for a women's fragrance, for
a scent named 212.
</P>
<P>
   The Fifi for the national men's advertising campaign of the year
was divided between two sets of winners. For ads for Acqua Di Gio
Pour Homme, the winners were the European designer fragrance
division of Cosmair Inc. in New York, part of L'Oreal SA, and its
agencies _ the Publicis unit of Publicis SA in New York, for the
print ads, and Baron &AMP; Baron, for the television commercials. And
for ads for the new Diesel men's fragrance, the winners were Exotic
Fragrances in Fairfield, N.J., and its agency, Paradiset DDB in
Stockholm, Sweden, part of Omnicom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
