<HEADLINE>
WHEN SCRABBLE MEETS MAH-JONGG  
 A BOX TO KEEP WATCHES WOUND   
 SNAP-OPEN FRAMES FOR EYEGLASSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    
 &HT;    This is the 50th anniversary of Scrabble, the classic spelling
game thought up by Alfred Butts, an unemployed architect, as he sat
in his fifth-floor walk-up apartment in Queens one night.
 &HT;    Is it possible that Butts' game can be improved? Pingsheng
Huang, an inventor in Towaco, N.J., thinks so.
 &HT;    Huang has patented a new type of word game that he describes as
a cross between Scrabble and the ancient Chinese game of mah-jongg.
 &HT;    His game, which he calls Magi Compo, uses 144 tiles, as does
mah-jongg. But mah-jongg tiles feature abstract symbols that have
to be matched up. Huang's tiles _ like those in Scrabble _ are
inscribed with English letters that are arranged to make up words.
 &HT;    But Huang's tiles are far more complex than those in Scrabble.
Each tile has not just a single letter, but also letter
combinations. A player can pick which combination of letters he
wishes to use. For example, he might draw a tile that has ``P,''
``PE'' and ``PER'' inscribed on it, and then draw a second tile
that has ``A,'' ``AL'' and ``AR.'' From these two tiles, he could
choose to form the words ``pear'' or ``pal'' or ``par'' or ``peal.`
 &HT;    The scoring system is also different, said Huang. In Scrabble,
players reap big points by using letters like ``x'' or ``q.'' With
Magi Compo, the longer the word, the bigger the score, with no
weight given to less-common letters or letter combinations. Huang
also includes a number of wild-card tiles that can be designated
whatever letter a player wishes.
 &HT;    Earlier this year, Huang, who is originally from China but has
lived in the United States since 1990, quit his job as a marketing
director for a computer company so he could promote his invention
full time. Last month, he visited China to line up a manufacturer
for the game, which he thinks will retail for about $50.
 &HT;    So far, though, Huang has not found an outlet to sell his game.
For inspiration, he might look to the story of Butts. Scrabble did
not come on the market until 1948 _ 10 years after Butts patented
it.
 &HT;    Huang received patent 5,556,102.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although battery-powered watches are the norm these days,
mechanical watches remain popular among timepiece connoisseurs.
Many of these are self-winding as the wearer moves his or her
wrist.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens if the watch is not worn for a few days? ``Once
it stops, it can be a pain to reset it,'' said Jeff Richards, an
inventor in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Richards has patented a battery-operated vibrating jewelry box
that will keep a watch ticking. ``The patent is on the motion
itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the jewelry box would sell for $250 to $350 but
that he hoped to persuade a watchmaker to give away the box with
high-end watches. ``That's reasonable if someone were to buy a
$10,000 watch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richards received patent 5,608,693.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   David Wedeck, a former television executive in Teaneck, N.J.,
has patented what he says is an inexpensive way to make a fashion
statement with eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
   His eyeglasses snap open at the point where the temple meets the
lens frame so that the same lenses can be used in several different
frames. The interchangeable frames can be either plastic or metal,
Wedeck said, and take less than a minute to snap out and put in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an inexpensive way to get yourself a variety of styles
and colors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wedeck, who said he would like to license his invention,
received patent 5,760,866.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
