<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HDTV-FCC-ART-(2TAKES)     06-07 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-FCC-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS ABOUND AS TELEVISION INDUSTRY MOVES TO DIGITAL
BROADCASTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic showing possible HDTV conflicts for consumers
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. A color photo showing Susan
Ness, an FCC commissioner, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204
or 1927.) 
(bb) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After more than a decade of planning, digital
high-definition television broadcasts are to begin in just a few
months, and so is the sale of HDTV sets.
</P>
<P>
   But the television industry is now conceding that most people
who buy one of these expensive new TV sets, ranging in price from
roughly $6,000 to $12,000, may face considerable difficulty
actually seeing the new crystal-clear programming. That is because
the first digital sets will be incapable of receiving any
high-definition programming if it comes in via cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really taken aback when I learned this,'' said Susan
Ness, a commissioner on the Federal Communications Commission. ``It
doesn't really make sense to me that this was allowed to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is just one of several problems that have become
apparent in the final weeks before the transition to digital
broadcasting begins. Among other difficulties, HDTV is incompatible
with most existing direct-broadcast satellite equipment, while in
some cities broadcasters are having trouble finding sites for
towers for the their new digital antennas. A new task force headed
by Ms. Ness will tackle that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-six network-owned television stations in the nation's 10
largest cities are scheduled to begin digital broadcasting by Nov.
1, and almost every major manufacturer of televisions plans to
introduce high-definition television sets by then.
</P>
<P>
   And although a few of the TV stations say they may not make the
deadline, it is the cable television problem that could raise the
biggest obstacle to consumer acceptance of HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the nation's television viewers are cable
subscribers, who typically receive their cable channels as well as
over-the-air broadcast stations through the cable system.
</P>
<P>
   And cable executives believe that most buyers of the expensive
new HDTV sets will probably be their most desirable customers _
subscribers to expensive premium services and pay-per-view movies.
But to receive the HDTV signals from local broadcasters, these
people will have to bypass their cable boxes and resort to a
television antenna if they have any hope of receiving
high-definition programming.
</P>
<P>
   And even that is not a guaranteed solution. In recent tests,
more than 40 percent of the homes using indoor antennas were unable
to pick up a digital signal broadcast from WHD-TV, the experimental
high-definition station in Washington. But the percentage was far
better for homes with roof-top antennas, and industry executives
argue that the problem will be diminished when commercial stations
begin broadcasting HDTV at full power.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, most people are cable subscribers. And through the
spring, the major cable companies have been arguing with the
broadcasters and Congress about whether their new digital set-top
boxes would be capable of receiving HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in recent weeks, the cable companies agreed to
manufacture the boxes so they can receive the broadcasters'
high-definition signals _ and digital programming transmitted by
some cable services, including HBO and the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But that was only half of the answer. The other half, the part
that was overlooked until it was too late, was how these signals
would be carried from the digital set-top boxes to the digital
sets. A special digital cable will be required.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the specifications for this cable _ the jacks into
which it plugs and the software for organizing the signal _ have
not been completed. As a result, none of the first generation of
HDTV's are expected to have the proper jacks to receive HDTV from a
cable box.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Green, president of Cable Labs, the research
organization that is coordinating inter-industry work on this
problem, said, ``Our little lab is pulling hard to get this done.''
But he said he did not expect the work to be completed until the
end of the summer _ far too late for the first HDTV sets that will
go on sale a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Ed Milbourn, manager of advanced television planning for Thomson
Consumer Electronics, the nation's largest TV manufacturer, said
that even if the work were finished today, ``it's about four months
too late.'' As it is, digital sets that include the new digital
jacks probably will not go on sale until late 1999 or 2000 _
``unless we want to guess what the specification will be, and
that's a pretty expensive thing to guess on,'' Milbourn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole system works on standards,'' he added, ``and without
a standard we had nothing to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Perry, director of marketing for another big TV maker,
Mitsubishi Consumer Electronics, said he expected demand for
high-definition products to be rather low at first, because of this
shortcoming and other problems. Anticipating the possibility of
angry consumers, Mitsubishi's literature for its high-definition
products includes a disclaimer noting that viewers will not be able
to receive high-definition programming from cable.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bonan, a senior vice president for Sony Electronics Inc.,
said the company had been holding back on the final design for its
first HDTV, hoping this problem could be resolved in time. Today,
however, ``the chances are rapidly dwindling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, each segment of the industry blames the other
for this problem. But Green said his lab would try things through
``an experimental approach'' to solve this.
</P>
<P>
   He did not elaborate. But one answer, several industry
executives said, might be to design a second converter box that
would be inserted between the cable converter box and the digital
TV.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea, Bonan said, might be a new stand-alone box that
translated the signal so it could be received through one of the
conventional jacks on the back of a TV. No one has suggested who
would build any of these boxes, though, or who would be expected to
pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   But the cable industry is not the only source of obstacles to
HDTV. About six million homes have direct-broadcast satellite
dishes. And these people _ proven early adopters of costly new
technology _ are expected to be heavily represented among the first
buyers of HDTV's.
</P>
<P>
   In January, DirecTV, the largest satellite company, announced
that it would begin broadcasting two channels of HDTV in the fall.
But more recently the company disclosed that anyone hoping to get
this new service would have to buy a new converter box _ and climb
up on the roof to replace their 18-inch satellite dish with a new,
larger model.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that an antenna is a very low-cost piece of
equipment,'' said Jeffrey Torkelson, a spokesman for DirecTV. ``We
will try to make it as convenient as possible for people to make
the change.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not viewers will be able to receive the broadcasters'
new digital signals, most of the big-city television stations that
are to begin their digital broadcasts by Nov. 1 seem to be on
schedule equipping themselves. In reports to the FCC last month,
only stations in Chicago, Detroit and New York said they were
having trouble, and in most the cases the problem was getting new
towers built to hold their digital antennas.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating that other cities might face similar problems, the
FCC set up a tower ``strike force'' last week headed by Ms. Ness to
help stations resolve their problems. ``For competitive reasons,
some broadcasters might not want to say publicly that they are
having problems,'' Ms. Ness said. ``In those cases we can help.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the rocky state of the transition to digital
television, Milbourn said: ``Is it going to go perfectly smoothly?
No. It's going to stammer and stumble at the start. But are these
new sets going to make spectacular pictures? That I can
guarantee.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
