u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      06-07 0422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unsettled weather will grip much of the Northeast. Low pressure
swirling off the New England coast will draw moist air into the
interior, resulting in ample clouds and showers. A few rumbles of
thunder are also possible. Highs will be more than 10 degrees below
normal. Brisk winds from the northwest will enhance the chill.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, high pressure will nose from the lower Great Lakes
states to the southeast coast. Sinking air currents will lead to
bright sunshine from the Deep South to the Middle Atlantic States.
Cumulus clouds will develop in the Appalachians, as rising warm air
mixes with chilly air aloft.
</P>
<P>
   A potent storm system will affect the middle part of the
country. A slug of moist air will be forced to rise over a dome of
cool air stretching from the northern Rockies to Middle West. The
result will be areas of light to moderate rain from Illinois to the
western High Plains. Embedded thunder is also expected. Clouds and
showers will steadily march through the Ohio Valley into Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry air to the south of the warm front will ignite several
clusters of thunderstorms across parts of Texas and the southern
Plains. Some storms will produce hail and damaging wind gusts.
Otherwise, seasonable warmth and fresh breezes from the southwest
will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   A pocket of cold air near 18,000 feet will help trigger patches
of mountain showers and thunder across much of the West. Valley
locations will have a mixture of clouds and sunshine. The Southwest
will be sunny and seasonably hot, while morning fog and low clouds
dot the Pacific coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Modern Chill
</P>
<P>
   For the past few days, record low temperatures for early June
have been set in many locations in the Plains and Middle West. Many
of the records that were broken date back to the early 1900s.
Modern air masses probably need to be colder than those of a
century ago to produce the same chill, especially in large
metropolitan areas. An ``urban heat island'' is created by the
activities and infrastructure of today's sprawling cities. At
night, this leads to temperatures that are several degrees higher
than the surrounding suburbs, where more extensive vegetation
retains less of the day's warmth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 1817EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980607.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-07 1547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA TALK: PERFUME BETWEEN THE PAGES; NBC LIFTS AD BAN; ANGRY
REPORTERS FILE SUIT; SOCKS AND BUDDY BETWEEN COVERS; WRITER BECOMES
PUBLISHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Magazine readers are by now blase about pages scented from the
samples in perfume advertisements. Beginning this fall, they will
find those and other samples in the editorial pages as well.
</P>
<P>
   The September issue of Allure, a beauty magazine published by
Conde Nast, a unit of Advance Publications Inc., will feature
cosmetic samples with some of its articles. The items, in enclosed
packets, will include perfumes, lipstick, creams and blushes from
such companies as Estee Lauder, Revlon and Prescriptives. The
October issue of Glamour will do the same. Each sample will be
clearly identified by the company it comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going from black-and-white TV to color TV,'' said
Linda Wells, the editor in chief of Allure. ``If you look at
photographed swatches of makeup, you can't make a leap between,
`OK, it looks good on the page, but how is it going to look on
me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wells described advertisers' reaction to the idea as
``absolute elation.'' Indeed, Robert Nielsen, the president of
Prescriptives, said: ``To have an opportunity to have an editorial
position from Allure _ I think it's extraordinary. We would expect
to see some wonderful, positive sell-through results.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wells said she was not concerned that readers might confuse
Allure's editorial features with advertisements. ``We're designing
the page the way we ordinarily design a page,'' she said. ``The
presentation of samples will not look in any way like an
advertising sample.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the idea originated on the business side of Conde Nast. It
was the brainchild of Catherine Viscardi Johnston, an executive
vice president in charge of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that advertisers are excited about this,
but we had to make the decision based solely on the editorial
merits,'' Ms. Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Johnston would not disclose the cost of the project, but she
said it was very expensive and that Conde Nast was regarding it as
a trial. While the cosmetics companies will provide the bulk
product at their own expense, the process of inserting the samples
into the magazines will be handled at Conde Nast's expense by
Arcade, a New York-based company that manufactures and prints
sampling technologies.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Ends Ban on `Dirty Work' Ads
</P>
<P>
   This weekend's update: The movie ``Dirty Work'' can buy
commercials on NBC after all.
</P>
<P>
   After a week of confrontation between an NBC executive and one
of the network's former stars, the president of NBC, Bob Wright,
decided to call off the advertising ban on the coming MGM movie. At
least one commercial for the movie will now appear on NBC next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the executive, Don Ohlmeyer, the president of
NBC's West Coast division, put out word that the network would not
accept commercials for the movie because it stars Norm Macdonald, a
former comedian on ``Saturday Night Live.'
</P>
<P>
   There was bad blood between the two: Ohlmeyer has been engaged
in an ongoing dispute with Macdonald over the decision to remove
him from his regular post as the anchor of the Weekend Update
segment on that show. Macdonald's reaction to that decision, in
appearances on ``Late Show With David Letterman'' and other
programs, angered Ohlmeyer.
</P>
<P>
   MGM was forced to change its media plan for the film, losing
some valuable exposure in such NBC broadcasts as the National
Basketball Association playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   According to NBC executives, Wright did not oppose Ohlmeyer's
original decision because he thought the commercials were only
scheduled to appear in an edition of ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear that MGM's commercials were dropped from
other NBC shows, Wright decided the situation had gone far enough.
He told the NBC sales department that if MGM called to repurchase
time on the network, they were to be told the network would agree.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Rich, the head of marketing for MGM, said that as soon as
he was informed of NBC's change of heart he immediately got in
touch with NBC's sales executives Friday to buy back the $500,000
commercial he had lost during the NBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted was a chance to get that spot back,'' Rich said.
The commercial for Macdonald's movie is now scheduled to appear in
Game 4 of the playoffs on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Sue Editor for Defamation
</P>
<P>
   Feelings among the laid-off reporters from The Arizona Republic
and its defunct sister paper, The Phoenix Gazette, were raw enough
before The Columbia Journalism Review quoted their former managing
editor as saying that most of those laid off were ``fat, lazy,
incompetent and slow.''
</P>
<P>
   The former editor, Steve Knickmeyer, had made the remark because
he was angered to discover that former Republic reporters had told
the author of a Columbia Journalism Review article that some of the
people were singled out for layoffs because their coverage
irritated moneyed advertising interests.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the article appeared in January, Knickmeyer
disappeared from the newsroom. But it may have been too late: Last
week, 18 of the laid-off reporters filed suit for defamation,
contending that the remarks were made ``in reckless disregard for
the truth and were calculated to cause severe emotional distress to
plaintiffs and damage their reputations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will defend the paper vigorously in the case _ we think
it's without merit,'' said David Bodney, a lawyer representing the
newspaper, which is being sued along with Knickmeyer and the
paper's owner, Phoenix Newspapers Inc., a unit of Central
Newspapers Inc. ``It's one thing to say whether the statements
should have been issued in a perfect world. It's another to hold
the newspaper liable for them under the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Pets Get Their Own Book
</P>
<P>
   It takes a warm and cuddly puppy.
</P>
<P>
   At least on the first lady circuit, where Hillary Rodham Clinton
has decided to follow in the tradition of her predecessor and
fellow celebrity author, Barbara Bush, by producing a book devoted
to the first pets _ in this case Socks and Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, which published Mrs. Clinton's first book and
nonfiction best seller, ``It Takes a Village,'' approached her with
the idea for the book, ``Dear Socks, Dear Buddy,'' which will
include an introduction from Mrs. Clinton and a selection of ``50
to 60 candid photographs'' of the first pets along with samples of
their fan letters from children.
</P>
<P>
   In their letters, the young writers probe for political candor
from the first pets with questions such as: ``Who do you like best?
Clinton? Mrs. Clinton or Chelsea?'' Or there's the standard
suffocating-security question: ``Does the Secret Service cat bug
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's proceeds from the book _ which will be published
in November _will be donated to the National Park Foundation, a
nonprofit organization that is allied with the National Park
Service and raises funds for the parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been having discussions with Mrs. Clinton about possible
projects since her first book,'' said Carolyn Reidy, president of
Simon &AMP; Schuster's trade division. ``She had this idea about doing
something with Socks, and then Buddy came into the picture. So we
asked questions about whether there were lots of letters to the
pets and they said there were tons. And she leapt on the idea of
letter-writing being a positive for children.''
</P>
<P>
   `Simple Abundance' Is Now a Press
</P>
<P>
   Writers write, publishers publish. But the Warner Books unit of
Time Warner Inc. is giving Sarah Ban Breathnach, best-selling
author of the women's spiritual guide ``Simple Abundance,'' the
opportunity to do both.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual arrangement, Ms. Ban Breathnach was named
publisher of a new imprint, the Simple Abundance Press, which will
issue four books a year in the booming spirituality and lifestyle
market, starting next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Warner, Maureen Egen, said Ms. Ban Breathnach
would share in the proceeds of the books, which she will acquire
but not write. Instead, she will choose topics and find authors
``who otherwise might not have a chance to be published.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ban Breathnach knows about that. ``Simple Abundance'' got 30
rejections before a Warner editor recognized its promise. After
Oprah Winfrey endorsed it, the book landed on the best-seller list
where it has remained for 113 weeks, a longevity enjoyed by only
three or four books that come out in any given year.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Warner will publish 750,000 copies of Ms. Ban
Breathnach's further spiritual musings, ``Something More,'' and
Warner has three other books under contract.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ban Breathnach's imprint points to a recent trend, in which
publishers are agreeing to new kinds of financial partnerships with
brand-name authors.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Stephen King left his longtime publisher to be a
partner with Simon &AMP; Schuster's Scribner division for his next
three books, taking a smaller advance in exchange for a share in
the profits. Three months ago, the Pocket Books unit of Simon &AMP;
Schuster made a similar deal with the novelist Clive Cussler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
