<SLUG> BC-FOOD-MUNCHIES-MOVIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE MUNCHIES BEYOND POPCORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TERESA TALERICO  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Forget popcorn, hot dogs and soda. Dump those
Raisinets. Nachos? Too cheesy.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you hit your local movie theater to catch
``Godzilla'' or ``Hope Floats,'' you might just be ordering a
single tall latte.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, theaters have introduced a new line of
snacks to tempt filmgoers who give thumbs-down to traditional movie
munchies.
</P>
<P>
   The options range from coffee and cookies, espresso and
biscotti, fancy fruit drinks and bottled water to self-serve
gourmet candy.
</P>
<P>
   If they haven't already, they're probably coming soon to a
theater near you.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman Fisher, a spokesman for Cineplex Odeon, which has 15
theaters in the Seattle area, said movie houses are competing with
video rentals for business. Owners are looking for new ways to lure
customers back into those seats. Movie theaters make profits almost
exclusively from their snack bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to expand is through concessions,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Many small, artsy movie houses have for years sold
unconventional snacks to appease their customers' bohemian tastes.
But the treats began appearing in mainstream theaters about five
years ago, when many began featuring self-serve bins of bulk candy,
Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   This appeals to customers who are more selective but still have
a sweet tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're hungry for something sweet, but not wanting a
half-pound box of Dots, that's the way to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alternative beverages soon followed, including coffee, bottled
water and juices.
</P>
<P>
   At Cineplex Odeon's Meridian theater in downtown Seattle, you
can buy espresso, latte, mocha and even hot tea at Cine Cafe, a
coffee stand near the regular concessions. The cafe also sells
cookies, brownies and biscotti.
</P>
<P>
   But the Academy Award still goes to popcorn. Cafe vendor Edward
Isakson leaned on the counter and admitted that business is slow.
Not far away, a couple loaded up on more traditional snacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people come to the movies, they're thinking popcorn and
candy,'' he said. ``You don't drink tea.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher conceded that options like movie cafes haven't grabbed
the multitudes quite yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still popcorn and soda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like betting on an underdog at the Oscars, this battle to seduce
moviegoers with new treats is an uphill one.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of filmgoers prefer popcorn, soft drinks and
candy, according to Cineplex Odeon studies. Movie theaters now want
to entice the 20 percent who historically turn up their noses at
conventional concessions.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, wooing filmgoers can be even more difficult,
considering the city's often pretentious tastebuds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A city like Seattle is, without question, more discriminating
than most cities,'' Fisher said. ``The best example is the
coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Cine Cafes are springing up all over Cineplex Odeon theaters.
But downtown Seattle is the only one that uses a local coffee
roaster _ Seattle's Best Coffee. ``We take into heavy consideration
where we're plopping a new theater,'' Fisher said. ``And Seattle is
the king of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Tastes vary depending on geographic region.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, nachos are still among the most popular movie
snacks, he said. In smaller towns, nothing beats a hot dog at the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   At several Seven Gables Landmark theaters, which specialize in
art movies and independent films, java and pastries have long been
a staple for the more intellectual crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Metro and the Seven Gables, both in Seattle's University
District, have served espresso and cookies for 10 years. Customers
love it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They range from college students to grandmothers, but they're
all looking for literary films,'' said Teri White, a district
manager for the theater chain. ``They're not looking for the
crash-up, bang-up. And they're much more likely to buy a cookie and
coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so at the Meridian on a recent afternoon. Whether they were
watching ``Woo'' or ``Deep Impact,'' most moviegoers seemed to
prefer hot buttered popcorn and Sprite to chocolate-chip cookies
and Earl Grey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's habit,'' said Patti Fiorito as she paid for her popcorn
before going into ``He Got Game.'' ``I can't watch a movie without
it. With all that butter, I think it's addictive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
