<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-OWEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE KITCHEN ARTISTRY STAVES OFF HUNGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is sometimes a slight disagreement between the Kelvinator
Ko-pilots in our kitchen. It's not that we fight over the last pork
chop on the platter. What we have is a philosophic debate as to who
is ``supposed'' to get the last pork chop on the platter.
</P>
<P>
   Alice argues that I get it because I'm bigger, although not
necessarily smarter. I feel everything should be evenly divided. I
can't immediately lay my hands on the document, but I believe
disposition of the odd pork chop is dictated in our marriage
license. What I think it says is, ``Whack! Right down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't admit it. But I believe that, down deep, Alice is
convinced she will not be considered a serious artist unless she is
allowed to starve a little.
</P>
<P>
   Writers do not have this compulsion, a fact I can prove to
anybody willing to take a position behind a journalist in a buffet
line. (In one of my first communications school lectures, the
professor described a ``journalist'' as ``a newspaperman out of a
job.'')
</P>
<P>
   Aha! But all newspapermen think they are covering The Last
Supper and accordingly handle their knives and forks like fencing
foils.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``starving artist'' usually appears on posters
advertising the sale of $49 oil paintings at the Holiday Inn. I'm
pretty sure Alice would actually starve before she would paint an
eagle clutching the American flag as it flies over Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Monet painted precious few American eagles. The same can be said
for Cezanne. Not only did they avoid starvation, they enjoyed long,
leisurely meals and took great interest in recipes and their
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Alice discovered these biographical insights and actually tested
a couple of recipes reprinted in the ``Cooking Journals of Claude
Monet.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few adjustments she recently produced these meals.
</P>
<P>
   Monet's Mixed Vegetable Soup
</P>
<P>
   2 cups dried green or yellow peas
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 leeks, white parts only, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups turnip greens, stems removed. (Monet called for sorrel)
</P>
<P>
   1 head of iceberg lettuce, trimmed and shredded (or 3 cups other
lettuce or spinach)
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs chervil (or parsley)
</P>
<P>
   2 medium-size potatoes, peeled and cut in chunks
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 can low-fat evaporated milk
</P>
<P>
   Monet's recipe called for sorrel, which tastes like a cow's cud.
We substituted turnip greens, but you could use fresh spinach. We
used evaporated milk instead of cream because, well, to tell you
the truth, Monet looked like he was putting on a few pounds in his
later years.
</P>
<P>
   Soak dried peas in water for two hours, then drain. Heat oil in
pot, add onion, leeks, turnip greens, lettuce and chervil. Cook
over low heat, stirring with a wooden spoon, until the vegetables
are well-coated; do not let them brown.
</P>
<P>
   Add the dried peas and potatoes, then the broth. Season with
salt and pepper and bring to boil. Cover and simmer over very low
heat for at least 2 hours. Puree in food processor (eat your heart
out, Claude) return to heat and add milk. Reheat, stirring.
</P>
<P>
   Serves six to eight.
</P>
<P>
   As you may have noticed, this soup contains no pork chops or
veal shanks, so division is not a consideration. The following
recipe contains portions of fish and they are so good I might try
to sneak the extra piece into my bowl, when Alice isn't looking.
</P>
<P>
   Cod Soup Cezanne
</P>
<P>
   1 pound true cod
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 medium potatoes, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 leeks sliced (white part only)
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon powdered cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   One-eighth teaspoon saffron (or one-quarter teaspoon turmeric)
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Cut the fish into at least 8 pieces. Dust with flour. Heat oil
in a skillet and saute the fish, turning once, until firm. Remove
to a warm plate before it browns.
</P>
<P>
   Pour any oil remaining in pan into a soup pot. Add the potatoes
and cook about 10 minutes covered, or until almost cooked through.
Remove to a warm plate. To the same pot add the leaks, pepper,
cloves, garlic, parsley, saffron and bay leaf plus whatever flour
is left over after you dusted the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Stir the pot once or twice, as the flour browns. Add the broth,
bring to a boil, then cover and simmer 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Slide the fish and potatoes into the soup and reheat. This
should serve six modest appetites or four starving artists.
</P>
<P>
   John Owen writes ``The Intermediate Eater'' weekly for the P-I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980607.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8157 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-07 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO SLOTS FOR TOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Confession time: At the age of 13, I was avidly
watching a crap game in the stairwell of Joan of Arc Junior High in
New York when a monitor caught us. Penalty: no diploma or handshake
from the principal at graduation. Ma gave me hell.
</P>
<P>
   That lesson may be at the root of my lifelong passion against
gambling. I believe that casino operators are predators; that
state-sponsored lotteries make a mockery of public policy; that
politicians who are on the take from gambling interests are
wallowing in the occasion of sin, and that Indian tribal leaders
who have turned aboriginal Americans into a croupier class are
contemptible. (Nothing wrong with gin rummy at home.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite decades of my banging a moralizing spoon against the
highchair, gambling is growing. The sucker who used to be born
every minute is now born every second. The recent ``Powerball''
lottery was front-page news in respectable newspapers; nobody did a
story on the kids who went unfed providing its huge payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Now that organized gambling has become a $25-billion-a-year
industry, it is buying protection from politicians. An independent
counsel has had to be appointed to find out how high-bidding Indian
tribes may have corrupted the Interior Department.
</P>
<P>
   Not all pols are vulnerable. Liberals like Ralph Nader know that
gambling is a tax on the poor; social conservatives like Gary Bauer
know that gambling substitutes get-rich-quick dreaming for the work
ethic. That leaves political pragmatists _ centrists with their
hands out _ as target for the gambling lobby's influence.
</P>
<P>
   The gamblers own a piece of the GOP's Trent Lott, from
casino-controlled Mississippi; he killed a Senate bill that would
have ended the ability of gamblers to deduct their losses, thereby
saving high-rolling millionaires $4 billion over a decade. And the
gambling lobby recently bought a chunk of Al Gore by kicking in
$700,000 for Democrats on the VP's last visit to the labor bosses'
pro-gambling orgy in Las Vegas. (Al's next fund-raiser: bingo for
Buddhists?)
</P>
<P>
   But one underfinanced little guy is driving the lobby up the
wall. He is Tom Grey, a Methodist minister from Illinois who
organized the National Coalition Against Legalized Gambling.
Although Big Gambling's largess is buying influence in Washington,
Grey's outfit has helped local citizens' groups keep beating the
casino interests in state after state.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, for example, where I usually vote straight right
wing, Gov. Parris Glendening, a Democrat, stands fast against
invasion by slot machines. If his Republican opponent goes soft on
slots or takes contributions in gamblers' chips, I'll split my
ticket this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Grey and friends badgered Congress into forming a National
Gambling Impact Study Commission. Although the gambling lobby was
able to infiltrate it with a Nevada casino operator and others
grinding casino-union axes, the majority report next June might
prove damning _ and make it more embarrassing for pols to skim
profits of riverboat roulette wheels.
</P>
<P>
   What should worry candidate Gore and GOP leaders most about the
commission's studies is ``slots for tots.'' If gambling is treated
merely as part of theme-park entertainment, harmless fun for the
whole family, then every casino and tribe will explode into the
Internet with their own Web sites. Every wired classroom desk would
become a casino table teaching a pernicious philosophy of
something-for-nothing.
</P>
<P>
   What worries the gambling industry most, however, is the
commission's investigation into gambling addiction. If it turns
out, as many psychiatrists suggest, that a significant number of
gamblers are compulsive, and were encouraged in their addiction by
the lure of casino advertising, then the gambling industry might
find itself in the position of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, among the legions of trial lawyers who were left out
of the great tobacco contingent-fee bonanza, some are staring at
the deep pockets of casinos, tribes, lobbyists and even
municipalities that may be shown to be partly responsible for the
damage caused to people's lives by taking advantage of a gambling
compulsion.
</P>
<P>
   Picture a smooth trial lawyer pointing to his gambling-ruined
client, holding aloft a damning government document supported by
scientific testimony _ what are the odds on his winning a bundle?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 1854EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
