<DOCNO> NYT19980607.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-C&AMP;W-ART-775(2     06-07 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-C&AMP;W-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRITISH PHONE GIANT LOOKS TO AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphics are being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a rapid international education it has been for Richard
Brown, who traveled 500,000 miles last year and can hand out his
business card in any of 17 languages. Before becoming chief
executive of the far-flung global telecommunications company Cable
and Wireless PLC two years ago, Brown, an American, had been
outside the United States only twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to run this company having never been to England before
in my life,'' he said in an interview last week at the company's
headquarters in London.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Brown's focus has again turned to the United
States. Seeking to expand Cable and Wireless' presence in this
country, where so far it mainly resells long-distance service to
business customers, he agreed two weeks ago to buy a large portion
of the Internet business of MCI Communications for $625 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, if approved by regulators, would give Cable and
Wireless one of the largest Internet operations in this country.
Yet such are the vagaries of the agreement, which is pegged to
MCI's pending acquisition by Worldcom, that Cable and Wireless
might conceivably wind up with a much larger chunk of the MCI
business _ or walk away empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown, who in two years has doubled Cable and Wireless
profit, is such an optimist that he speaks of the MCI deal as if it
were already done. ``We now are the first non-U.S.-based company to
be a tier-one Internet provider,'' he said. ``We have leap-frogged
the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, like almost every executive in the telecommunications
industry, is deeply concerned these days about ``the others.'' The
industry is engaged in a race for financial, technical and
operational bulk in the widespread belief that the global
communications market will end up being dominated by a handful of
international giants.
</P>
<P>
   And Cable and Wireless may be the quintessential midsize
competitor in that race. Despite its global reach, it is smaller
than each of the three largest long-distance companies in the
United States _ AT&AMP;T, MCI and Sprint _ with $11.6 billion in
revenue last year. And it is larger than only the smallest of the
regional Bell companies, US West.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and Wireless actually had more revenue last year than
Worldcom, which recorded $7.4 billion in sales. But Worldcom has
something that Cable and Wireless, even under the energetic Brown,
has been less able to generate: buzz and momentum on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom was able to make a $37 billion bid to acquire MCI
because Worldcom's shares trade at such a hefty multiple to
earnings _ about 50 times estimated 1998 earnings, compared with
about 25 for Cable and Wireless' American depository receipts. That
allowed Worldcom to base its acquisition of MCI largely on stock
and to avoid the prospect of devastating its future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But the continued regulatory uncertainty over Worldcom's bid for
MCI threatens Brown's plan to become a major Internet competitor in
the United States and take the next step toward the front of the
industry's dash for mass.
</P>
<P>
   MCI would be selling the Internet unit to Cable and Wireless to
help streamline its takeover by Worldcom. But the European Union's
competitiveness commissioner, Karel van Miert, seems to have agreed
with foes of the MCI-Worldcom deal, principally GTE, that selling
part of MCI's Internet holdings to Cable and Wireless would not
sufficiently address antitrust concerns about MCI and Worldcom's
combined power in the Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   And the Justice Department, which is also reviewing the proposed
acquisition and is working closely with van Miert, has not yet
indicated whether it plans to endorse the deal with Cable and
Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   All this could imperil Brown's Internet aspirations. But one
outcome might be his emerging with an even bigger slice of MCI's
strong Internet operation. That is because Worldcom is under
increasing pressure to complete the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is not finished by the end of the year, Worldcom
must pay about $1.6 billion in cash to MCI, and MCI could simply
walk away. Failing to complete the MCI deal would also be a big
blow to the image of Bernard Ebbers, Worldcom's chairman, on Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   One easy way for Worldcom to win approval of the acquisition of
MCI would be to sell its own big Internet operation, called Uunet,
which Worldcom gained as part of its acquisition of MFS
Communications in 1996. But Uunet is Worldcom's crown jewel, and
its chief, John Sidgmore, is now Worldcom's vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   So if regulators tell MCI and Worldcom to relinquish more
Internet assets, the additional pieces would almost surely come
from MCI. And the most likely beneficiary might be Cable and
Wireless.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, MCI has agreed to sell Cable and Wireless its business
of providing wholesale Internet access to other Internet service
providers, as well as 22 Internet nodes, or central traffic-control
hubs.
</P>
<P>
   And while Cable and Wireless does not have an automatic right of
first refusal to any additional Internet properties that MCI may
agree to sell _ like the unit that provides cyberspace access to
large corporations _ analysts say it is almost inconceivable that
Brown would not be given the first opportunity to bid on such
units, should MCI decide to sell.
</P>
<P>
   And according to people close to Brown, it is almost
inconceivable that he would not be interested. Cable and Wireless
is already one of the 10 largest long-distance carriers in the
United States, providing its service almost exclusively to business
customers. Adding Internet access to its menu would be attractive
to corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Brown is no stranger to wheeling and dealing. Ever
since he arrived at Cable and Wireless after nearly three decades
in the American telecommunications business, including a stint as
vice chairman of Ameritech, the company has been buying and selling
like a commodities trader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been at the helm we've done 19 deals valued at over
$18 billion,'' Brown said with pride.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Cable and Wireless has always been a company of
scattered interests. It came into being in 1929 through the merger
of many privately owned British companies, including Eastern
Telegraph Co., which laid the first submarine cable route from
Britain to India in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   The company remained private until it was nationalized in 1946
under the postwar Labor government. Its status changed again under
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, when the government sold half of
the company to the public in 1981 and the other half by 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But privatization was not a panacea for Cable and Wireless. When
Brown first arrived, the company was struggling. The previous
management team, led by a former politician, Lord Young, and by
James Ross, most of whose experience had been in the oil business,
had been forced out by the board.
</P>
<P>
   One of Brown's biggest deals was also the most controversial _
selling part of Cable and Wireless' largest overseas holding, Hong
Kong Telecom, to China's state telephone company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were approaching the July 1997 handover of Hong Kong to
China from Britain,'' Brown said. ``Here we were with 15,000
employees in Hong Kong and a disproportionate amount of our revenue
and earnings in China. How do we stabilize that situation?''
</P>
<P>
   His answer: Sell 5.5 percent of Hong Kong Telecom to China
Telecom for $1.2 billion, increasing China Telecom's stake in Hong
Kong Telecom to 13 percent and leaving Cable and Wireless with 54
percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   In a move still criticized by some analysts, Brown also agreed
to transfer additional shares in Hong Kong Telecom to China Telecom
at a future date, which will make Cable and Wireless just an equal
partner with the Chinese company.
</P>
<P>
   But in Brown's approach to the global telecommunications game,
control may ultimately be less important than clout. Many industry
executives predict that the result of all of his financial
maneuvering may one day be the sale of Cable and Wireless to
another company. Bell Atlantic Corp. and GTE have been mentioned on
Wall Street as potential suitors.
</P>
<P>
   According to some analysts, a merger could be just what the
company needs to get to the next level. ``They are too small to
take on the high end of the market without a partner,'' said Andrew
Harrington, an analyst for Salomon Smith Barney in London.
</P>
<P>
   Brown himself seems quite open to the concept of his company's
being acquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets of the next century are outside of the United
States,'' he said. ``How does an American company become global?
Construct those networks yourself? It would take our lifetime. If
you buy most European companies, you get a country. Buy British
Telecom, you get Great Britain. Buy Telstra, you get Australia.
We're the only one you can buy and get the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he quickly added, ``But I'm not hanging a `for sale' sign
above the company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
