<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NBC-SHAPIRO-ART-1     06-07 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-SHAPIRO-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHOSE `DATELINE' IS RESHAPING PRIME TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927. A graphic is being sent to NYT graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Neal Shapiro does not own one of the biggest homes in Beverly
Hills; nor has he found work for Farrah Fawcett, Joan Collins or
Heather Locklear, and his production company has never been traded
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But check out the fall prime-time television schedule: Neal
Shapiro is currently the closest thing in the business to Aaron
Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   Spelling, producer of such fare as ``Charlie's Angels,'' ``The
Love Boat'' and ``Fantasy Island,'' once controlled seven hours of
ABC's schedule. In the fall, Neal Shapiro, executive producer of
``Dateline NBC,'' will be in charge of five hours of NBC's schedule
_ all ``Datelines.''
</P>
<P>
   That news magazine program has become the most pervasive
generator of ratings on the hit-laden NBC schedule, having grown
from one struggling hour in 1993, Shapiro's first year at NBC, to
four hit hours this last season.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to network television's inveterate penchant for imitating
success, ``Dateline'' is also remaking the landscape of prime time,
as recent events demonstrate. ABC has reconstituted its three news
magazines under the single title of ``20/20'' and hopes to extend
that franchise to other nights. And CBS executives continue to
ponder the option of adding a second weekly edition to the gold
standard of the genre, CBS News' ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Shapiro's guiding hand _ and not always to the delight of
media critics _ ``Dateline'' has rewritten the rules of the news
magazine show. Among the touches ``Dateline'' has added to the
format: blanket coverage of breaking stories in the news, like the
O.J. Simpson trial; expanded single-hour coverage of stories, like
the fate of an entire Bedford-Stuyvesant fourth-grade class from
the 1980s, and short regular features like ``Time and Again,''
which quizzes viewers on what year certain events took place.
</P>
<P>
   As its success has grown, ``Dateline NBC'' has also reshaped how
entertainment executives view news magazines. They once considered
them a news division nuisance, which interfered with their
entertainment feifs. Now they increasingly see the news magazine as
a highly useful, multinight franchise that can ease the pressure to
fill 22 hours with more expensive entertainment shows.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the NBC News magazine program has become the
target of frequent critical attacks for focusing more on ratings
than news value, for bending too much toward tabloid-style stories
like the Simpson trial and the JonBenet Ramsey murder and for
opening the door to influence from the entertainment division.
</P>
<P>
   Don Hewitt, the producer who invented the news magazine with
``60 Minutes,'' has said of the plan to expand his program, ``Do
you want a second edition of `60 Minutes' or do you want `Dateline'
with the name `60 Minutes' on it?'' He said that ``Dateline''
reminded him of ``the Dole pineapple family that went to Hawaii as
missionaries; they went to do good, and they did well; `Dateline'
is doing very well for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The man at the center of this programming revolution and
journalism debate is a softspoken, 40-year-old news producer, who
once thought having even two news magazines was a daunting
prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had the one show, I thought, `no one had ever done two
_ I wonder if I can do it,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many people thought he could not, including a friend from the
ABC News magazine program ``Prime Time Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me; `This will never work. You can't do two shows
as well as one. You'll never find enough people. There's no way to
find enough stories to be on twice a week. You'll crash and
burn,''' Shapiro recalled.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Shapiro said, ``Going to two turned out OK;
two to three wasn't that hard; three to four was little more
demanding, but news is our friend.''
</P>
<P>
   A typical week of ``Dateline'' shows, like last week, includes
interviews (the actor Harrison Ford, the former football player and
convicted gambler Art Schlichter), an investigative piece (an
examination of accusations of sexual harassment at Ford Motor Co.),
a light story (the conflict between two office workers over the
$100,000 prize from a Pepsi bottle) and an update of a continuing
story (a look at the Ramsey case).
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said one main element of the success of Dateline had
been its willingness to drop everything and chase like a thundering
herd after whatever story is driving daily coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the number of stories ``Dateline'' did on the
Simpson case, Shapiro said, ``I have no idea _ dozens and dozens.''
It was the same after the death of Diana, Princes of Wales. But
Shapiro notes that many of these stories provided information not
found anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Using a newspaper term, Shapiro said that ``Dateline''
aggressively ``seeks out sidebars, millions and millions of
sidebars'' to stories in the news. ``We do stories on the things
people are talking about,'' he said. ``The stories that are in the
public consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   That approach has led to the most consistent criticism of
``Dateline:'' that the show builds its big audiences by pandering
to popular taste.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro is more thoughtful than outraged about this suggestion.
``People say I'm cynical and I'm just trying to get the audience
in. Is there an element of that? Yeah. But along the way I give
them a good story and they come away saying, `I didn't know
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for the charge that the show is filled with soft features and
tabloid-style stories, Shapiro said, ``I think that's a little
loaded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, there are some things that are perfectly legitimate and
appropriate to do, and I'm kind of puzzled why some things are OK
in the printed world, but not on television,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that print magazines frequently do featurey reports in
the backs of their books, not unlike ``Dateline'' features like
``Discoveries,'' which has chronicled such developments as a man
who invented a pizza box that will not collapse.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The viewer-friendly touches have made it easier, Shapiro said,
to attract an audience for extended reports on topics that only
``Dateline'' could have developed into attention-getting reports.
He cited a full-hour show about layoffs at AT&AMP;T that followed three
employees for a year after they had been dismissed and a report
that used a hidden camera to document the prejudice that the
disabled face in finding a job, getting an apartment and getting a
seat in a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro's most pointed defense of the quality of journalism at
``Dateline'' is a simple enumeration of awards the show has piled
up: three Emmy awards this last year; eight the year before; nine
National Headliner Awards; a Robert Kennedy Journalism Award, and a
DuPont Silver Baton.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about `Dateline' is we're always trying to
redefine the genre,'' Shapiro said. ```60 Minutes,' because of its
tradition, for so long defined the news magazine as three pieces
and Andy Rooney. What's lost is when Don Hewitt started, he was the
pioneer. He was this aggressive young guy, and the traditionalists
who did documentaries said: `What is he doing? Documentaries need
to be an hour. You can't do three in an hour. What are these ambush
interviews that he's doing? It's outrageous.' Don has been an
incredible pioneer, but that doesn't mean it should stop there.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Dateline'' under Shapiro is all the more
remarkable because the show came so close to extinction _
self-immolation, really _ in 1993 when, under a previous producer,
it rigged up an explosion of a General Motors vehicle for a report
on truck safety.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in an abject apology, the departure of the
previous producer, Jeff Diamond, and the resignation of the
president of NBC News, Michael Gartner.
</P>
<P>
   When Andrew Lack, the new president of NBC News, arrived, he
said he had found ``a place in shambles.'' He had never met
Shapiro, who was thrust into an effort to salvage ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro had been recruited from ABC, where he was the broadcast
producer for ``Prime Time Live.'' (In 1992 he won a George Polk
Award for foreign reporting.) A native of Albany, N.Y., Shapiro
began his journalism career as a part-time newspaper correspondent
before moving to television. He had numerous assignments at ABC
News including stints producing for ``Nightline'' and ``World News
Tonight.'' He is married to the ABC correspondent JuJu Chang.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro rather quickly moved ``Dateline'' past its truck-story
humiliation, helping to encourage Lack to pursue his conviction
that a single news magazine could broadcast multiple versions each
week.
</P>
<P>
   Now Shapiro is managing a machine that churns out 600 to 800
stories a year. About 200 stories are in some stage of production
at all times. The show's staff, about 80 in 1993, will reach 320
when the fifth edition begins in September.
</P>
<P>
   But the costs of adding a new edition of ``Dateline'' are less
than they would be with a new magazine show, or a drama. ``There
are all sorts of economies of scale,'' Shapiro said. Among the
biggest: The two anchors, Jane Pauley and Stone Phillips, work
every edition.
</P>
<P>
   News magazines cost about two-thirds of the $1.2 million average
for a drama. But they stay in production all summer, which pushes
up costs.
</P>
<P>
   Advertiser support is especially good for ``Dateline'' because
the show attracts the young adult urban viewers most favored by
advertisers. Two editions, Tuesday and Monday, are among the 15
top-rated shows on television. The Friday edition wins its time
period most weeks, and ratings have grown for the Sunday edition.
</P>
<P>
   Don Ohlmeyer, who heads NBC's entertainment division, said:
``There is no show more important to us than `Dateline.' I look on
`Dateline' as a hit show the same way I look on `E.R.' as a hit
show.''
</P>
<P>
   From Shapiro's point of view, ``Dateline'' also provides all the
drama any viewer could want. The ideal ``Dateline'' story, he said,
should have ``a good character in conflict over something. That's
the essence of what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro clearly has a feel for keeping audiences in their seats
_ and one reason, said one senior NBC executive, has been his
willingness to listen to programming advice from the entertainment
division.
</P>
<P>
   The executive said Shapiro had reserved some especially potent
stories for sweep rating months and has occasionally moved stories
around depending on what audience he was told was likely to be
available. Monday, for example, is the night for stories tailored
to female viewers because the show follows a lineup of comedies
aimed at women and competes with football on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said he never had made any decision based on advice from
NBC entertainment executives. ``I do the stories I want to do. I've
never been told what to do. I tell them what I'm doing,'' he said.
``They'll call and say about a certain story: `That was a great
piece, we need more like that.' They may take that as instruction.
I consider it an attaboy.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure of adding one more night to his already busy week
does not seem to faze Shapiro. ``I never say no,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, if other magazines copy us, or `60 Minutes,'
I don't care. If our contribution is saying we put the news back
into the news magazine, I'm delighted about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
