<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 CULTURE NOTES: THREE NIGHTS OF CABARET; DANCE FESTIVAL OPENS; ART
FAIR IN SWITZERLAND; KOREAN GALLERY AT THE MET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's party time beginning Monday night at Town Hall.
To be specific, it's ``A Swell Party,'' a three-night celebration
of cabaret presented by the Mabel Mercer Foundation, starting at 6
p.m. Opening night brings performances by more than a dozen
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the 106th anniversary of Cole Porter's birth will be
celebrated by singers like Ann Hampton Callaway, Liliane
Montevecchi, Steve Ross, Elaine Stritch, Margaret Whiting and Julie
Wilson. And on Wednesday, the centennial of the birth of Gertrude
Lawrence will be commemorated by performers like Celeste Holm,
Andrea Marcovicci, Phillip Officer and K.T. Sullivan. (212)
980-3026.
</P>
<P>
   In Steps
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating its 65th anniversary with 13 world premieres and a
tribute to Israel's 50th anniversary, the American Dance Festival
opens on Thursday at Duke University in Durham, N.C. The 42
performances, through July 26, begin with a world premiere by
Pilobolus Dance Theater, set to a new score by the jazz composer
Maria Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   Among other companies in the festival are Urban Bush Women, the
Merce Cunningham Dance Company, the Parsons Dance Company and the
Paul Taylor Dance Company, as well as troupes from France, Israel
and Argentina. Israel's anniversary will be celebrated on July 20
and 21. Information: (919) 684-6402.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Watch
</P>
<P>
   More than 260 galleries from Europe, North America, Asia and
Australia will exhibit more than 1,000 works of 20th-century art
when the 29th annual international art fair known as Art Basel
opens on Wednesday in Basel, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The works of artists like Marc Chagall, Chuck Close, Max Ernst,
Jacques Lipchitz, Joan Miro and Robert Rauschenberg are expected to
draw some 50,000 visitors before the show at the Messe Basel
Fairground ends next Monday. Besides painting, photography, prints,
mixed media, video and installations, Art Basel will present for
the first time a section devoted solely to large-scale sculpture.
Information: 011-41-61-686-2020.
</P>
<P>
   New and Old
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Completing a 30-year plan for the establishment of
major new galleries of Asian art and the enrichment of its Asian
collection, the Metropolitan Museum of Art will open its first
permanent gallery dedicated to the display of the arts of Korea
Tuesday. The Arts of Korea Gallery will draw from the museum's
collection to display paintings, ceramics, sculpture, metalwork and
lacquerware spanning 1,500 years.
</P>
<P>
   The inaugural exhibition, ``Arts of Korea,'' consisting of 100
works and continuing through Jan. 24, includes art from the
museum's collection and loans from major public and private
collections, and 22 Korean national treasures. Information: (212)
535-7710.
</P>
</TEXT>
