<HEADLINE>
MOYA DOMINATES CORRETJA TO TAKE FRENCH OPEN CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bb) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Carlos Moya flopped down, flat on his back and
vulnerable for the first time after playing the leading man in a
2-hour, 18-minute performance. It was a 6-3, 7-5, 6-3 mauling of
his outclassed friend and opponent, Alex Corretja, that proclaimed
Moya, the flashy bandanna-clad Spaniard, the latest French Open
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of Arantxa Sanchez Vicario's defeat of
Monica Seles in the women's final on Saturday, Moya put the
finishing touches on a Spanish sweep of this Grand Slam event's
singles titles on Sunday, a coup that last occurred when Sanchez
Vicario and Sergi Bruguera monopolized the event in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot explain with words how happy I am,'' said Moya, the
young man from Majorca, who improved his ranking to fifth in the
world. Moya recalled coveting this title since he saw Bruguera
pocket the first of his back-to-back French Open championships in
1993. ``When he was handed the trophy, I was wondering, you know,
how I'd love to be there,'' Moya said. ``It was like jealous, but
in a good way. And five, six years later, I'm here in his place. So
as I said before, I don't have any way to describe this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did have a novel way of reacting to it.
</P>
<P>
   Having just captured his first Grand Slam event championship in
the second all-Spanish finale here, the 21-year-old Moya did what
came naturally: he lay down on the clay that had served him so well
for the past two weeks, did a shocked little shimmy, and made a
rust-colored snow angel on center court at windblown Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment you're thinking about all the people who helped
you since I was a little kid, all the people who trust you in the
bad moments,'' said Moya, whose parents brought a 20-member
cheering section from Majorca. ``This victory is for all these
people, especially for my parents, my family, my coach.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the 12th-seeded Moya, who rehearsed for Sunday's
manifesto by coming out of nowhere to reach the 1996 Australian
Open final, was done playing in the dirt, the 14th-seeded Corretja
had vaulted over the net and was waiting to hug him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw how happy he was, I was happy for him,'' Corretja
said. That is not unusual for the Spanish men: Here in Paris, Moya
and Corretja were part of a posse of 19 Spanish men who wined and
dined together, and the 24-year-old Corretja said they fully
intended to celebrate together Sunday night. ``Maybe if I lost to
another guy I would not feel like this, but as I said before, even
if I win or if I lose, I'm happy. I think we should make a big
party, because this is not normal,'' he said of Spain's domination
here.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The diplomatic Corretja, a player best known for double-faulting
at match point of his 1996 U.S. Open quarterfinal against a
retching, cramping Pete Sampras, also pointed out the sportsmanship
he and his compatriot displayed Sunday. There was not a line
dispute in the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult for us both, but we tried to be professional
about it,'' he said. ``But we didn't need the chair umpire or the
linesmen because every time we were giving the balls to each other.
Next time we meet, we just play by ourselves because I just trust
him. I never check the mark. He never check the mark with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Together again on the presentation podium, Moya and Corretja
clowned around with Pele, who geared up for his VIP duties at the
World Cup soccer festivities by helping to hand out the trophies.
Once the formalities were completed, Pele handed each tennis player
a soccer ball and grabbed Moya's trophy for himself before being
enticed into some soccer gambits.
</P>
<P>
   First Moya, and then Corretja, headed the ball back-and-forth
with their idol, but they found no success when they tried to coax
the secret behind his soccer prowess out of him, not with Spain and
Brazil about to get their World Cup campaigns under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extra motivation to win,'' Moya said, joking, ``because
I knew he gave the trophy to the winner. He's been the greatest
ever soccer player.''
</P>
<P>
   Moya put himself in the proper frame of mind for fighting for
this title by choosing to receive and then immediately breaking
Corretja, who played a nervous opening set and never quite found
his bearings for the rest of the match. Corretja could not keep his
groundstrokes sufficiently on the mark to prevent Moya, whose
forehand is as oversized as his baggy NBA-style shorts, from
running around his backhand and thwacking out forehand winners.
</P>
<P>
   Corretja converted only two of nine break chances, no contest
against Moya's 6-for-19 conversion rate. Moya, the more versatile
of the two, won 18 of his 107 points at the net, served five aces
and kept his performance free of double-faults.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't handle the wind,'' Corretja said. ``I was the whole
time trying to find the ball. He played much better than me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS:
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Moya received his championship trophy, called the
Mousquetaires Cup, from Don Budge, who in 1938 became the first
player in the sport's history to win all four Grand Slam events in
a calendar year and earn the Grand Slam of tennis. ... In the
women's doubles final, second-seeded Martina Hingis and Jana
Novotna defeated top-seeded Lindsay Davenport and Natasha Zvereva
6-1, 7-6 (7-4). In the men's doubles final, which was postponed by
rain on Saturday, top-seeded Jacco Eltingh and Paul Haarhuis fended
off unseeded Mark Knowles and Daniel Nestor 6-3, 3-6, 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
