<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8204 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNOWMAIDEN-BALLET-REV     06-07 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOWMAIDEN-BALLET-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVISH $1.2 MILLION PRODUCTION SUCCEEDS TO A POINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A color photo showing dancers Nina Ananiashvili and Angel
Corella is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bb) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The expense of producing new full-evening story
ballets these days has nearly guaranteed the demise of the genre.
But American Ballet Theater persists. On Friday night, the company
presented the much-anticipated New York premiere of ``The Snow
Maiden'' at the Metropolitan Opera House. Was the lavish $1.2
million production worth the gamble? The answer is a slightly
qualified yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Snow Maiden'' looks spectacular, a thing of shimmering ice
palaces and exquisite costumes, designed by Desmond Heeley. There
was accomplished and persuasive dancing from two casts of dancers,
on Friday and Saturday nights. And at the ballet's heart, there is
a haunting and provocative tale that has been imaginatively
realized in the choreography of Ben Stevenson, the artistic
director of the Houston Ballet, which produced ``The Snow Maiden''
with Ballet Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson drew his plot from Aleksandr Ostrovsky's
``Snegurochka'' (``The Snow Maiden''), an 1873 play based on Slavic
folk stories, with incidental music by Tchaikovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Though the play was unsuccessful, Ostrovsky's story was reborn
in the Rimsky-Korsakov opera of the same name and in subsequent
ballet versions. This production is set to music by Tchaikovsky,
assembled by John Lanchbery from the Ostrovsky original and a wide
variety of other unnamed scores.
</P>
<P>
   It is not difficult to understand the lure of the story, given a
central character with the tantalizing pathos of the doomed and
dooming sylphs and maidens who populate the 19th-century ballet
classics.
</P>
<P>
   Here, that character is a beautiful, childlike woman made of
snow and ice who has the misfortune to fall in love with a man and
who melts to a wisp of dress at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Stevenson decided to create this version while
working on a ballet production of ``Peer Gynt'' three years ago.
This ``Snow Maiden'' is ballet as Ibsen might have choreographed
it, a story of dashed idealism and love and faithless society that
is more searingly dark than the grimmest of fairy tales.
</P>
<P>
   For all the lilting snow maidens, leaping reindeer and cavorting
villagers, it is an intimate story. And it is in the ballet's most
intimate moments that Stevenson's creation comes most fully and
fascinatingly alive.
</P>
<P>
   Those moments include pas de deux and solos danced by the Snow
Maiden, by Misgir, with whom she falls in love, and by Coupava, his
fiancee. The repeated furlings and circlings of the wedding pas de
deux suggest, for example, the orderly, cozy, loving world Misgir
and Coupava have made for themselves. The final pas de deux is
harrowing, with the Snow Maiden's drooping, falling body clinging
to Misgir as she melts.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Ananiashvili, who danced the title role in Houston and on
Friday at the Met, was a figure of poignant loneliness, her
fluttering hands and childlike playfulness recalling Carla Fracci
as August Bournonville's Sylph and the long, tapering line of her
body suggesting hope.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Kent's Snow Maiden, on Saturday, was a metaphor for light
and ice, an effect enhanced by Duane Schuler's magical lighting.
Ms. Kent's maiden came closest to human frailty as she hurtled
excitedly off into another world in a silver sled.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson has given his lead characters the kind of acutely
observed specific qualities that are seldom seen in ballet. Misgir,
in varying degrees, is not entirely smitten with the maiden. He is
not the lost, dreaming poet hero of Romantic ballet but a sturdy,
kind-hearted peasant who soars and spins like the nobleman
Stevenson has made him, at least as portrayed by Angel Corella on
Friday and a heart-rending Guillaume Graffin on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Coupava, as played by Kathleen Moore on Friday, is a bit of a
scold with the upper hand in this relationship, turning lyrical in
the pas de deux and her central solo. Ashley Tuttle, replacing an
injured Martha Butler on Saturday, made Coupava's determination and
happiness evident through her dancing alone, without much effort at
acting.
</P>
<P>
   Father Frost, brilliantly performed by Victor Barbee on Friday
and Michael Owen on Saturday, spends a lot of time falling and
sitting on the ice, establishing his forest people's affinity for
their chill world. He scrambles tellingly across the ice on all
fours, giddy at first and later fearful as he sees his beloved
daughter race off to annihilation.
</P>
<P>
   The production's great problem is the length and tedium of its
group and ensemble dances and the Snow Maiden's opening solo.
Unlike the divertissements and group dances of late-19th-century
story ballets, on which this ``Snow Maiden'' is modeled, they
seldom advance the plot or suggest anything about classical ballet
itself. Like some of the Tchaikovsky score, they are numbingly
incidental-feeling, with folk accents that look like the threadbare
ballet conventions they have become. ``The Snow Maiden'' cries out
for editing.
</P>
<P>
   But the dancing was of a high order in a lead cast completed by
Joaquin de Luz, John Selya and Sascha Radetsky as the village's
bounding drunks, and Christina Fagundes, Veronica Lynn, Ekaterina
Shelkanova, Maxim Belotserkovsky (on Friday), Parrish Maynard (on
Saturday), Giuseppe Picone and Keith Roberts as Misgir's friends.
Irina Kolpakova, a company coach, was quietly spectacular as the
Czarina, amusing casting given Ms. Kolpakova's former prominence as
a Soviet ballerina. Hiller Huhn assisted Stevenson in setting the
production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
