<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON-HEALTHCARE-700     06-07 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-HEALTHCARE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEMEDICINE GETTING TEST IN EFFORTS TO CUT COSTS OF TREATING
PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Iowa, Kan., Mass., Texas, Va.)  (bb) 
 By KATE MURPHY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Universal health care is a reality in one part of the United
States: prison.
</P>
<P>
   By law, inmates are guaranteed medical treatment. And with the
ranks of prisoners rising an average of 8 percent every year since
1990, providing that treatment is an expensive proposition.
</P>
<P>
   To control costs and improve security, a handful of states are
trying out telemedicine _ health care via telecommunications. With
government agencies, managed-care providers and legislators
watching, these programs are serving as a proving grounds for
broadening the use of telemedicine.
</P>
<P>
   After two decades of limited acceptance as a way to provide
health care to people in areas where there are few doctors,
telemedicine has been embraced by prison officials as a way to
minimize the costs and dangers of transporting inmates to hospitals
when they need advanced or specialty care.
</P>
<P>
   Most prisons are in rural areas, requiring inmates to travel
hours, shackled and under guard, to see a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``With telemedicine, prisoners don't even have to leave their
cellblock,'' said Dr. Steven Viegas, a hand surgeon who oversees
the prison telemedicine project at the University of Texas Medical
Branch at Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1994 and covering roughly 100,000 inmates in 12
prisons, the University of Texas telemedicine program is the
nation's oldest and largest. Yearly, the online network saves about
$300,000 in prisoner transportation costs alone.
</P>
<P>
   Prisons generally have infirmaries operated by primary-care
doctors or nurses. When an inmate needs more than rudimentary care,
the jail's medical personnel use specialized equipment _ like
electronic stethoscopes and otoscopes _ to transmit real-time audio
and high-resolution video images of prisoners to physicians at
hospitals hundreds of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Both the off-site doctor and patient have two monitors so they
can see each other as well as their own images.
</P>
<P>
   The hardware costs $60,000 to $100,000 and charges for
high-speed phone lines are around $1,000 to $1,500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Although statistics are hard to come by because prison
telemedicine programs are so new and so few, administrators say
their economic benefits go beyond savings in transportation and
security. Anecdotal evidence suggests that inmates are more likely
to seek care when they do not have to travel to see a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lower threshold to getting care probably reduces the
likelihood of more expensive acute care later on,'' said Dr.
Michael Kienzle, associate dean for clinical affairs at the
University of Iowa Hospital in Iowa City, which last year began to
extend electronic health care to 4,000 inmates in four state
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Telemedicine also streamlines the delivery of specialty care.
For example, the University of Virginia Health Sciences Center in
Charlottesville schedules weekly online clinics for jail inmates in
such medical specialties as dermatology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The specialist sits at a computer and sees patients from
different units all across the state, one after another,'' said
Richard Settimo, deputy director of the University of Virginia's
office of telemedicine, which opened last year to serve 5,000
inmates in five state prisons. ``The ability to block-schedule
prisoners saves a whole lot of time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   The on-site medical staff follows the treatment recommendations
of the specialist. If the treatment is complicated, the prisoner is
then transported to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The efficiency of prison programs has not escaped the attention
of public and private interests responsible for providing health
care to people who are not behind bars. Based on its success in
treating prisoners, the University of Virginia received a grant
from the Commerce Department in October to set up a $1.2 million
telemedicine network to serve Medicaid patients in the state's
rural southwestern region.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the University of Iowa's prison project led to a
joint venture with a private managed-care company, Help Innovations
Inc. of Lawrence, Kan., to provide home health care using
telemedicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are able to point to our experience in the prisons as
evidence of the effectiveness of telemedicine,'' Kienzle said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two managed-care companies _ Partners Health Care System Inc.,
based in Boston, and Kaiser Permanente, based in Sacramento, Calif.
_ had prison programs in mind when they recently established
telemedicine networks as an inexpensive way to serve isolated,
homebound elderly and chronically ill subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew of the effectiveness of prison care systems and used
them as a basis for carving out our own application,'' said Eric
Menn, corporate manager of Partners' telemedicine division.
</P>
<P>
   The military uses telemedicine, as well. For example, the United
States Army has a $30 million system in place in Bosnia, linking
the medical staff there to physicians at military bases around the
world. Its benefits are aimed less at controlling costs than at
keeping doctors out of harm's way, though.
</P>
<P>
   The prison telemedicine systems have provided arguments for
reimbursing the expenses of telemedicine when it is used to care
for the general population. Currently, telemedicine is generally
not covered by Medicare or private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony from prison administrators before a Senate ad hoc
committee on telemedicine led to the inclusion of a provision in
last year's Balanced Budget Act that will require Medicare to pay
for telemedicine delivered to certain rural areas found to have a
shortage of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision makers have definitely been watching what's going
on in the prisons,'' said Deborah Dakins, editor of Telemedicine
and Telehealth Networks, a bimonthly magazine that tracks the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Positive preliminary results from these ``test cases'' have
modestly increased access to telemedicine in both the public and
private health care sectors, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take more time and more data before it is
commonplace for patients outside prison to stick out their tongues
and say ``ahhhh'' for a computer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
