<DOCNO> NYT19980607.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8216 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIFE-INSURANCE-DECLIN     06-07 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFE-INSURANCE-DECLINE-ART-(1,000)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS TURNING AWAY FROM TRADITIONAL LIFE INSURANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Calif., Texas)  (Duplication warning: Also moving in `f' category) 
(ART ADV: A graphic on trends affecting the life insurance industry
is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans looked at life insurance for generations as a
cornerstone of their family finances, as crucial as a home mortgage
or savings for college.
</P>
<P>
   But as people have begun to live longer and worry more about
running out of money in retirement, millions of Americans have
started either to do without life insurance or buy less. Instead,
they have been pouring money into investments like mutual funds and
variable annuities, which they hope will take them comfortably
through their golden years.
</P>
<P>
   The shift in attitudes, which has been building gradually for
years, has now reached a critical mass, sending life insurance
sales into something of a free fall and radically changing how
insurance companies do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby boomers are hitting their 50s and, as always, they
think they are going to live forever,'' said Michael Weiss, an
author and marketing analyst who has written about consumer
lifestyles. ``Because they don't trust Social Security or Medicare
being around, they really feel they have to plan financially for
their future. And they're going for the best return they can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Many young people have also gotten caught up in what financial
specialists call ``wealth accumulation,'' pumping spare money into
401(k) and other retirement plans _ hoping, effectively, to
self-insure against any catastrophe. Fifteen years ago, Americans
bought 17.7 million new policies; last year, they bought 11.1
million, a 37 percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   The change, industry experts say, is being driven by several
trends that reflect the hybrid nature of life insurance, which not
only can provide financial protection for survivors but also serve
as a vehicle for saving.
</P>
<P>
   More and more people are deciding that insurance is simply not a
good investment. A growing number of people are concluding that
financial protection can best be achieved with an inexpensive term
policy. And in an age of two-income families, still others are
determining that protection is less necessary because they have the
means to look after themselves.
</P>
<P>
   All of these trends have combined to cut sharply into the sale
of traditional whole-life insurance, or so-called permanent life
policies, which have fulfilled both the investment and protection
functions and long served as the industry's most profitable
product.
</P>
<P>
   The sales decline has become deep enough to transform the
insurance business and to play a key role in the recent wave of
mergers sweeping the industry. Many insurers are now focused on
selling investment products and financial advice, and some have
gone so far as to drop life insurance from their names. One
company, Sun America Inc., which used to be known as Sun Life
Insurance Co. of America, now offers no death benefits at all
except in conjunction with mutual funds and other investments.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the insurance industry argues that traditional
coverage remains as valuable as ever. ``Our lives have a way of
taking unexpected turns,'' said John Dolan, a spokesman for the
American Council of Life Insurance, a trade group in Washington,
``and permanent life insurance provides a long-term safety net.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, plenty of insurance is still being sold.
Middle-class Americans with young children and mortgages continue
to be regular customers, although often buying much less coverage
than their parents. Big policies, those with a face value of
hundreds of thousands of dollars and up, are selling briskly,
providing protection for the affluent against estate taxes. And the
number of new term policies is rising as premiums continue to fall
for this basic coverage, which provides protection for a specified
period and has no saving feature. As a result, the total face value
of new policies of all kinds is up.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, less than half of all American households now have
life insurance beyond the often minimal coverage provided by
employers, according to an estimate by A.M. Best &AMP; Co., an
insurance ratings agency. That compares with nearly three-quarters
of the households in the 1960s, says another industry group, the
Life Insurance Marketing and Research Association, known as LIMRA.
</P>
<P>
   While a decision to go without insurance, or with less coverage,
would have been seen as highly imprudent not long ago, it is now
increasingly viewed as the sensible thing to do, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people have become better informed, they have found that
the life insurance policy was not a very good way to save money,
particularly in the current bull market,'' said Roy DiLiberto, a
financial planner and former insurance agent in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Whole life includes an investment feature that typically pays
just 4 percent to 5 percent annually. For years, financial planners
have urged clients to buy much cheaper term coverage and put the
savings in premiums into mutual funds or individual stocks. Last
year, a third of all new policies were term, up from 23 percent in
1994, according to LIMRA.
</P>
<P>
   But big demographic changes are also at work. The nature of the
American household has changed substantially and with it the need
for financial protection.
</P>
<P>
   People are marrying and starting families later and now often
buy their first life insurance in their 30s rather than in their
20s. And, increasingly, they are abandoning their policies as they
move into their 50s and 60s, pay off their mortgages and see their
children graduate from college. These shifts have added to the
popularity of term life policies.
</P>
<P>
   But the rise of the two-income family has made some people
question the need even for term coverage. Many two-income couples
without children and with little debt have calculated that the loss
of one income would not be a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the Ozzie-and-Harriet world of working dad and
stay-at-home mom may have needed life insurance,'' said Rick
Adkins, a former insurance agent who is now a co-owner of Arkansas
Financial Group, a financial planning firm in Little Rock, Ark.
``But with dual working couples, many are making the rational
decision that they don't need the insurance and should be more
invested in the stock market.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Edward Miller, chief executive of Equitable Cos., which had its
origins in insurance but now makes most of its money from
investment products and services, says that rising affluence has
changed the nature of the protection many families seek. ``There is
less concern about a financial crisis if something happens to
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More people with lower incomes have also been going without
insurance, analysts say, at least partly because agents, looking
for bigger sales with bigger commissions, have stopped knocking on
their doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no agents calling to say, `Let's sit down around
your kitchen table so I can sell you a $30,000 insurance policy,'''
said Mark Trencher, a senior researcher at Conning &AMP; Co., which
specializes in insurance research.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many insurance companies no longer call their
salespeople agents. Instead, they are financial planners, offering
life insurance as only one possibility among an array of mutual
funds and annuities. Since Miller took the helm at the Equitable
eight months ago, he has stepped up efforts to recruit lawyers and
accountants for his sales force.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Martindale, a financial planner in San Luis Obispo,
Calif., says that her goal for her clients, most of whom have
household incomes of $70,000 to $80,000, is for them to, in effect,
provide their own insurance. ``The idea,'' she said, ``is to have
enough in investments to take care of the surviving spouse and
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Most young couples will not have enough in savings to do that
immediately, she said. So she tells them to buy term life. Yet many
choose to skimp.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Merrill, a 32-year-old chemical analyst in Austin, Texas,
with a 3-year-old daughter and an infant son, is one example. He
has about $50,000 in term life, or not quite enough to cover a
year's salary _ less than a third of what Ms. Martindale usually
urges. But Merrill said that his wife would soon be returning to an
office job and that he was confident she would be in no danger
financially if he died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any fears for her well-being,'' Merrill said,
``because she's as capable as anyone I know in terms of earning a
living.''
</P>
<P>
   What worries him, though, is the distant future. ``We're not
counting on getting anything in retirement from Social Security,''
he said. ``So we're going to have to rely on our investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Struggling to cope with the new attitudes, the life insurance
industry has been gradually remaking itself. While the biggest
companies still have millions of life insurance policyholders on
their books, the fastest-growing companies have been emphasizing
the sale of variable annuities, mutual funds and financial advice.
</P>
<P>
   Variable annuities are investments in mutual funds that are
designed to make regular payments in retirement. But they also come
with protection against a market downturn and in that sense
function as something of an insurance substitute. In exchange for
fees that are somewhat higher than a regular mutual fund, an
annuity guarantees that the owner's survivors will receive no less
than the owner's initial investment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most breathtaking revolutions has taken place at Sun
America. In the eight years since it changed its name and sold all
of its traditional life insurance units, the company, with assets
that now exceed $35 billion, has plunged headlong into variable
annuities and mutual funds. For the last decade, its stock has been
one of the best-performing issues on the New York Stock Exchange,
rising an average of 42 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Most big insurers, like Prudential Insurance Co. of America,
Metropolitan Life and New York Life and Equitable, still offer a
basket of life insurance choices. But they, too, expect much of
their future growth to come from meeting the investment needs of
the 76 million baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of whole life policies have also suffered because of
lawsuits brought by millions of policyholders who said they were
misled by agents about how much their coverage would actually cost.
Several companies have paid tens of millions of dollars to settle
these suits.
</P>
<P>
   At some companies, life insurance has come to be almost an
afterthought. At Nationwide Life Insurance Co., for example, 90
percent of the revenue last year was from annuities, according to
A.M. Best. That figure included sales of fixed annuities, a less
popular variety that promises to pay a fixed amount of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp-elbowed competition for new _ and different _ business
has driven insurers to cut costs, reorganize operations and look
for merger candidates. Last year, for example, Metropolitan Life
bought a company specializing in 401(k) plans and another that
concentrated on annuities. Some companies, including Prudential,
have been sharpening their focus by selling businesses that do not
fit in with their new profiles as financial services companies. And
a few, like Jefferson Pilot, are actually moving more heavily into
traditional life insurance, betting they will pick up business that
others are eschewing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet amid all the movement by consumers from insurance to other
investments, some financial planners are sounding a note of
caution. Permanent life insurance may look like a poor cousin
during a bull market, these planners say, but it will take on a
different aura entirely when the bull turns to a bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young people who feel they don't need insurance have
only seen the best part of investing,'' said Richard Hammel, a
planner in Brentwood, Tenn. ``They haven't been through the hard
times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
