<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC AGREES TO LET OBSERVERS INTO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also KOSOVO-REBELS.)  
(lb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia has
agreed to allow diplomatic observers to enter and move through the
province of Kosovo, where Serbian troops and policemen have been
attacking the ethnic Albanian majority, senior administration
officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The first observer missions could take place as early as Monday,
the officials said, after weekend negotiations in Belgrade, the
Serbian capital, between Milosevic and the U.S. ambassador to
Macedonia, Christopher Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hill will be allowed to escort the chief negotiator for the
ethnic Albanians, Fehmi Agani, and presumably bring journalists
along to view areas where the Serbian military and police have been
operating, the officials said. Milosevic's forces have prevented
foreigners from traveling in Kosovo, Serbia's southernmost
province, and Agani was denied access to those areas on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials stressed that the new agreements did not
absolve Milosevic of responsibility for using fear and force to
drive residents from villages along Kosovo's border with Albania,
an operation apparently intended to prevent the infiltration of
arms and new fighters from outside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   (In Kosovo, members of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army said
Serbian troops were removing bodies from areas observers might
visit and concealing other evidence of their attacks.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethnic cleansing, whether as a goal or a tactic, is still a
crime,'' a senior U.S. official said. ``We cannot ignore that
extraordinarily grave events occurred last week, and we cannot
allow Milosevic to get a breather because some diplomatic observers
are let in.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said Washington and its allies continued to insist
on the withdrawal of Serbian special police and Yugoslav army units
from Kosovo and on full access for other foreigners. ``Just having
some diplomatic observers who come back and say, `Gosh, this is
terrible and they've destroyed the place,' isn't sufficient,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks, Milosevic, the former president of
Serbia, has ordered a crackdown against the ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo and, in particular, against the Kosovo Liberation Army,
which is fighting for independence. Western governments do not
support independence for Kosovo, fearing that it would reopen the
Balkan ethnic and religious caldron.
</P>
<P>
   At least 250 people have been killed, 10,000 refugees have fled
into Albania and 50,000 people have been displaced from their
homes, according to an estimate given in London on Sunday by the
British foreign secretary, Robin Cook, but the West has done little
except plan new meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic over the past week has crossed the
threshold,'' said Cook, whose government holds the rotating
presidency of the European Union. ``The use of tanks, of artillery,
of the might of the military army against civilian centers of
population is wholly unacceptable within the modern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook and Prime Minister Tony Blair have decided to push
Washington and the West ``to a much tougher policy, both
politically and militarily,'' a senior British official said. Blair
told his Cabinet on Thursday that the use of force may be necessary
to get Milosevic to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The British are circulating a draft Security Council resolution
at the United Nations that would authorize NATO to use force ``in
or over Kosovo,'' the official said, a move intended in part to put
pressure on Russia to act more aggressively against its traditional
allies, the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the British are prepared to be out there themselves,''
a senior U.S. official said Sunday. ``I have the feeling they want
to be sure that we're out there.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Monday, the British will be host to a European Union foreign
ministers' meeting to press for the imposition of tough economic
sanctions _ especially an investment ban, as well as the more
symbolic freezing of Serbian assets abroad _ that were suspended at
Washington's request when Milosevic agreed to open talks with
Ibrahim Rugova, the leader of Kosovo's Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Those sanctions were never imposed, because Washington used
their suspension as an inducement to Milosevic to open the talks
with Rugova, even though just a week earlier Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright pressed U.S. allies to agree to them.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, too, is now ready to impose those sanctions and to
discuss new ones, U.S. officials said Sunday. They said Milosevic
had used the suspension of sanctions as an excuse to crack down in
Kosovo, embarrassing the Americans and making a further round of
talks with him impossible for Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans insist that dialogue _ together with the pressure
of new sanctions and the ultimate threat of NATO action _ is the
only avenue to a peaceful solution in Kosovo, and that it will
continue.
</P>
<P>
   But some officials, both American and European, fear that the
Milosevic crackdown may mean that any opportunity for a solution is
already lost, and that Rugova's credibility has already suffered
too much as the Kosovo Liberation Army gains strength.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Contact Group on the Balkans _ the United States,
Britain, Germany, Italy, France and Russia _ will meet on Wednesday
in Paris at the political director level, and could impose the
suspended sanctions, officials say. The group will meet at the
foreign ministers' level in London on Friday, along with Japan and
Canada, and there is a NATO defense ministers' meeting on Thursday
in Luxembourg, where Kosovo will be a prime topic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has already asked for military options and accelerated
planning for deployments around Kosovo to prevent a possible
regional conflagration. But the British, especially, feel that the
problem is within Kosovo, not around it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Pentagon has made it clear that it does not favor
any new troops to be sent to the Balkans, even as the U.S. forces
in Bosnia and Herzegovina are reduced.
</P>
<P>
   And a U.S. threat to Milosevic of a military response to a
crackdown in Kosovo _ a warning first issued by President George
Bush and repeated by the Clinton administration to Milosevic in
1993 _ remains ``on the table.'' But this threat is ``not now a
topic of real discussion,'' a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   One U.S. official said that in contrast to Bosnia, where
Washington let the war go on for three years before acting and
involving NATO, the United States has engaged much more rapidly in
Kosovo, even if not quickly enough to satisfy the British.
</P>
<P>
   The push for Milosevic-Rugova talks, backed by sanctions and
then backed by NATO action if the violence continues, is a strategy
that can work, the U.S. official insisted. But as with Bosnia, he
said, there is a great reluctance in the White House ``to move
further into the Balkans, rather than out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
