<SLUG> BC-ONECONOMICS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS WOMEN ARE MORE GENEROUS THAN MEN, AFTER ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN MARSHALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
No less an authority than Charles Darwin once claimed that women
differ from men in their ``greater tenderness and less
selfishness.'' But today, such observations are politically
incorrect, open to charges of sexism.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The claim also is empirically suspect. Psychologists and
economists who have devised experiments to test generosity,
altruism and cooperation often have found that women don't live up
to their stereotype and appear to be less generous or cooperative
than men.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical experiment, each subject gets a chit worth a
dollar. The subjects then are given a chance to donate it into a
common pool. Any chits they keep remain worth a dollar. But those
in the pool become worth two dollars and then are divided equally
among all the subjects.
</P>
<P>
   If subjects were trusting and cooperative, they would donate
everything to the pool and double their money. But individuals have
an incentive to hold back their chits because they will share the
pool regardless of whether they contribute. Of course, if no one
donates to the pool, everyone ends up worse off. (This incentive to
shirk is why governments tax their citizens rather than relying on
voluntary contributions to fund public programs.)
</P>
<P>
   In one such experiment reported in 1993, men proved much more
cooperative than women. In the first round of the game, for
example, men donated 94 percent of their holdings into the common
pool. Female subjects, on the other hand, donated only 72 percent
of their chits.
</P>
<P>
   But now it turns out that Darwin, and the conventional wisdom,
may have been right all along. New findings by economists Catherine
Eckel at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and Philip Grossman at the
University of Texas restore the reputation of women as the more
generous sex.
</P>
<P>
   In a new paper published in Economic Journal, they point out the
flaw in previous research: The experiments all involved strategy.
In other words, they measured not just innate generosity or
cooperation, but how subjects guessed others would behave in turn.
Strategy games, where the payoff depends on interactions between
subjects, all involve risk, a contaminating factor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``There is a lot of evidence that suggests men are more
risk-loving than women,'' Grossman said. ``They engage in more
illegal drugs, unsafe sex and riskier recreational activity.'' The
different behavior of men and women in strategy games may reflect
their different responses to risk, not their natural level of
generosity.
</P>
<P>
   So Eckel and Grossman devised the simplest of all experiments,
called a Dictator game because one subject alone determines the
outcome. They gave each college-student subject $10 and invited him
or her to share the money with an anonymous partner. A selfish
subject would keep all the money; a generous one would split the
windfall more evenly.
</P>
<P>
   The results vindicated Darwin: Women, on average, donated twice
as much as men to their unseen partners. The average donation from
women was $1.60, versus 82 cents for men.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few subjects could be termed generous: 47 percent of
women and 60 percent of men didn't hand over a dime. Most others
gave only a dollar or two. Maybe that reflects the fact that most
subjects were students studying topics such as economics and
accounting.
</P>
<P>
   EL NINO MOVES MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   El Nino is one powerful baby. Besides shutting off the rain in
Australia and Southeast Asia, flooding Peru and sending exotic fish
up the coast of California, El Nino usually also manages to jolt
world commodity markets.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the naughty child has surprised economists:
Commodity prices are down, not up, despite predictions of global
climate disruption. Experts say the disruption of Asia's economies
has cut world commodity demand faster than El Nino could cut
commodity supplies.
</P>
<P>
   By upsetting traditional weather patterns, El Nino can disrupt
agricultural harvests, sending crop prices soaring. It also can
crimp the output of mines by flooding access roads, washing out
ports or drying out water sources used for hydraulic excavations.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when scientists began predicting one of the largest
El Nino events in history, Federal Reserve Board economist Allan
Brunner started asking how it might affect commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent paper surveying data back to 1964, Brunner confirms
that El Nino does wield power over the economy as well as the
weather. A modest El Nino, he found, pushes up overall commodity
prices by 4 percent; a big one like that of 1982-83 boosted
commodity prices 30 to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond mere commodities, Brunner reports, the ebb and flow
of El Nino can account for 10 to 15 percent of variation in world
price inflation and world economic output.
</P>
<P>
   In the infamous El Nino of 1982-83, for example, droughts in
Asia and Australia sharply increased grain prices. The disruption
of fisheries off South America fueled the nudge up in soybean
prices because fish meal is a substitute in some markets for
soymeal. And copper prices rose following floods in Chile, which
halted production in the mines.
</P>
<P>
   The latest El Nino also has hammered crops in Australia and
fisheries off Latin America, but the overall effect on commodity
prices appears to be subdued. Indeed, the International Monetary
Fund's non-oil commodity price index has fallen 15 percent in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Brunner said one reason is that by some geophysical measures,
this year's El Nino is actually much less severe than that of
1982-83. Another reason is that food prices have been on a downward
trend since peaking three years ago, when a variety of natural
disasters temporarily slashed world food stocks. Finally, and most
important, Asia's economic crisis has dampened demand for all sorts
of commodities, softening prices across the board.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS AND ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that a strong economy can drive up the stock
market, but sometimes cause and effect are reversed. Lately, the
buoyant U.S. stock market helped the economy to boom, even in the
face of the crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market influences the health of the economy through
the ``wealth effect.'' When stock prices are high and households
feel confident, they are more prone to spend, particularly on
big-ticket items like houses, cars and appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Second, higher stock prices help families meet their savings
objectives faster. Because people don't need to sock away as much
money for college or retirement, they spend more money, fueling an
economic surge.
</P>
<P>
   A recent analysis by Goldman Sachs economist Ed McKelvey notes
that the value of stocks held by Americans soared to 143 percent of
gross domestic product by the end of last year, from 80 percent
three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increase in this ratio is more than double the
next-biggest rise over any three consecutive years in the postwar
era,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   The gains also are probably more widely shared than ever. The
latest available survey, taken in 1995, found that 41 percent of
households owned equities or equity mutual funds, up from 32
percent in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   McKelvey estimates that the rise in stock prices spurred enough
new consumer spending and investment to contribute an extra
percentage point to GDP growth over each of the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   One downside is that as people consume more, they save less of
their income. Last year, the personal savings rate fell to the
lowest level in 57 years, McKelvey reports. In the long run, the
economy needs domestic savings to fund new investment.
</P>
<P>
   But even people with no stock market holdings have benefited
from the recent surge in economic growth. Real wages are growing,
and the unemployment rate is at its lowest point in nearly three
decades. Just keep your fingers crossed that the market doesn't
tumble and take the economy down with it.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Marshall can be reached by e-mail at
marshall &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
