<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-BIRD-CALLERS-AR     06-07 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BIRD-CALLERS-ART-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PROUD AND LOUD RITE IS TAKING FLIGHT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A color photo of a bird calling contestant is being sent
to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase
by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bb) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ Ali Loeb seemed to be having some kind of
seizure. Arms flailing, knees buckling, she staggered across a
stage at this Bay Area town's high school emitting a shriek so
bone-rattling it sounded like a summons for paramedics. But all it
drew were gales of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Erdem Kiciman appeared to be choking. One hand clutching his
throat, he coughed and heaved and heaved and coughed in a manner
that suggested the urgent need for the Heimlich maneuver, or at
least a potent expectorant. But all he got were thunderclaps of
applause.
</P>
<P>
   What in the world was possessing Miss Loeb, a Harvard-bound
senior, Kiciman, a strapping sophomore on the water polo team, and
dozens of other scholars and athletes who turned Piedmont High
School's auditorium into a cacophony of wailing and whistling,
chest-thumping and cheek-thwacking? And why were the 600 people in
the audience reacting with such unalarmed delight?
</P>
<P>
   Because it was all for the birds, and a proud, peculiar
tradition was taking flight again.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the claim to fame of Piedmont, an affluent
community of about 10,500 residents nestled next to Oakland, had
been the high school's annual bird-calling contest, in which the
college-destined sons of physicians and daughters of lawyers took a
frivolous pause from more relevant endeavors to imitate the calls
of the wild.
</P>
<P>
   They made like macaws and emulated egrets, and the feistiest
migrated south to Burbank to appear on Johnny Carson's ``The
Tonight Show.'' But three years ago, after the death of the science
teacher who had started the competition, the din lapsed into
silence.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it screeched back, thanks principally to the hard
work and high ideals of two seniors, Mandy Gruber and Sara
Thierman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the skills you learn through bird-calling cannot be
learned in the classroom,'' said Miss Gruber, who will attend Brown
University in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Which skills might those be?
</P>
<P>
   Miss Gruber's answer was more like a question. ``Poise?'' she
said. ``Self-confidence?''
</P>
<P>
   She and Miss Thierman, who is headed to Yale University, honed
those attributes not only by coordinating the reborn contest, which
took place Sunday afternoon, but also by invoking the babble of the
pileated woodpecker, which they selected with careful thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some squeaking at the end, which is amusing,'' Miss
Gruber explained. ``Also, neither of us can whistle, so that cut
out a lot of birds.''
</P>
<P>
   They failed to finish in the top 3 of 12 acts, most of them duos
or trios, so they may not get to appear on ``The Late Show with
David Letterman,'' which has agreed to feature the most spirited
contestants on June 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you go wrong with birdcalls?'' said Rob Burnett, the
Letterman show's executive producer. ``It's the definition of money
in the bank, as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   The contest originated in 1964 with Leonard J. Waxdeck, who was
looking for a way to get his students excited about the natural
world.
</P>
<P>
   Although Waxdeck was a marine biologist by training, he thought
the skies afforded more easily replicated theater than the seas.
``You couldn't do too much with fish,'' Jean Waxdeck, his widow,
said in an interview on Thursday. ``They make a splash, but that's
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first years, he held the competition in his classroom.
But the crowds that filled the hallway suggested a wider appeal, so
the contest was moved to the auditorium and opened to all students
at the school. In 1974, it caught the attention of Carson, who made
it famous.
</P>
<P>
   Waxdeck found himself recognized on the street when vacationing
in Europe. Professional athletes from the Bay Area, local disk
jockeys and even Charles Schulz, the creator of ``Peanuts,'' came
to judge, evaluating the authenticity of all the warbling, clucking
and cooing by hunch as much as anything else.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To produce these sounds, students selected and studied any of
more than 400 possibilities from an aural library that Waxdeck and
Dale Porter, another science teacher, compiled. The tortured squawk
of a tufted puffin was a favorite. ``It's kind of like a big
burp,'' Porter explained.
</P>
<P>
   This year, students presented their offerings, from whooping
cranes to kookaburras, as the codas to skits that incorporated
information about the birds' habits and habitats.
</P>
<P>
   Two young women adopted the singsong cadences of characters from
the movie ``Fargo'' to play Minnesota tourists in Hollywood who spy
a bird from their home state as they ogle the actor Patrick Swayze
through binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, ya!'' one of them said. ``That's definitely a greater
prairie chicken. It's got that great big chicken thing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   They placed second, just ahead of Miss Loeb and her partner, who
impersonated the Manx shearwater, a raucous denizen of California's
coastline. Kiciman, who wore a pink tutu and plastic beak for his
fling as a flamingo, did not win.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors and a bag of birdseed went to two young men who
introduced the tremulous vibrato of the willow ptarmigan, common in
Alaska, with a song that equated its lovely ``plumage'' with its
``va-va-voom-age.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Loeb's father, Michael, shook his head at the end. ``One
thing's for sure,'' he said of his daughter, ``nothing will ever
embarrass her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
