<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8237 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELDERLY-CARE-ART-1     06-07 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-CARE-ART-1,000(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 GAP IN LONG-TERM CARE COVERAGE FOR ELDERLY SEEN AS GROWING THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A consumer's guide to long-term care for the elderly is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927. A photo is
being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 212-556-1243 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Janice Davocato's devotion to her disabled mother
has wiped out her savings and turned her into a seven-day-a-week
workhorse.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Sylvia Davocato, was taking care of her own mother
in 1986 when she fell in her South Philadelphia rowhouse and badly
broke a leg. She ended up with severe gangrene and a near-fatal
blood infection. When she left the hospital, it was in a
wheelchair, with a catheter. She is still in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years, despite some help from the state, paying for her
76-year-old mother's care at home has largely fallen to Janice, a
40-year-old office manager: $80 a day for a private nurse for two
months when her mother came home, then $50 a day _ $75 on weekends
_ for an aide ever since. With free-lance typing jobs on the
weekends, she earns about $32,000 a year, of which about $11,000
goes for her mother's care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had $30,000 saved from all my years of working,'' she said.
``That's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   As Americans continue to live longer than ever, some elderly
people and their families are being caught in the gap between the
cost of long-term care, necessities ranging from private aides to
diapers, and the limited amount of government aid to pay for it.
And as the baby boomers age over the next 30 years and the over-85
population grows particularly fast, the need for such care will
only escalate, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Families Pay 40 Percent of Health Care Burden
</P>
<P>
   Already, about 6.5 million people, nearly a fifth of the
population 65 years and older, require assistance and about 22
million families _ nearly one in four _ are providing some form of
assistance to an older relative or friend.
</P>
<P>
   For all the attention on the problems in Social Security, the
federal pension program, or Medicare, the federal health insurance
program for the elderly, many experts say that the gap in long-term
care coverage poses the most immediate and often most devastating
threat to the financial security of older Americans and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nearly $91 billion spent on long-term care and nursing
homes in 1995, the elderly and their families paid almost 40
percent, double the proportion paid out of pocket for that year's
overall health spending of $991 billion, according to the Health
Care Financing Administration.
</P>
<P>
   But little is being done about the gap, in part because of its
sheer size. Policy-makers fear an overwhelming demand for services
from families that are now caring for elderly relatives themselves
at no cost to the government.
</P>
<P>
   There are precedents: While Medicaid is thought of as a federal
health insurance program for the poor, it also pays nursing homes
for the cost of caring for residents who have exhausted their
savings; in 1995, 68 percent of Medicaid's total spending on the
elderly went to nursing homes. And since Medicare, the federal
health insurance for the elderly, began providing some home-care
benefits, spending on them grew to $18.3 billion in 1996 from $3.8
billion in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians worry that if they make it a benefit it will get
overused, and everyone will use it,'' said Diane Rowland, executive
vice president of Henry Kaiser Family Foundation, a national health
care philanthropic organization. ``The other side of the coin is
that many families will continue to endure, and will only use
outside services when they need them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress' dirty little secret is Medicaid,'' said Sen. John
Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., one of the few members of Congress
pressing the long-term care issue. ``When someone says, `Oh, you
don't provide for longtime care, we say, `Yes, we do, you just
spend down and go into Medicaid.' But at what price?''
</P>
<P>
   `There Are Times I'm So Tired I Could Cry'
</P>
<P>
   With few answers coming from Washington, adult children whose
parents aren't ill enough for a nursing home or who are determined
to keep their parents at home, improvise and struggle along as best
they can, their fortunes altered by the facts of old age and
disability.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Lynn Mokos, a care manager for the Pennsylvania Area Agency
for Aging, which provides home care assistance, has heard hundreds
of stories like that of the Davocatos. She works with 80 families
in Bucks County, outside Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Middle-class people, educated people, can believe that `those'
people _ whoever `those' people are _ have enough money to care for
themselves,'' Ms. Mokos said. ``They have no idea how easily this
could happen to any one of us. It could be them. `Those' people
includes you and me. It's us.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day at lunchtime, Linda Stumm, a 46-year-old mother of two
teen-age sons, leaves her job as an elementary school secretary and
goes home to change her mother's diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stumm's mother, Lena Pimpinella, 78, was diagnosed with
Alzheimer's disease 13 years ago. Unable to speak, or to eat or to
move without help, she spends her days on a hospital bed in the
living room of her daughter's rowhouse in South Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stumm does not consider a nursing home an acceptable option
for her mother, but she says she does not know how much longer her
energy will hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times I'm so tired I could just cry,'' she said one
afternoon as she fed her mother yogurt with a spoon. ``Child care
eventually evolves to less and less. There's no end to this. You
know you're going to be changing diapers all the time. It's always
the same. It just gets worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial implications are immense. If there does exist a
nursing home that could provide her mother with the proper love,
dignity and care, Mrs. Stumm said, it is surely not one she could
afford. Nursing homes providing basic care can easily cost $40,000
a year, and nearly two out of three families end up relying on
welfare _ Medicaid _ to pay the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stumm does receive substantial help from the state to help
care for her mother at home, but she bears most of the caregiving
burden herself. And the toll is high.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the early stages of her mother's disease, Mrs. Stumm stayed
home from work for two years to provide the constant care that was
needed. Then she gave up her former position as a legal secretary,
and went back to work as a $15,000-a-year school secretary _ half
the salary of her old job _ because it allowed her flexibility to
care for her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Now, her elder son, Greg Jr., a 16-year-old honors student,
wants to go to the University of Pennsylvania. Mrs. Stumm and her
husband, Greg Sr., 47, a laid-off welder retraining as a public
schools building engineer, say they don't know how they will afford
any college.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Stumm's mother, nearly two-thirds of the disabled
elderly live at home or with relatives. But even while Pennsylvania
and other states are shifting money toward home care, nearly
two-thirds of public spending for long-term care for the elderly
still goes to nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Pennsylvania, which has a greater percentage of
residents over age 60 than any state but Florida, spent $2.3
billion on nursing home care, and $184 million on home and
community-based care for the elderly, with most of that smaller
amount coming from the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of people who are getting older, and the number of
people in late life who are living longer, is growing faster than
the lottery is,'' said the Pennsylvania secretary of aging, Richard
Browdie. ``I wish I could say to you that we would be able to serve
everyone who needs it. But there's not enough money to do it for
everybody. It's a national problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people with a disabled elderly relative face painful
options. Some make the choice of placing a parent in a nursing
home, despite its lack of privacy, often minimal care, and high
cost. Others, like Linda Stumm and Janice Davocato, keep their
relatives at home by piecing together assistance from the state _
if they qualify for it _ from private aides they pay for
themselves, and from their own labor.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia and Janice Davocoto live together in a rowhouse in South
Philadelphia. Mrs. Davocato, who was a housewife, has no savings,
and meager Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Janice Davocato would not consider a nursing home, ``not for my
mother.'' For the past seven years, Philadelphia Corp. on Aging, a
nonprofit group that serves the elderly in the Philadelphia region,
has provided her mother with an aide five days a week, for three
hours a day. Ms. Davocoto, who hires a private aide to cover the
remaining hours in the day and weekends, says the help from the
state has reduced her costs by about $18 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That took a great burden off me,'' she said. ``I'm blessed to
get as many hours as I do. There's people who can't get anything.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been so demoralized by watching her mother suffer and by
her own difficulties in getting help that she says, only
half-joking, that she has developed a plan should she become
disabled in old age: ``I'm going to go right off the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time, not so long ago, when Fedele Capozzi, 85,
could not have imagined turning to the government for help. He was
earning good money as a real estate appraiser. He and his wife,
Elvira, who is 83, had a home on one of the most beautiful blocks
in South Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Vail, Paris, Italy,'' Capozzi said. ``If my wife
wanted new drapes, I'd say, `Put 'em in.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, five years ago, Mrs. Capozzi was diagnosed with
Alzheimer's disease. Her memory went. She became incontinent. She
refused to walk up the stairs of the house where they had lived for
57 years.
</P>
<P>
   Capozzi sold the house and moved them into an apartment. He
hired aides, at $8 an hour, to bathe his wife, dress her, change
her diapers and help him with cooking and cleaning. The cost:
$30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, after going through his savings, Capozzi became
eligible for help from the state. Philadelphia Corp. on Aging
assigned him an aide for six hours a day. Capozzi still spends $380
a week on a private aide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you why they give me this help,'' he said one
morning while his wife, who no longer recognizes him, was eating a
breakfast of cereal and fresh strawberries that he had prepared for
her. ``They're smart, in a dumb way. If my wife was sent to a
nursing home, it would cost the state $46,000 a year. The state is
saving money, giving me 42 hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   And Capozzi is right if he feels caught in the middle. ``It is
the middle class that gets squeezed the most,'' said Raymond
Coward, a gerontologist and dean of health and human services at
the University of New Hampshire. The wealthy can afford to buy the
care they need, he said, and the poor qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   And it is likely to stay that way, many experts say, as long as
the issue is not addressed on a national level, because of its
potential cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every serious proposal for long-term care basically comes down
to spending more money, either publicly or privately,'' said Joshua
Wiener, a health policy analyst with the Urban Institute in
Washington. ``And that's not a popular position right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The market has come up with private long-term care insurance.
But many experts say that its high cost makes it an answer only for
the affluent. The average annual premium for policies covering four
years of nursing home and home care in 1995 was $1,124 if bought at
age 50, $2,560 if bought at age 65, and $8,146 a year if bought at
age 75, according to the Health Insurance Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Ferraro, 77, recently received a postcard from a company
warning of the ``devastating'' financial consequences of nursing
homes _ and pitching long-term care insurance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Ferraro, who also lives in Philadelphia, has already gone
through much of her savings taking care of her husband, Joe, who
was paralyzed by a stroke seven years ago and who died last month
at age 79. She is still caring for a 90-year-old aunt, who also had
a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely that any company would sell Mrs. Ferraro
insurance. She has had double bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Ruth, 61, could never afford long-term care insurance,
either. She has gone through most of her savings to care for her
85-year-old mother, Catherine Ruth, who suffered a stroke three
years ago and is paralyzed and bedridden at home.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare, and the state, provide Ms. Ruth with some home care
assistance. But it is not nearly enough. Two years ago, Ms. Ruth, a
licensed practical nurse, quit her $14.60-an-hour job so she could
care for her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ruth's care manager is Jo Lynn Mokos. ``This woman is
absolutely and totally devoted to her mother,'' Ms. Mokos said.
``She will die before she will put her mother in a nursing home.
She says, `What is going to happen to me when I get old?' We can't
tell her, `You're going to be OK.'
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll end up in a nursing home _ where she won't put her
mother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
