<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8241 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-ECON-ART-580(3TA     06-07 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-ECON-ART-580(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA FEELS STRAIN MOST AT SOCIETY'S MARGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Bangon Phailak is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(lb) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAN WAN YAI, Thailand _ Sitting on the ground beside her hut,
Bangon Phailak chopped up wild plants for lunch and pondered a
wrenching question.
</P>
<P>
   What does her 4-year-old daughter need more, food or a mother?
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bangon, a gentle woman whose soft face is framed by thick
black hair, explained that the family cannot afford both. As a
result of the Asian financial crisis, her husband has lost his job
as a construction worker, so the family earns only a trickle of
cash through odd jobs in this tiny village in northeast Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   That money can be used to buy rice and milk for the little girl,
Saiyamon, who has become anemic and malnourished. Or Mrs. Bangon
can try to save the tattered small-denomination bills to pay for a
stomach operation that she needs to save her own life.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Mrs. Bangon has chosen to spend the money on Saiyamon.
She herself has already lived for 32 years and, she reasons, what
would be the point of preserving a mother at the cost of a child?
</P>
<P>
   Seen up close in villages, the Asian financial crisis is not a
conundrum of currency pegs and credit crunches and various
imponderables. In households like Mrs. Bangon's, it is as immediate
as a typhoon, and rather more deadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, at least we had enough rice,'' Mrs. Bangon said
softly. ``These days, we don't even have enough to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 11 months since the crisis exploded in Thailand and began
spreading through the region, the most prominent victims have been
the humbled tycoons in the big cities, and they have indeed fallen
farthest. But they are neither the most common victims nor the most
desperate. The worst off are those like Mrs. Bangon, who were
already at the margins of society _ those who had almost nothing
before and who now, somehow, have even less.
</P>
<P>
   A lag in the data means that there are few statistics so far on
the social impact of the crisis. Most evidence of the human cost is
anecdotal, gleaned from travels through remote areas in Asia and
from the findings of rural clinics and aid workers like field
representatives of the relief group Oxfam. They report that many
Indonesian mothers can no longer afford milk, which has tripled in
price, and are giving their babies tea.
</P>
<P>
   The picture that emerges suggests increases in death rates,
school dropouts, and malnutrition. Some experts say that the legacy
of the crisis will be felt long after the region's economies are
purring again.
</P>
<P>
   ``When children are malnourished before they are 5 years old,
the impact on their intelligence is permanent,'' said Dr. Anugerah
Pekerti, chairman of World Vision Indonesia, an aid organization.
``When you combine the two factors we're now seeing _ malnutrition
and its impact on IQ, and also children dropping out of primary
school _ the impact will be quite devastating 10 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia has always had many poor areas and hungry children, so the
problems are not new. But they have been hugely magnified. On the
eve of the crisis, Indonesia had about 20 million people who lived
below the poverty line, getting by with a per capita income of less
than $1 a day. Now World Bank officials suggest that the number of
people below this poverty line may surge to 40 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   For those 40 million, and for the tens of millions more who live
in similar deprivation in countries like Thailand, Vietnam and
Burma, the poverty does not necessarily just mean living more
simply. In extreme cases, it means living not at all.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Ill
</P>
<P>
   Many Prayers, But No Medicine
</P>
<P>
   In the Thai hillside village of Pasingh, near the border with
Laos, Som Chianda is the heavily tattooed patriarch of a family
living in a dark brown wooden house. Each day, Som and his wife
pray at the Buddhist altar on one side of the living room for a son
who is quietly dying on the other side of the room.
</P>
<P>
   The son, Lamkwan, 32, is a casualty of the Asian financial
crisis, for the devaluation of the Thai currency has left his
family unable to afford the medicine that he needs to keep him
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Lamkwan suffers from a severe lung ailment, but his doctors
prescribed a medicine that for three years kept the sickness in
check. The medicine was expensive, $50 a month, but the family
could afford it with the money sent home by Lamkwan's two brothers
working as laborers in Bangkok, the Thai capital 300 miles to the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Then in October, the crisis in Thailand worsened. The cost of
the medicine soared to $120 a month, and the two brothers lost
their jobs and stopped sending money. So the parents stopped giving
Lamkwan his medicine, and he began to deteriorate quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day he gets worse,'' said his mother, Sanguan Chianda,
as he looked on placidly a few feet away. ``Mentally, he's going
downhill, because he's thinking too much about it. And then someday
he won't be able to eat any more, and then he'll lose his strength.
And then he'll be finished.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The heaviest feeling in the world is to have no money, to be
unable to continue his medicine,'' she said. ``The helplessness is
overwhelming. We can't help our own son. We can just sit and watch
him get worse day by day.''
</P>
<P>
   The end, she said, will probably come later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lamkwan is one data point in a health-care crisis that is
brewing across Asia because of the financial crisis. Medicine in
the region is often imported, and thus sometimes doubled or even
quadrupled in price when local currencies tumbled against the
dollar. A result, according to rural doctors and social workers, is
that people are dying who would normally be saved.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, children are dropping out of schools, which play an
important role in monitoring their health by arranging check-ups,
vaccinations and referrals to doctors. The schools also teach basic
practices like hand-washing and cultivate a more educated
population that in the long run will be more conscious of hygiene
and will be crucial to sustaining Asia's industrial revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Data on school drop-outs are scarce, but in Thailand officials
say that an unpublished government survey of school enrollment
indicates that 40,000 to 50,000 first-graders have dropped out of
the school system this year alone. That amounts to 4 percent of all
first-graders, and with other survey information it suggests that
the number of elementary school drop-outs in Thailand may have
almost tripled.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, the government warns that 8 million elementary and
junior high school students may drop out this year, compared with
2.8 million in a normal year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, governments in countries like Indonesia and
Thailand have had to cut spending, and a result in some cases has
been an end to school lunches and cutbacks for public-health
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have village hygiene organizations and
public-health representatives in the village, but now we've had to
cut all that back,'' said Chitana Saribut, a 28-year-old nurse at a
rural clinic in northeast Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Chitana said the budget of the clinic had been cut 30
percent, even as the cost of medicines soared. As a result, the
clinic is out of penicillin, fever medicine and other essentials.
</P>
<P>
   ``When patients come to us,'' she said, ``we often have nothing
to give them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thirsty
</P>
<P>
   Splinters on Menu Because of Drought
</P>
<P>
   Sickness and death are closely linked to malnutrition, and the
spreading hunger is readily visible in places like the little
village clearing in Indonesia where Wilhelmina Boemao was preparing
her dinner behind her thatch-roof hut. On the menu that night:
boiled wood.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Boemao, a tall, good-natured woman living in West Timor,
Indonesia, is being forced by hunger to eat putak, the wood of a
kind of palm tree that grows wild. She chops up the putak and boils
it into splinters that taste as unpalatable as they sound, or else
she grinds it into what she calls flour, but it is actually
sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   The economic crisis has coincided with crippling droughts caused
by El Nino currents. So rain has not fallen and crops have failed,
particularly in eastern Indonesia. With no rice and corn, villagers
are turning in desperation to anything edible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past I used putak to feed pigs, and even they didn't
like it,'' Miss Boemao said. ``I never ate putak. My grandmother
used to talk about eating it in hard times, and my mother may have
eaten it once or twice, but in my lifetime, never.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in normal times, the drought would be a calamity, but it is
doubly so in the middle of an economic crisis. First, families have
less cash income to buy food, because prices have gone up and
because people have lost their jobs. Second, Indonesia's
government, absorbed by financial problems and political upheaval,
has not been able to help the villagers, and will be hard-pressed
to import grain to cover the shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the boom years, 39 percent of Indonesia's children
were malnourished, according to World Bank figures, along with 45
percent of Vietnamese children. Most experts expect those figures
to increase, but such numbers are a bit unreal because it is
impossible to tabulate accurate health statistics for peasants who
are so poor that they cannot afford to go to a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   In remote villages of West Timor, it is easy to see children who
display the thin limbs and light, patchy hair that are signs of
malnutrition; such children are visible everywhere except in the
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rarely see people suffering from severe malnutrition,''
said Dr. Joyce Manek, director of a little hospital in the city of
Soe. ``Because if they can't afford food, then they can't afford to
come to a hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, doctors at two remote clinics said that the number of
their patients had fallen by up to half. The doctors explained that
families now use any bit of cash to buy food, so they no longer can
afford to pay a consultation fee that is the equivalent of 5 cents
in U.S. currency.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Migrants
</P>
<P>
   Hunger, Hiding and Brutal Police
</P>
<P>
   It is not just poverty that keeps people from going to doctors,
but also fear. Among the most desperate people in Asia these days
are the migrant workers who are hiding from police crackdowns
aiming to send them home to their native countries.
</P>
<P>
   On the edge of Bangkok, a gravel road tapers into dirt and then
nothingness. At first the area seems a deserted swamp, but at dusk
it comes alive with hundreds of Burmese laborers hiding from the
police in hovels and half-constructed buildings. One of them is
Adahm, a 20-year-old construction worker wearing a rubber sandal on
his left foot but none on his right foot, his sarong knotted
tightly around his waist.
</P>
<P>
   Adahm said his wife was five months pregnant. She has not seen a
doctor, and he is agonizing about what to do. Should he take her to
a clinic and risk being turned in to the police and deported, or
should he keep her hidden in his hut and risk her death and the
baby's?
</P>
<P>
   Asia has several million migrants like Adahm who travel to
wealthier countries without passports, savings or local language
skills, simply hoping that they will somehow get jobs and save
money and ensure a better life for their children. They have been
the worst-hit victims of surging unemployment throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Some 22,000 people have lost their jobs in Asia each day so far
this year, and many more layoffs are expected. With jobs
disappearing, foreign migrants have become natural scapegoats. So
each country is cracking down on migrants and trying to ship them
home: Singapore is sending home the Malaysians, the Malaysians are
sending home the Thais and Indonesians, and the Thais are sending
home the Burmese.
</P>
<P>
   The growing resentment against foreigners is leading to
increasing reports of abuse. Indonesians accuse the Malaysian
police of clubbing and torturing them before deporting them, while
in Thailand the Burmese say that they are being cheated by
employers and robbed by the police.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked at three construction sites where I was never paid at
all,'' Adahm said. In all, he said, he was owed the equivalent of
more than $1,000, but construction bosses simply laughed at him,
knowing that if he complained, they could have him arrested and
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The migrants say that the possibility of arrest evokes special
horror because the police frequently steal a family's entire
savings and abuse people as they wish. Maung Moe and Ko Soe Win,
two Burmese men who were detained in Thailand earlier this year,
assert in a written statement prepared with the help of aid workers
that the police routinely beat the Burmese men in their detention
center and raped the women.
</P>
<P>
   Each evening, they say, the Thai police raped a young Burmese
woman in front of her mother. Finally, the daughter and mother
threw a piece of plastic twine over a bar above the toilet in their
cell and committed suicide together by hanging themselves from
opposite ends of the single length of twine.
</P>
<P>
   The Safety Net
</P>
<P>
   Where Foragers and Lenders Live
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the deprivation caused by the crisis, the situation
is not uniformly bleak. Some people are dying or suffering greatly,
but Asia is a more complex and varied canvas than a focus solely on
the victims would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside the most wretched there are also many poor people like
Bulu Kadi. Kadi, a 55-year-old peasant with a head of unkempt hair
and a machete tucked under his belt, is lean and hungry but still
not remotely worried that he will ever starve.
</P>
<P>
   Kadi and his neighbors in Puumawo, a village on the small
Indonesian island of Sumba, are running out of food, and the
village is so remote that the government will never manage to send
relief. To get to Kadi's house, one must hike for a couple of miles
through the muddy rice paddies from the nearest gravel road, then
wade across a creek, and finally balance on a log that is the only
bridge over a river.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as Kadi recounts how he manages to get by, the conversation
underscores the two safety nets that have protected Asia from far
worse suffering. Most countries in Asia do not have the kind of
safety net popular in the West _ unemployment insurance, welfare
system, food stamps _ but nonetheless there are two cushions to
soften the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The first is the strong mutual support system that links people
together. The second is the natural bounty of the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tradition here is that if people don't have food, they can
borrow from their neighbors,'' said Kadi. ``If you borrow one sack
of rice, you have to pay back two sacks. People always help each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Kadi's thatch-roof hut is in its own world outside the cash
economy. But he has borrowed two sacks of rice from a nephew, and
this traditional system of lending rice on 100 percent interest
rates has created a crude but effective banking system that rescues
the needy and encourages savings.
</P>
<P>
   Asian society is urbanizing and becoming looser-knit, but most
laid-off workers still have relatives in a village somewhere _ a
place that they call home and to which they can return at any time.
</P>
<P>
   The tropical climate and abundance of the land offer a second
kind of safety net. The putak that the villagers are eating in
Timor may not be tasty, but it is edible. Two doctors said that the
wood can be a source of carbohydrates _ a poor source, but enough
to keep people alive.
</P>
<P>
   In short, these two safety nets offer a rare bit of consolation
that however bad things are, they could be much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Kadi and his neighbors are supplementing their diet with
grasshoppers, wild potatoes, wild pumpkins, leaves and a root
called wee-ah. Peasants normally avoid wee-ah because it must be
repeatedly boiled and soaked or else it gives anyone who eats it a
severe rash, but in a pinch there is enough wee-ah around to tide
people through almost any food shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere one goes in Asia, it seems people are cutting their
food expenses by resorting to nature. In her roadside home in a
rural area of northern Thailand, Maesubin Sisoipha bounced her
3-year-old granddaughter on her knee and nibbled on a breakfast
that did not cost anything at all: fried beetles served with mango
leaves and rice and fish paste.
</P>
<P>
   ``We catch the beetles ourselves,'' Mrs. Maesubin said. ``The
mango leaves we pick from a tree. The rice we grow ourselves. And
we make the fish paste from fish we catch in the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Maesubin said her two sons, laid off from their jobs in
Bangkok, are returning soon to the village. But she does not
anticipate any problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll have to stay in this house, but it'll be no problem to
feed the extra mouths,'' she said. ``We'll just have to look for
more beetles for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
