<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGIC-MAIN08-COX     06-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGIC-MAIN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Midnight Magic
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- They don't call former basketball star Earvin Johnson
``Magic'' for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   He's won five NBA championship rings. He's silenced critics who
said his movie theaters in Atlanta, Houston and Los Angeles would
bomb. He's even beaten oddsmakers who predicted he'd be dead by
now, nearly seven years after announcing he has the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   But if Johnson hopes to slam dunk his new syndicated late-night
talk show, ``The Magic Hour,'' which debuts at midnight on WAGA, he
might need a new nickname.
</P>
<P>
   How about ``Miracle''?
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't put the time and effort that I need to put into the
show, I will fall _ and fall fast,'' Johnson has said.
</P>
<P>
   At least give the guy points for honesty. Johnson knows that it
will take more than his mile-wide grin and slick ``show time''
moves for his show to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magic Hour'' is the latest celebrity-driven talker in the
late-night sweepstakes, a woeful lottery littered with the battered
egos of those who've failed: Chevy Chase, Dennis Miller, Whoopi
Goldberg, Lauren Hutton, Pat Sajak, Rick ``Disco Duck'' Dees and,
most recently, Keenen Ivory Wayans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've watched those shows and we've learned a lot,'' says
Geovanni Brewer, one of the producers of ``The Magic Hour.'' ``We
don't plan on making those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Wayans' canceled show and Sinbad's barely breathing
``Vibe,'' which targets younger, urban and minority viewers, ``The
Magic Hour'' wants an audience that's more mainstream. Johnson is
shooting for the same crowd that watched his late-night idol,
Johnny Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson's no Carson, the show's producers scrapped the
traditional opening monologue. Instead, the rookie host will get an
assist from sidekick Craig Shoemaker, a little-known stand-up comic
who'll do ``bits'' with Johnson at the top of the show.
</P>
<P>
   Other comedians have been hired to perform pre-taped sketches,
some including Johnson as various characters.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing a gimmick from Carol Burnett's long-running variety
show and banking on Johnson's ``aw shucks'' charm, he'll also do an
unrehearsed Q&AMP;A segment with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer says no subject will be off-limits and that Johnson
expects questions about the sexual recklessness that almost cost
him his career _ and his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody wants to ask him about that, he won't be shy to
respond, but it's not that type of show,'' she says. ``This is
going to be purely entertainment, a feel-good show.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, however, won't be grilling his opening week guests, who
include Harrison Ford and Peta Wilson on Tuesday; Arsenio Hall,
Gloria Estefan and Michael Douglas on Wednesday; Christine Lahti
and Kenny G on Thursday; and Gillian Anderson and Johnson's former
basketball coach, Pat Riley, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The show's house band will be fronted by Sheila E., a move
Johnson's spin doctors are touting _ incorrectly _ as a late night
first. (Wayans had an ``all-girl'' band. It still didn't help).
</P>
<P>
   Sheila E., a former Prince protege and daughter of rock pioneer
Peter ``Coke'' Escovedo, is one of the world's best percussionists.
She'll be joined by her brother Peter, also an accomplished
musician.
</P>
<P>
   As added insurance in Atlanta, ``The Magic Hour'' should get a
boost from its late-night lead-in: the highly rated ``Jerry
Springer Show,'' which airs at 11.
</P>
<P>
   A legendary stickler for preparation when he was playing
basketball, Johnson has spent months doing rehearsal shows and
taking lessons from a voice and interviewing coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax and make a space, like it's your home,'' Johnson said
recently about the cozy ambience his handlers want him to create on
the set.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is also getting pointers from Jay Leno, against whom his
show competes in several key markets, and Hall, a buddy and former
gabmaster.
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds great on paper. But late-night talk shows don't
exist on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey Steele, senior vice president for Zenith Media, a New
York consulting firm, was impressed by Johnson during a
presentation he made to promote the show to advertisers. But Steele
voiced doubts that the show will last beyond its initial 13-week
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very charismatic and sweet and likable, and he's turned
his adversity into a higher level of celebrity,'' Steele says.
``All of that is good for initial audience curiosity, but the show
itself will have to be even better (than other late-night shows) if
it's going to last.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the show is an air ball or a swish will be up to the man
who has been pulling surprises out of his bag of tricks for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, when the Lakers blew it, Magic blew it,'' Johnson
says. ``That's what went along with the title of being a leader.
With this show I just think we're going to be a winner. I feel
we're going to be a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
