<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With virus controlled, NBA retiree staying busy
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Almost seven years ago, Magic Johnson faced a battery
of cameras and announced his retirement from the NBA ``because of
the HIV virus I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Today he is remarkably robust by any definition of good health,
thanks to drugs that have been so successful that they have reduced
the virus to levels that cannot be detected. His wife and three
children are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's new TV show, ``The Magic Hour,'' is just one aspect of
a busy life:
</P>
<P>
   HIS HEALTH: While by no means cured, he owes the appearance of
remarkable health to a Spartan lifestyle and modern medicine. Like
many AIDS patients on these new medications, he takes a combination
of three drugs, one a protease inhibitor. Side effects can include
nausea, vomiting, headaches, backaches or gastrointestinal
problems. The drugs are expensive, costing $12,000 to $15,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   HIS MOVIE THEATERS: He's a partner in a joint venture with Sony
Theaters in Los Angeles, Houston and Atlanta, with expansion plans
for nine more cities. In Atlanta, where he already has one
multiplex theater at Greenbriar Mall, the financing plans for a
second one, in south DeKalb County, drew criticism because of
concerns that public money would be used. But the plan, which was
approved by the DeKalb County Commission and will be implemented
through the DeKalb County Development Authority, provides financing
and interest rate incentives and uses funds from private investors.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER BUSINESS INTERESTS: Johnson recently became Starbucks'
first joint-venture partner, with a location in Los Angeles. He has
a joint venture with TGI Friday's, with plans to open restaurants
near his theaters. He also has formed California Urban Investment
Partners with the California Public Employees' Retirement System,
investing in commercial real estate. And he represents American
Express and Adolph Coors in TV ads. Recently, he joined Janet
Jackson and record industry executive Jheryl Busby in buying a
majority stake in Founders National Bank, California's only African
American-owned bank.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980607.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOMAR-COX     06-07 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOMAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This is Nomar's World
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Pizza is a rather simple food to eat. Just pick it
up, take a bite and chew.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't work for Nomar Garciaparra of the Boston Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   When Garciaparra was at Georgia Tech, he had a special way of
eating his pie. He would cut out the inside of a slice of pizza,
because he figured it was the hottest. He didn't want to burn his
mouth, you see.
</P>
<P>
   Quirky? No doubt about it. But that's Garciaparra, whose methods
sometimes border on paranoia and whose meticulous routine is one of
the reasons he has become one of the best shortstops in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember he came in for our team banquet (this year), and
his buddies wanted to come out from California to see him,'' said
Danny Hall, who coached Garciaparra for one year at Tech. ``He told
them, `You guys can come out, but you can't change my routine.' He
likes things in order. He is one of those guys who has tremendous
concentration and stays with a routine day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who plays here tonight against the Braves in the
first of a three-game interleague series, changes nothing. He wore
the same cap all three years at Tech. He listens to the same music
on the way to the ballpark and takes the same route every day. When
he dresses, it's right sock, left sock, right sanitary sock, left
sanitary sock, right stirrup and so on. When he is at the plate, he
tugs on his batting gloves between pitches, taps his spikes in the
dirt. In the field, he will remove his glove, spit on his hands and
put the glove back on as the pitcher begins his windup. He wears
the same underwear _ ``He's got a pair with about two strands
left,'' said teammate Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Call it superstitious; call it a little nutty. Garciaparra calls
it ``a game of routines,'' adding, ``I have my routines, just like
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But while this may seem eccentric, it has made Garciaparra the
player he is today. He ran away with American League rookie of the
year honors last year after one of the best power seasons ever for
a shortstop. Garciaparra hit .278 with 30 homers and 96 RBIs.
Despite missing 17 games with a shoulder injury this year, he's
hitting .278 with seven homers and 35 RBIs. With seemingly endless
range, his defense can be magnificent. He rarely ever blows a
routine play.
</P>
<P>
   And Garciaparra, 24, has turned the rather caustic baseball city
of Boston giddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to learn the game and be a great player,'' Red Sox
general manager Dan Duquette said. ``(Ted) Williams was obsessive
in the way he approached the game. Yaz (Carl Yastrzemski) was.
(Jim) Rice was. Cal Ripken's the same way. There is comfort in
routine. There's a saying that practice doesn't make perfect, but
perfect practice makes perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be no more valuable shortstop in baseball. While Ken
Griffey Jr., Mark McGwire and Juan Gonzalez typically are named as
the game's best players, consider how important Garciaparra is to
his club: When he missed 17 games in May, the Red Sox were 7-10.
With Garciaparra in the lineup, Boston is 27-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's lived up to the expectations and then some,''
said Red Sox teammate Darren Bragg, who played with Garciaparra at
Tech. ``I think by the time he's done he could probably be one of
the best who has ever played, not just for the Red Sox, for all of
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Garciaparra prefers to keep a low profile. When
time allows, he will grant interviews, but he keeps his answers
short and to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``No questions about statistics,'' he said before an interview.
``I don't like them. They don't tell the whole story.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he is questioned: ``I'm not better than anyone else,
and I don't think anybody's better than me. It's all opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   He also prefers not to talk about his new-found power. When he
arrived on the Georgia Tech campus in 1991, he weighed around 140
pounds. At 6-foot, 180 today, he's still not large by baseball
standards. But his strength comes from the weight room, where his
routines are relentless.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he pairs strength with remarkable baseball instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his junior year we went to play Florida State, and we were
facing Paul Wilson (the No. 1 overall pick by the Mets in the 1994
draft),'' Hall said. ``The Mets were out there to watch Wilson
pitch, and he was throwing 95 mph. He decided to start game with
slider, and Nomar hit the ball out. You can't fool him.''
</P>
<P>
   And there is a strong competitive heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at Wichita State for the regionals (1994), and we had
to play twice on the championship day,'' Hall said. ``It was over
100 degrees out there, and Nomar totally dehydrated himself in the
first game. He was taken to the hospital to get (fluids replaced),
and we ended up starting (the second game) without him. I'm
thinking, 'We don't have our shortstop; we don't have our leadoff
hitter.' He then comes back and says to me, 'I'm ready to go.' I
pinch-hit him for Mike Sorrow, and he hits the first pitch out of
the park. I was coaching third base, and the home-plate umpire
looks at me and says, `I can't believe what I'm seeing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hall was recently at the College World Series when the coach at
Southern Maine approached him and told him a story about
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me his two sons idolize Nomar,'' Hall said. ``He said
he was down in Fort Myers (where the Red Sox train) and had gone
over to visit the Red Sox spring training camp. A few minutes after
they are there, Nomar is playing catch with his oldest son. This
year, they go down to a game at Fenway, and the Red Sox are coming
off from the field from batting practice. Nomar looks and sees his
oldest son and yells, 'Hey, I know you.' He has only met this kid
once, and he starts talking to him.''
</P>
<P>
   After Garciaparra left the field, the coach's youngest son
looked at his older brother and said: ``Wow, you know Nomar?''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be long before everyone knows Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-07-98 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
