<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980607.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-07 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODWILL-GAMES-COX     06-07 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODWILL-GAMES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. Last Friday I asked my 8th-graders to close
their books (Saroyan's, The Human Comedy) and define the word
(ITAL)dignity(END ITAL). For a long few seconds, nothing happened.
Then Johnny went for a dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dignity,'' he read as he stood in front of the class making
like an orator of old (being the class ham), ``bearing, conduct, or
speech indicative of self-respect. Nobility or elevation of
character.'' Satisfied with his performance, Johnny sat.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen puzzled faces focused on me, waiting for the other shoe
to drop. They've come to expect a method to my apparent madness.
``Who has some?'' I ask as I swivel my chair for emphasis. No
takers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Ellen asks the obvious: ``Some what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dignity. How many of you respect yourselves?'' Brows knit in
obvious concentration, but no one answers. I wait for them to mull
it over. I know that if one of them takes the initiative, the
others will follow. Fourteen is an insecure age.
</P>
<P>
   After what seems an eternity, Jenny tentatively raises her hand.
``Sometimes I think I have some,'' she begins, apparently uneasy
with being the first to speak, ``but then something wrecks it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some(ITAL)thing(END ITAL),'' I ask, ``or some(ITAL)body(END
ITAL)?''
</P>
<P>
   While Jenny's thinking that one over, Bobby picks up: ``Parents
wreck our dignity. The other night I was helping my dad rototill
the garden and I messed up. He called me stupid. That hurts a kid's
self-respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy agrees. ``My sister calls me stupid all of the time, but
that doesn't bother me because I know she hates me. But parents
shouldn't call their kids names. They're supposed to love us. All's
I know is (I cringe but now's not the time for a grammar lesson)
I'm never going to call my kids ``dumb'' or ``stupid'' because it
really hurts our feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Patty wants into the discussion. ``Kids wreck each other's
self-respect. We call each other names all of the time.'' I nod,
recalling voices I've heard in the hall raised in less than praise.
``Stupid!'' ``Faggot!'' ``Pervert!'' are three of their favorites.
Worst of all, many of the kids who use them aren't even sure of the
meaning of the truly tasteless terms they're mouthing. A few days
earlier I'd hauled Benny and Art into my room for just such a
display.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you call Art a faggot?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he acts stupid,'' he grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faggot is a derogatory term for a homosexual. Are you offended
because Art is gay?'' Art choked and denied any such proclivities.
Benny had the decency to blush and admit that wasn't what he meant
at all. He said he had been annoyed because Art had been paying
attention to Susie in study hall and she was Benny's girlfriend. I
asked if calling Art a faggot in this case, might not have been a
contradiction in terms.
</P>
<P>
   Benny scrutinized his shoe-tops and admitted, ``Yeah, I guess.''
I ask him what he might have said to Art instead of calling him a
name. He was stumped for an answer. Art asked Benny why he didn't
just come up and ask him if he was out to steal his girlfriend.
Says if he had, he would have explained that his sister wanted him
to ask Susie if she was going to be riding the bus home that
afternoon so she could return some gym shorts she'd borrowed from
her. Benny still studied his Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do others have to respect us before we can respect
ourselves?'' I ask of no one in particular. Quite a few say yes,
and that if others don't treat them well they feel really down on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you don't respect yourselves first, how is anyone else
going to do it for you?'' I ask. Teddy wants to know why he should
respect himself. That's the opening I was looking for. I direct my
questions to the entire class, asking them not to answer aloud, but
just to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you earn your own grades or do you sit for a quiz with the
answers written all over your sneakers?'' A couple of giggles. They
think teachers don't notice stuff like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you tell the truth, even when it means you'll have to pay
the consequences? Do you compliment instead of criticize? Do you
encourage rather than belittle? Do you listen more often than you
talk? Do you avoid gossip? Do you dress like you're proud of
yourself? Do you choose friends for ``quality'' rather than for
``cool''? and do you more often think about what you can do for
that friend rather than what he or she can do for you?''
</P>
<P>
   They're looking a bit bored, and I'm beginning to think maybe
I'm whistling in the wind - again. Saved by the bell.
</P>
<P>
   But as they storm out the door, Sandy slows down long enough to
add a postscript: ``It just hurts more when grown-ups call us dumb
and stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Shame on us.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
