<SLUG> BC-BBO-PIAZZA-MARTINEZ-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA BRISTLES AT MARTINEZ'S BRUSHBACK WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Forget about giving Mike Piazza a bat and Pedro
Martinez a baseball to settle their continuing dispute about
Martinez's inside fastball that plunked Piazza in the left hand on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Just rent out Madison Square Garden, hand each player a
microphone and let Vince McMahon be the promoter. This verbal
skirmish about whether Martinez intended to hit Piazza has all the
earmarks of professional wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   The fierce animosity between Piazza and Martinez escalated
Sunday after Piazza, the Mets' catcher, chastised Martinez, the Red
Sox pitcher, for lacking decorum in uttering two expletives in
reference to him in an interview for Sunday's Boston Herald. A
perturbed Martinez countered by insisting that he has more class
than Piazza, who comes from a wealthy background.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's pretty funny that all the money in the world
can't buy you class,'' said Piazza, swiping at Martinez's $75
million contract. ``I don't think there's any excuse for that
language in the paper. He should invest in lessons in etiquette.
It's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez fired back with words as biting as one of his chin-high
fastballs and made reference to Piazza's perennially hefty bank
account.
</P>
<P>
   ``What class is he talking about?'' Martinez asked. ``He wants
to talk about class? Well, he was a millionaire since he was a kid.
But I can tell you the fans can't say anything bad about me. What
class? Education? School? What? He's not a better person than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who has been out of the lineup since suffering the
bruised hand and was not scheduled to start Sunday night, accused
Martinez of trying to obscure the fact that he cursed in an
interview to be published in a paper that children might read.
Martinez agreed that expletives are not proper language for
publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ridiculous for him to make this into a background
thing,'' said Piazza, whose father, Vince, is a millionaire
entrepreneur, and who turned down a contract from the Dodgers in
excess of $80 million. ``I'm not better than him. I just think he
should have more manners on language in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine that Piazza and Martinez were teammates
with the Dodgers for part of 1992 and all of 1993. After Martinez
hit Piazza with a 2-2 pitch and first base open in the first inning
on Friday, Piazza intimated strongly that he had been a target.
</P>
<P>
   The innuendo bothered Martinez, who is notorious for throwing
inside at hitters and does not dispute the reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The Herald did not actually print the language that Martinez
used. But the paper made it clear he used expletives and quoted
Martinez as saying: ``You can put that in the paper. I could care
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that prompted an angry response from Piazza. Standing
in the cramped clubhouse at Fenway Park before Sunday night's game
against the Red Sox, Piazza speculated that Martinez's sensitivity
about the subject might be evidence that he had thrown at him on
purpose. Keeping with the World Wrestling Federation theme, Piazza
even challenged Martinez to journey the 200 yards across Fenway to
locate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's got a problem with me, he knows where to find me,''
said Piazza. ``It's unfortunate. I prefer to work these matters out
in private.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a lawyer seizing an opening in the courtroom, Martinez
pounced on Piazza's challenging remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does he want me to do? Go and fight him? Go throw
punches?'' Martinez asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not me. That's where I have my class.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite the mutual hostility, Piazza and Martinez both said they
did not have previous problems with each other. Both said they had
few encounters off the field when they were teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have nothing to say about Piazza,'' Martinez said. ``I love
his dad. His dad is my friend. If he wants to talk about me hitting
him, that's why I said what I said. I don't need to have Michael
thinking I hit him on purpose. Come on. Give me a break. Michael
knows me better than anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez conceded he has thrown at hitters, but only after one
of his teammates, as Piazza used to be, was already hit.
Essentially, that is what Piazza was hinting at on Friday, even
though no Red Sox were hit and it was the first game of the season
between the New York and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody hits one of my players, I'm not afraid to hit
anybody,'' Martinez said. ``I'm one of the best in the last three
years at hitting people. What is he talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was surprised that Martinez used profanities and
surprised that Martinez sounded so defensive Sunday. The catcher
then tweaked Martinez a final time before the two players and the
two teams part for the rest of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' Piazza said, ``he didn't get the fruit basket I
sent him for Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH:
</P>
<P>
   The Mets think that Hideo Nomo might have been tipping off his
forkball this season and also think he should slow down his
corkscrew delivery because he was working too quickly. But Dave
Wallace, a senior adviser to the club who used to be Nomo's
pitching coach with the Dodgers, said he did not have concerns
about Nomo's debut on Tuesday against Tampa Bay at Shea Stadium.
``It wasn't like anything was way out of whack,'' Wallace said. ...
Mike Piazza said Manager Bobby Valentine told him to rest his
bruised left hand for one more day. ``It's still sore,'' Piazza
said. ``There's no need to push it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
