<HEADLINE>
BULLS PLAY MIND GAMES AGAINST MALONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Chicago Bulls are still trying to fool with Karl
Malone's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Scottie Pippen whispered to Malone before Malone
went to the free-throw line in Game 1 of the NBA finals, ``The
Mailman doesn't deliver on Sundays.'' Malone missed the two free
throws, setting up Michael Jordan's game-winning shot.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, after Game 2 of this year's finals, Dennis Rodman
said shutting down Malone was no problem, ``if the referees let me
play my game.'' He went on to say of Malone: ``He's effective when
he can get around guys who are stagnant, like Luc Longley. He can't
do that to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when asked if Rodman's defense was the reason he had
made just 14-of-41 shots in Games 1 and 2, Malone just rolled his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman might get the same response from NBC executives after his
remarks when he exited the Delta Center in Salt Lake City on Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to come back here for Game 6,'' Rodman said.
``Because NBC wants its money. They need the money. Without the
Chicago Bulls, they're nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen did not agree. As he was leaving the Delta Center on
Friday night, he boasted to the national cable television channel
CNN-SI: ``We're not coming back. Get ready for the WNBA season.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's remarks after Chicago's 93-88 victory in Game 2 alluded
to Utah's entry in the Women's National Basketball Association, the
Starzz, who begin their season on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams in Demand
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams is watching the labor situation between the
owners and the players more closely than most veteran power
forwards are. An invaluable rebounder for the New Jersey Nets, who
nearly partied himself out of the National Basketball Association
four years ago, Williams is one of the hottest commodities on the
free agent market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm giving the Nets the first crack, and hopefully we can get
it done, but after that everything's fair game,'' he said before
Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is working for a variety of news outlets, doing his own
offbeat commentary on the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBA.com, NBA Jam, anything you can think of,'' he said.
``Funny, huh? They didn't want me around a few years ago. Now I'm
working for the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches Aren't Complaining
</P>
<P>
   One of the subplots swirling about the Bulls' seven-game series
with the Indiana Pacers was the tug-of-war Phil Jackson and Larry
Bird were playing with the officials' ears. One day it was Bird
contending that Scottie Pippen was getting away with hammering Mark
Jackson on defense. The next day it was Jackson railing on the
referees for their lack of ``courage'' in making calls on the
Pacers in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   And now ... not a peep. Although there have been some
questionable calls, neither Jackson nor Jazz Coach Jerry Sloan has
made the officiating of this series an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to fight them as hard as I can on the sideline,''
Sloan said before Game 3 Sunday night. ``But when the game is over,
it's over. It makes no sense to hear all that stuff once it's
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal Has a Doubter
</P>
<P>
   Paul Westphal is homing in on the vacant Seattle SuperSonics
coaching job, but he has apparently run into a huge hurdle: Gary
Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, the Sonics' All-Star guard, is unconvinced that
Westphal, a former Phoenix Suns coach, is the right man for the
job, according to a person close to Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle General Manager Wally Walker and Payton are expected to
meet on Tuesday to discuss the possibility of Westphal replacing
George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Silas, a Charlotte assistant who was a part of the Sonics'
lone championship team in 1979, interviewed for the position. Lenny
Wilkens was also said to be in the mix, but Atlanta Hawks General
Manager Pete Babcock said the Sonics have yet to ask permission to
speak with Wilkens, who coached the Sonics from 1977 to 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
