u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-     06-07 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/7/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- June 7, 1998 -- DEMS-FUNDRAISING, 6-7 --
Rep. Albert Wynn of Maryland, is one of several House Democrats who
may buck the party on the overhaul of campaign finance laws. The
three-term congressman is balancing his doubts against party
loyalty. ``I consider myself a team player,'' he says, ``and I've
voted for things when I wasn't enamored with the idea in the
interest of the team and may do the same thing here.'' (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PIEDMONT, Calif. -- June 7, 1998 -- CALIF-BIRD-CALLERS,
6-7 -- Erdem Kiciman, a Harvard-bound senior, wearing a pink tutu
and a plastic beak to impersonate a flamingo, in Piedmont High
School's bird-calling contest. The contest originated in 1964 with
Leonard Waxdeck, a science teacher at Piedmont, and a marine
biologist by training, who was looking for a way to get his
students excited about the natural world. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) PHILADELPHIA -- June 7, 1998 -- ELDERLY-CARE, 6-7 --
Janice Davocato's devotion to her disabled mother, Sylvia, 76, has
wiped out her savings and turned her into a seven-day-a-week
workhorse. Janice Davocato has been taking care of her mother, ever
since a fall left her in a wheelchair 12 years ago. Healthcare
costs have devoured Ms. Davocato's savings and now consume a third
of her income. ``I had $30,000 saved from all my years of
working,'' she says. ``That's gone.'' Mrs. Davocato, who was a
housewife, has no savings, and meager Social Security benefits.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WEST TIMOR, Indonesia -- June 7, 1998 -- ASIA-ECON-3, 6-7
-- With Asia's financial crisis comes hunger, malnutrition,
sickness and death. In West Timor, Wilhelmina Boemao, right,
prepares putak, the wood of a kind of palm tree that grows wild,
for eating. The economic crisis has coincided with crippling
droughts caused by El Nino currents. So rain has not fallen and
crops have failed, particularly in eastern Indonesia. With no rice
and corn, villagers are turning in desperation to anything edible.
``In the past I used putak to feed pigs, and even they didn't like
it,'' says Miss Boemao. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NY7) PASINGH, Thailand -- June 7, 1998 -- ASIA-ECON-2, 6-7 --
Devaluation of the Thai currency, has left Som Chianda and his wife
Sanguan, praying at a Budhist altar, unable to afford medicine for
their son, Lamkwan, 32, in rear. Lamkwan suffers from a severe lung
ailment, and doctors have prescribed a medicine that has kept the
sickness in check for three years. But the cost of the medecine has
soared from $50 to $120 a month, leaving them hopeless. ``The
heaviest feeling in the world is to have no money, to be unable to
help our own son,'' says Mrs. Chianda. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BAN WAN YAI, Thailand -- June 7, 1998 -- ASIA-ECON-1, 6-7
-- The Asian financial crisis is forcing Bangon Phailak to choose
between food for her 4-year-old daughter, Saiyamon, who has become
anemic and malnourished, and life-saving surgery for herself. In
the 11 months since the crisis exploded in Thailand and began
spreading through the region, the worst off are those like Mrs.
Bangon, who were already at the margins of society. ``A year ago,
at least we had enough rice,'' says Mrs. Bangon. ``These days, we
don't even have enough to eat.'' (Nicholas D. Kristoff/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MEXICO CITY -- June 7, 1998 -- MEXICO-LABOR, 6-7 --
Alejandra Barrales Magdaleno, 30, leader of Mexico's 2,000-member
flight attendants' union, during the vote on the Aeromexico accord
on Saturday. Ms. Barrales brought to a successful conclusion, the
first nationwide strike by one of the country's politically
independent unions, the National Workers Union, that formed a new
federation last year. ``This strike strengthened not just our union
but the entire workers' movement,'' Ms. Barrales told hundreds of
flight attendants about their new salary and benefits package.
(Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 7, 1998 -- SNOWMAIDEN-BALLET-REVIEW, 6-7
-- Nina Ananiashvili and Angel Corella, in the American Ballet
Theater production of ``The Snow Maiden,'' at the Metropolitan
Opera House. ``The Snow Maiden's'' plot is drawn from Aleksandr
Ostrovsky's ``Snegurochka'' (''The Snow Maiden''), an 1873 play
based on Slavic folk stories, with incidental music by Tchaikovsky.
Despite all of the lilting snow maidens, leaping reindeer and
cavorting villagers, it is an intimate story and romantic ballet.
(Nan Melville/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LONDON -- June 7, 1998 -- BAKER-INTERVIEW, 6-7 --
Nicholson Baker, an author of many reputations. Baker's latest
novel is ``The Everlasting Story of Nory,'' which describes the
relatively uneventful life of an imaginative 9-year-old American
girl spending a year in England. ``Every book I've written I've
tried to make very different from the one before,'' says Baker.
``I'd like to have all my books make the same point -- and it's
kind of a stupid point, really -- that a single human being can
think about a lot of different things. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 7, 1998 -- TV-NBC-SHAPIRO, 6-7 -- Neal
Shapiro, the executive producer of ``Dateline NBC,'' is expanding
the program to five nights a week. As its success has grown,
``Dateline'' has reshaped how entertainment executives view news
magazines. One main element of the success of ``Dateline'' has been
its willingness to drop everything and chase like a thundering herd
after whatever story is driving daily coverage. ``We do stories on
the things people are talking about,'' says Shapiro. ``The stories
that are in the public consciousness.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- June 7, 1998 -- HDTV-FCC, 6-7 -- Susan
Ness, commissioner of an FCC task force on high-definition
television. Ms. Ness is trying to ease the transition to HDTV by
helping TV stations build towers for digital antennas needed for
transmission. Twenty-six network-owned television stations in the
nation's 10 largest cities are scheduled to begin digital
broadcasting by Nov. 1, and almost every major manufacturer of
televisions plans to introduce HDTV sets by then. ``For competitive
reasons, some broadcasters might not want to say publicly that they
are having problems,'' says Ms. Ness. ``In those cases we can
help.'' (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
