<HEADER>
A8444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MUSICIAN-JOBS-2TAK     06-07 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MUSICIAN-JOBS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSICIAN ADAPTS TO DECLINE IN JOB OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By N.R. KLEINFIELD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a nod to the audience, Jeff Ausfahl got ready to
play. As gigs go, the crowd was awfully young. Appropriately, he
began with ``I'm Popeye the Sailor Man.''
</P>
<P>
   The hubbub of chatter stopped. As Ausfahl strummed his guitar,
the roisterous kindergartners at Public School 114 in the Bronx
lifted their faces in delight. Accompanying him were Brian Grice on
the drums and Sue Terry on the flute. Between songs, they taught
the rudiments of their instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's this made of?'' Ausfahl asked as he held his guitar
aloft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wood,'' chirped a boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right. Now how many strings does it have?''
</P>
<P>
   A girl guessed three, half the correct answer.
</P>
<P>
   The trio performed an Aesop fable set to music. They distributed
maracas for the children to shake along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a far cry from a real gig, huh?'' Ausfahl said as the
children filed out. ``Isn't the club date business great?''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ausfahl has played the guitar professionally for 25 years.
He is what is known as a club date musician, who primarily performs
at single engagements like weddings and private parties. A highly
malleable guitarist, he can play everything from dance to rock to
classical to merengue to polkas. He plays songs of contagious cheer
and songs with a lot of ache in them, though he no longer gets to
perform anywhere as much as he would like to. Such is the sharply
altered shape of the musician's life in a world more in thrall to
canned music than live.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Ausfahl, at 43, finds himself doing about 75 gigs a
year in front of schoolchildren, arranged through Music Outreach, a
nonprofit outfit that puts on music demonstrations in public
schools in New York. The audience is highly appreciative. He needs
the work.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an evolving decline in jobs for live musicians,
caught in the undertow of disc jockeys spinning CDs on much
improved sound systems and a more thrift-minded economy.
</P>
<P>
   Local 802, the New York chapter of the American Federation of
Musicians, to which Ausfahl belongs, says union club dates in the
city have tumbled to about 6,000 a year from as many as 15,000 15
years ago. The union reports that the bar mitzvah business and
lower-end weddings have been almost totally lost to DJs, who
generally cost a fraction of what a band does.
</P>
<P>
   Far fewer musicians find themselves able to play full time
anymore. Many teach. And it has become axiomatic among union
musicians that they must accept nonunion jobs to eat, a practice
the union tolerates.
</P>
<P>
   It is not strictly economics that has brought on this state of
affairs. Many people do not want to hear someone who sounds like
Bruce Springsteen or Elton John. They want Bruce Springsteen or
Elton John, even if he is coming out of a box.
</P>
<P>
   One can sometimes go to a $200-a-plate dinner today and be
entertained by a music system. Years ago, the size of the band was
a mark of the status of an event. The work was so copious that it
was hard to find enough musicians. Bands enlisted ``phantoms,''
nonplayers who simply held instruments to swell the size of the
band. Saxophone players were known to pick up violins and apply
soap to the bows so no sound would emerge as they ``played.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, musicians have come to feel like very expensive
bottles of wine, tasted less and less often.
</P>
<P>
   It was a languid Monday void of gigs, and Ausfahl was working on
the attic of the tidy Teaneck, N.J., house that he shares with his
wife, Janet, and a parakeet named Henry. Ausfahl is a sinewy,
genial man with longish hair and sharply chiseled features.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a wedding yesterday with just a flutist,'' he said
ruefully. ``We played just the ceremony. When we left, the DJ
started.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of DJs causes him to snort with indignation.
Brusquely, he said: ``It does bug me. It bugs a lot of people. I'm
not mad at anyone. I just want to make a living. You know, it
started out that the records were to sound like the bands. Then it
got to where the bands were supposed to sound like the records. Now
they just need the records.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Ausfahl played 250 to 300 club dates a year.
These days he is lucky to get 100, plus his school jobs. His single
biggest source of work is Lester Lanin Orchestras, the society band
group. ``I also work for his competitors,'' Ausfahl said. ``I have
to.''
</P>
<P>
   His year of greatest income was 1993, when he made about
$60,000. The next year, he earned less than half that, but lately
he has rebounded to about $40,000 a year. ``I had some 10 years or
so where I would be idle at most one or two Saturday nights,'' he
said. ``Now I'm idle 20 or more Saturdays.''
</P>
<P>
   He never imagined this constricted condition when he embarked on
his free-form career. He was born in Peoria, Ill., where his father
was a factory manager for Caterpillar, the tractor maker. Ausfahl
started guitar lessons when he was 10. At 13, he was playing in a
band at school sock hops. ``When you're young, you want to find
your self-worth somewhere,'' he said. ``I tried a bunch of things
and I was good at this.''
</P>
<P>
   He eventually received a degree from Berklee College of Music in
Boston, after several interruptions. For a spell, he played rock
music at bars and Holiday Inn lounges. For eight months in 1975, he
joined a band in Chicago called Even Steven. The musicians wore
silver satin suits and played soul music. One summer, he journeyed
to Virginia Beach and played military bases and wet T-shirt
contests.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, he drove from Boston to New York. He knew no one. He
thumbed through the Yellow Pages to ``Bands &AMP; Orchestras'' and
began dialing numbers. Some places hung up on him. Others invited
him in for a tryout. One contractor asked him if he was free
Saturday. He was free indefinitely. ``Put yourself down,'' the man
told him. ``You've got two weddings.'' He picked up a third later
the same week. Within a year, he was subbing in Broadway plays. He
felt good about his footloose choice of career.
</P>
<P>
   Ausfahl now regards himself as one of the car mechanics of the
music business, someone who can be relied on to do solid, reliable
work. ``The way my career turned out, I'm not George Benson,'' he
said. ``I'm not a star. But I can really play.''
</P>
<P>
   He has never recorded his own album, though he has been on a few
bootleg records. In the past, he appeared at many familiar New York
nightclubs like CBGB and the Bitter End, but he has forsaken that
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally not lucrative,'' he said. ``They think you should
work for a piece of the door because of the exposure and then their
guy counts the door and you never seem to get what you should.
You're better off staying in your basement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He went on: ``At Christmas time, company parties were insane
years ago. No more. I used to do a lot of industrial jobs _ IBM
sales conferences and stuff. They've all cut back.'' He performed
at a fair number of debutante balls, but they have dried up, too.
``The ones I do,'' he said, ``instead of a parade of girls, I see
six.'' Another nearly defunct source of steady work is songwriter
demos. These days they tend to be done on a computer in a home
studio.
</P>
<P>
   Work used to flow worldwide. ``Once I was playing a party north
of London,'' he recalled, ``and the bass player nudged me and
pointed out that there was the queen.'' Nowadays, he travels very
little.
</P>
<P>
   He considers himself hard-boiled about social trends, but he has
made adjustments. He had done some music teaching, but doesn't much
care for it. He took classical guitar lessons and has been picking
up more classical and jazz gigs at restaurants and parties.
``Instead of working with bands, I find myself playing solo
classical,'' he said. ``The trouble is, when you play solo dates,
you're living wallpaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Within reason, he'll take whatever comes along. He has a steady
Friday night gig at a university club, where he plays swing and
dance music and also sings. Once he played a divorce. A man was so
elated when his divorce papers were signed that he threw a party.
In exchange for a free checkup, he recorded a song written by his
dentist to be entered in a contest to anoint a state song for New
Jersey. (It lost.)
</P>
<P>
   He did a funeral in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn. In her will, a woman
specified that a Dixieland band was to play at her final
appearance. Ausfahl was among the musicians hired to fulfill her
wish. As the coffin was carried out of the church, they struck up
some slower Dixieland numbers like ``Just a Closer Walk With
Thee.'' A weeping woman came up to Ausfahl and sobbed, ``Mother
would have loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday parties pay about $200 (weekdays are about $170), and
if he leads the band, it's $100 more. There is a $10 bonus if he
lugs along his own amplifier, which he always does. When he plays
solo guitar in a restaurant, he has trouble getting more than $125.
A jazz club pays him no more than $50 to $75. In these days of
depleted jobs, fees can get insulting. Not long ago, Ausfahl
rebuffed an offer to play jazz in a prison in Albany for $80.
</P>
<P>
   He finds it hard to comprehend why more people do not insist on
live music. ``To me the difference between a record and live music
is night and day,'' he said. ``When you play in a band and it all
works right, it's like floating on a cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   The splendiferous Bedens Brook Club lies at the end of a curving
road in Skillman, N.J., on the outskirts of Princeton. On a recent
Thursday evening, the Princeton class of 1953 had gathered for a
reunion dinner and dance. Don Anderson, a grizzled, 67-year-old
band leader and piano player, had hired Ausfahl and three others to
provide the evening's entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The elder classmates moved peristaltically across the polished
floor, most of the men in their Princeton orange sport jackets. The
band members were in black tie. The bass player, Michael Battiston,
said, ``I feel like a piece of dirt in a glass of orange juice.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson spelled out his plan for the evening: ``We'll play some
stuff here. If nothing happens, we may assault them.'' ``Assault''
meant they would stroll from table to table and play.
</P>
<P>
   As the cocktail chatter proceeded, the band stayed with
background music, beginning with two Princeton songs. A woman
strutted over and asked Anderson to tone it down, it was hard to
talk over the music. ``Ah, they love us,'' Ausfahl said.
</P>
<P>
   He gazed at the crowd. ``We're talking people in their late
60s,'' he said. ``This seems to be what I get. I don't get the
young groups anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   On they played: ``East of the Sun,'' ``Anna,'' ``Blue Moon.''
Anderson sang, ``New York, New York,'' sounding not even like the
treasurer of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Ausfahl did a solo and a woman stopped by to coo: ``He can just
do that all night long. I'm going to take someone like you home
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson quickly handed her a business card. ``I don't want to
be pushy,'' he said, ``but this is what we have to do.'' When she
had gone, he mentioned, ``One year, in 1986, I grossed $400,000.
Now I can do maybe a tenth of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson strapped on his accordion and announced that they were
going to stroll.
</P>
<P>
   Ausfahl looked stricken. He abhors strolling. He is not much for
repartee with the audience. When you stroll, people get up to sing
_ often in unknown keys _ and won't sit down. One table requests a
popular song like ``Memory'' and then all the other tables request
it. You wind up playing it 25 times.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it was the same Princeton standard that everyone wanted:
``Going Back to Nassau Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   After dinner had been ingested, the band got heavy into dance
songs. The alchemy was just right, and they were clicking. The
reunion-goers rose from their chairs. Good drink had oiled
reluctant limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the evening waned, the floor was seething with dancers.
The musicians had smiles on their faces. By no means was Jeff
Ausfahl wallpaper tonight. He was making music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
